Angelo, Via Cinthia, I-80126 Napoli, Italy)"], "journal_name": "Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society", "volume": "446", "publication_year": "2015/01/1", "start_page": "683", "end_page": "704", "keywords": ["methods: data analysis", "galaxies: clusters: general", "galaxies: clusters: individual: A1689", "dark matter", "Astrophysics - Cosmology and Nongalactic Astrophysics"], "url": "https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2015MNRAS.446..683D", "abstract": "We examine Abell 1689 non-parametrically, combining strongly lensed Hubble Space Telescope images and weak distortions from wider field Subaru imaging. Our model incorporates member galaxies to improve the lens solution. By adding luminosity-scaled member galaxy deflections to our smooth grid, we can derive meaningful solutions with sufficient accuracy to permit the identification of our own strongly lensed images, so our model becomes self-consistent. We identify 11 new multiply lensed system candidates and clarify previously ambiguous cases, in the deepest optical and near-infrared data to date from Hubble and Subaru. Our improved spatial resolution brings up new features not seen when the weak and strong lensing effects are used separately, including clumps and filamentary dark matter around the main halo. Our treatment means we can obtain an objective mass ratio between the cluster and galaxy components. We find a typical mass-to-light ratios of M/L<SUB>B</SUB> = 21 \u00b1 14 inside the r < 1 arcmin region. Our model independence means we can objectively evaluate the competitiveness of stacking cluster lenses for defining the geometric lensing-distance-redshift relation in a model-independent way.", Moro 2, I-00185 Rome, Italy</div>\r\n    </div>\r\n\r\n    <div class=\"info-card-search-label\">\r\n        Search for other works by this author on:\r\n    </div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"info-card-search info-card-search-internal\">\r\n    <a href=\"/mnras/search-results?f_Authors=L.+Izzo\">Oxford Academic</a>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n    <div class=\"info-card-search info-card-search-google\">\r\n        <a href=\"http://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=author:%22Izzo L.%22\">Google Scholar</a>\r\n    </div>\r\n    <div class=\"info-card-search info-card-search-ads\">\r\n        <a href=\"http://adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/nph-abs_connect?return_req=no_params&amp;author=Izzo,L\">ADS</a>\r\n    </div>\r\n</div>                                    </span>\r\n                                </span>\r\n                                <span class=\"al-author-name-more js-flyout-wrap\">\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n                                    <a class=\"linked-name js-linked-name-trigger\" href=\"javascript:;\">G. </div>\r\n</div>\r\n<input id=\"hfEnableOupOnlineProductsFeatures\" name=\"hfEnableOupOnlineProductsFeatures\" type=\"hidden\" value=\"False\" />\r\n\r\n<input id=\"routename\" name=\"RouteName\"   <div class=\"widget widget-ArticleFulltext widget-instance-OUP_Article_FullText_Widget\">\r\n        <div class=\"module-widget\">\r\n    <div class=\"widget-items\" data-widgetname=\"ArticleFulltext\">\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n                    <h2 scrollto-destination=21026294 id=\"21026294\" class=\"abstract-title js-splitscreen-abstract-title\" >Abstract</h2>\r\n<section class=\"abstract\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">We examine Abell 1689 non-parametrically, combining strongly lensed <em>Hubble Space Telescope</em> images and weak distortions from wider field Subaru imaging. Our model incorporates member galaxies to improve the lens solution. By adding luminosity-scaled member galaxy deflections to our smooth grid, we can derive meaningful solutions with sufficient accuracy to permit the identification of our own strongly lensed images, so our model becomes self-consistent. We identify 11 new multiply lensed system candidates and clarify previously ambiguous cases, in the deepest optical and near-infrared data to date from <em>Hubble</em> and Subaru. Our improved spatial resolution brings up new features not seen when the weak and strong lensing effects are used separately, including clumps and filamentary dark matter around the main halo. Our treatment means we can obtain an objective mass ratio between the cluster and galaxy components. We find a typical mass-to-light ratios of <em>M</em>/<em>L</em><sub><em>B</em></sub>\u00a0=\u00a021\u00a0\u00b1\u00a014 inside the <em>r</em>\u00a0&lt;\u00a01 arcmin region. Our model independence means we can objectively evaluate the competitiveness of stacking cluster lenses for defining the geometric lensing\u2013distance\u2013redshift relation in a model-independent way.</p></section>                        <div class=\"article-metadata-panel clearfix at-ArticleMetadata\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"kwd-group\"><a class=\"kwd-part kwd-main\" href=\"javascript:;\" data-keyword=\"&quot;methods: data analysis&quot;\">methods: data analysis</a>, <a class=\"kwd-part kwd-main\" href=\"javascript:;\" data-keyword=\"&quot;galaxies: clusters: general&quot;\">galaxies: clusters: general</a>, <a class=\"kwd-part kwd-main\" href=\"javascript:;\" data-keyword=\"&quot;galaxies: clusters: individual: A1689&quot;\">galaxies: clusters: individual: A1689</a>, <a class=\"kwd-part kwd-main\" href=\"javascript:;\" data-keyword=\"&quot;dark matter&quot;\">dark matter</a></div>                    <h2 scrollto-destination=21026296 id=\"21026296\" class=\"section-title js-splitscreen-section-title\" data-legacy-id=sec1>1 INTRODUCTION</h2>\r\n<p class=\"chapter-para\"><em>Hubble Space Telescope</em> (<em>HST</em>) imaging of the galaxy cluster Abell 1689 (A1689) has revealed an exceptional number of strongly lensed multiply imaged galaxies, including high-redshift candidates. Previous studies have used these data to obtain the most detailed dark matter (DM) reconstructions of any galaxy cluster to date, based on parametric methods and resolving substructures \u223c25\u00a0kpc across. A fuller exploration of non-parametric cluster lensing is increasingly motivated by new dedicated deep <em>Hubble</em> imaging surveys, with the aim of examining DM structures in the least biased way. Multiple sets of lensed images are now typically identified in deep, high-resolution images of any cosmologically distant cluster imaged with <em>Hubble</em> (with the exception of the CLASH cluster RXJ1532.8+3021; Merten et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib35\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib35\" data-open=\"bib35\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2014</a>), allowing systematic exploration of the cluster DM and discovery of the most distant galaxies (Broadhurst et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib7\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib7\" data-open=\"bib7\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005b</a>; Clowe et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib10\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib10\" data-open=\"bib10\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2006</a>; Zitrin et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib52\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib52\" data-open=\"bib52\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2009</a>, <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib53\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib53\" data-open=\"bib53\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2010</a>, <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib54\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib54\" data-open=\"bib54\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2011</a>; Coe et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib11\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib11\" data-open=\"bib11\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2010</a>, <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib12\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib12\" data-open=\"bib12\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2012</a>, <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib13\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib13\" data-open=\"bib13\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2013</a>; Zheng et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib51\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib51\" data-open=\"bib51\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2012</a>). In practice, secure identification of multiple images need the guidance of a reasonably accurate lens model as even the counterimages of large arcs are typically hard to find given the complexities in the central mass distribution of clusters, so that images for a given source are far from symmetrically located.</p><p class=\"chapter-para\">Furthermore, due to the uncertain redshifts of faint lensed images, even when a reliable mass model can be built, counterimages are predicted to fall on long, largely radial loci or may fail to be generated at all if the unknown source distance is insufficient. This means that there are often several contending counterimages unless internal colours and morphology are sufficiently distinctive. Photometric redshifts, if unambiguous, are very helpful in selecting counterimages that are too faint for spectroscopy. The 16 overlapping broad-bands of the CLASH programme (Postman et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib42\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib42\" data-open=\"bib42\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2012</a>) covering from the UV to the near-infrared (NIR), maximizes the photometric redshift accuracy possible with <em>Hubble</em> and have provided reliable examples of the most distant galaxies known, as in the case of the <em>z</em> \u2243 11 candidate lensed by MACS0647 (Coe et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib13\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib13\" data-open=\"bib13\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2013</a>), where multiple images are identified both photometrically and geometrically.</p><p class=\"chapter-para\">To date, the galaxy cluster A1689 remains the best studied cosmic lens with hundreds of magnified images in the central region visible in deep <em>Hubble</em> images (Broadhurst et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib7\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib7\" data-open=\"bib7\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005b</a>). Over a hundred of these arcs have been matched to their corresponding background galaxies by several authors and their redshifts estimated (Broadhurst et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib7\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib7\" data-open=\"bib7\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005b</a>; Halkola, Seitz &amp; Pannella <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib20\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib20\" data-open=\"bib20\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2006</a>; Limousin et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib31\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib31\" data-open=\"bib31\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2007</a>; Coe et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib11\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib11\" data-open=\"bib11\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2010</a>), including several of the brightest highest redshift galaxies known, extending to <em>z</em> \u2243 7.6 (Frye, Broadhurst &amp; Ben\u00edtez <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib17\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib17\" data-open=\"bib17\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2002</a>; Frye et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib18\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib18\" data-open=\"bib18\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2007</a>, <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib19\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib19\" data-open=\"bib19\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2012</a>; Bradley et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib4\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib4\" data-open=\"bib4\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2008</a>). The relaxed appearance of this cluster and the relatively undisturbed optical and X-ray morphology have made A1689 a preferred target for constraining the equilibrium mass profile by several independent means (Lemze et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib27\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib27\" data-open=\"bib27\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2008</a>; Sereno et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib46\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib46\" data-open=\"bib46\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2013</a>).</p><p class=\"chapter-para\">Several studies have reconstructed the mass distribution using the strong lensing (SL) data alone (Broadhurst et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib7\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib7\" data-open=\"bib7\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005b</a>; Diego et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib15\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib15\" data-open=\"bib15\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005b</a>; Halkola et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib20\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib20\" data-open=\"bib20\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2006</a>; Jullo &amp; Kneib <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib22\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib22\" data-open=\"bib22\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2009</a>; Coe et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib11\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib11\" data-open=\"bib11\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2010</a>) and in combination with weak lensing (or WL hereafter) measurements (Broadhurst et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib6\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib6\" data-open=\"bib6\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005a</a>; Limousin et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib31\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib31\" data-open=\"bib31\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2007</a>; Umetsu &amp; Broadhurst <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib48\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib48\" data-open=\"bib48\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2008</a>) including the use of background red galaxies whose surface density is depleted by lens magnification and independent observationally from WL shear. A1689 has been studied also using higher order derivatives of the lensing potential, like the flexion, (see Leonard, King &amp; Goldberg <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib30\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib30\" data-open=\"bib30\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2011</a>, for a recent analysis). The mass profile of A1689 was shown to be very well fitted by the standard Navarro, Frenk and White (NFW) profile describing the equilibrium mass distribution expected for collisionless, cold dark matter (CDM; Broadhurst et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib6\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib6\" data-open=\"bib6\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005a</a>,<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib7\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib7\" data-open=\"bib7\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">b</a>) but with a concentration that is surprisingly high. Triaxiality of the mass distribution has been explored as a mean to boost the projected concentrations, and certainly may be expected to be partially responsible (Oguri et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib38\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib38\" data-open=\"bib38\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005</a>; Broadhurst &amp; Barkana <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib5\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib5\" data-open=\"bib5\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2008</a>; Sereno et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib46\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib46\" data-open=\"bib46\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2013</a>).</p><p class=\"chapter-para\">A1689 has been subsequently followed at other wavelengths, allowing lensing to be combined with SZ and X-ray data (Sereno et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib46\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib46\" data-open=\"bib46\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2013</a>) and also with the dynamics of member galaxy motions via the Jeans equation and via velocity caustics (Lemze et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib28\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib28\" data-open=\"bib28\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2009</a>). Multiwavelength science opens the door to new exciting studies since it is no longer sufficient to model the DM mass or gas separately but instead both have to be integrated in the same model in order to explain the observations. Previous work on A1689 combines <em>HST</em> and <em>Chandra</em> and reveals some tension between hydrostatic+lensing reconstruction and other observations (Zekser et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib50\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib50\" data-open=\"bib50\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2006</a>; Leonard et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib29\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib29\" data-open=\"bib29\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2007</a>; Lemze et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib27\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib27\" data-open=\"bib27\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2008</a>; Umetsu &amp; Broadhurst <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib48\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib48\" data-open=\"bib48\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2008</a>; Cain, Schechter &amp; Bautz <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib9\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib9\" data-open=\"bib9\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2011</a>; Sereno &amp; Umetsu <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib45\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib45\" data-open=\"bib45\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2011</a>). Peng et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib40\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib40\" data-open=\"bib40\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2009</a>) finds a discrepant hydrostatic mass based on X-ray data from <em>Chandra</em> but Riemer-S\u00f8rensen et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib43\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib43\" data-open=\"bib43\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2009</a>) find that excluding substructure alleviates or even eliminates the discrepancy. Lensing data combined with X-ray and SZ data have the potential to reveal information not only about the <em>invisible</em> DM distribution but also about the physical phenomena taking place in the cluster that have to bring the gas pressure and DM-driven gravity to a quasi-equilibrium state. The new Frontier Fields programme<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fn1\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fn1\" data-open=\"fn1\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-fn js-xref-fn\"><sup>1</sup></a> is now underway to provide the deepest <em>Hubble</em> data ever recorded for massive lensing clusters, further motivating our assumption-free modelling.</p><p class=\"chapter-para\">Despite exhausting lensing studies of A1689, many arcs still remain unmatched for this cluster. Certainly, many missing counterimages of highly magnified images are too faint to be useful or remain undetected. Others are of too low contrast to be detected within the light of luminous cluster members. Inaccuracy of mass models used to reconstruct the mass distribution is another issue, given the significant variation between published solutions. In Ponente &amp; Diego (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib41\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib41\" data-open=\"bib41\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2011</a>), the authors show how very erroneous mass distributions can still reproduce lensing data to high accuracy. In other words, being able to reproduce the observed arcs is no guarantee that the reconstructed mass distribution is right. The most detailed SL analysis of A1689 have been able to match tens of arcs, have relied either on the distribution of member galaxies to guide the models or on parametric models with the inclusion of many parameters depending on the number of substructures adopted.</p><p class=\"chapter-para\">However, the persistent resistance of some obvious bright lensed images to be matched with other images (when the same models predict other bright counterpart(s) for those lensed images) suggests that these models are still missing fundamental pieces needed to solve the puzzle. One of the limitations of SL data is that it quickly becomes insensitive to the mass distribution beyond the Einstein radius, especially if the distribution of matter around the centre is approximately spherical. Clumps with a significant amount of matter that lie just beyond the Einstein radius might go unnoticed with these parametric models as the model contains enough parameters within the Einstein radius to easily fit the data. Attempts have been made to constrain the matter distribution beyond the Einstein radius of A1689 by combining the WL data with SL data but in all cases (to the best of our knowledge) these <em>joint</em> analyses have been made a posteriori when either the density profiles are combined to extract a single density profile (Umetsu &amp; Broadhurst <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib48\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib48\" data-open=\"bib48\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2008</a>) or the SL solution is tested against the WL data for consistency (Limousin et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib31\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib31\" data-open=\"bib31\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2007</a>).</p><p class=\"chapter-para\">In this paper, we revisit A1689 to obtain a truly joint solution combining in a single inversion (i.e. not a posteriori) the SL and WL data. By doing this, our two-dimensional model of the mass distribution has to account simultaneously for the multiple lensed systems observed in A1689 and for the reduced shear measurements that extend well beyond the Einstein radius. As reference cosmological model, we consider a flat \u039bCDM model with \u03a9<sub>m</sub>\u00a0=\u00a00.3.</p>                    <h2 scrollto-destination=21026306 id=\"21026306\" class=\"section-title js-splitscreen-section-title\" data-legacy-id=sec2>2 ACS DATA</h2>\r\n<p class=\"chapter-para\">In this paper, we used public imaging data obtained from the ACS (filters: <em>F</em>450<em>W</em> and <em>F</em>814<em>W</em>) and the WFC3 (filter <em>F</em>125<em>W</em>), retrieved from the Mikulski Archive for Space Telescope. The data come from two different programmes. The <em>F</em>814<em>W</em> (ACS) and <em>F</em>125<em>W</em> (WFC3) data were obtained within the <em>HST</em> programme 11718 (PI Blakeslee, Cycle 17), from 2010 May 29 to July 8, while the ACS <em>F</em>475<em>W</em> images were obtained within the programme 9289 (PI Fors, Cycle 11) on 2002 June 16. The total exposure time is 9500, 75172 and 14367\u00a0s in the <em>F</em>450<em>W</em>, <em>F</em>814<em>W</em> and <em>F</em>125<em>W</em> filters, respectively. The <em>F</em>814<em>W</em> data set has been independently reduced and used by Alamo-Mart\u00ednez et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib1\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib1\" data-open=\"bib1\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2013</a>) to study the intracluster population of globular clusters. The data reduction of the optical data consisted in two main steps, based mostly on <span class=\"small-caps\">multidrizzle</span> (Koekemoer et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib26\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib26\" data-open=\"bib26\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2002</a>).<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fn2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fn2\" data-open=\"fn2\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-fn js-xref-fn\"><sup>2</sup></a> First, we combined the images obtained in each run and optimized the image sampling. Then, we performed cosmic rays rejection and aligned the images.<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fn3\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fn3\" data-open=\"fn3\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-fn js-xref-fn\"><sup>3</sup></a> The final mosaic has a pixel scale 0.05\u00a0arcsec. We combined these three bands images to produce the colour image of the new candidate lenses shown in the appendix.</p>                    <h2 scrollto-destination=21026310 id=\"21026310\" class=\"section-title js-splitscreen-section-title\" data-legacy-id=sec3>3 LENSING DATA ON A1689</h2>\r\n<p class=\"chapter-para\">A compilation of systems found in the literature is shown in Table\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-tbl2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"tbl2\" data-open=\"tbl2\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">A1</a> in the appendix. They are obtained basically from three sources: Broadhurst et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib7\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib7\" data-open=\"bib7\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005b</a>), Limousin et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib31\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib31\" data-open=\"bib31\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2007</a>) and Coe et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib11\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib11\" data-open=\"bib11\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2010</a>). Many of these systems are also listed in Halkola et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib20\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib20\" data-open=\"bib20\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2006</a>). Table\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-tbl2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"tbl2\" data-open=\"tbl2\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">A1</a> is built after cross-correlating the original tables in the references above to avoid repetitions. Systems that were listed originally in Broadhurst et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib7\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib7\" data-open=\"bib7\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005b</a>) are referred as B05. Systems that appear in both Limousin et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib31\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib31\" data-open=\"bib31\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2007</a>) and Coe et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib11\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib11\" data-open=\"bib11\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2010</a>) or just in Coe et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib11\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib11\" data-open=\"bib11\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2010</a>) are listed as C10. Systems that appear only in Limousin et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib31\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib31\" data-open=\"bib31\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2007</a>) are listed as L07 and the new system candidates presented in this paper are listed as D14 in Table\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-tbl2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"tbl2\" data-open=\"tbl2\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">A1</a>. Some of the original systems in Broadhurst et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib7\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib7\" data-open=\"bib7\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005b</a>) were rearranged or updated with additional arclets by other authors in later papers after comparison with alternative mass models. In this paper, we rely on the original selection of Broadhurst et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib7\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib7\" data-open=\"bib7\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005b</a>) after excluding some dubious systems but we explore also the solutions obtained after incorporating the alternative systems published in the literature. The exclusion (or re-arrangement) of some systems listed in Table\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-tbl2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"tbl2\" data-open=\"tbl2\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">A1</a> is made after a new visual colour and morphology comparison of the system members based on the new and deep ACS images. For instance, the confusion between systems 10 and 12 can be resolved by the presence of a pinkish core in system 10 not present in system 12. Different authors (Limousin et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib31\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib31\" data-open=\"bib31\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2007</a> and Coe et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib11\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib11\" data-open=\"bib11\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2010</a>) have suggested alternative rearrangements for some of these systems. Although we do not consider all the alternative possibilities in this paper, they might be perfectly valid as well. In fact, as we show later, some of the new counterimages discovered by other authors (like in system 12) will be naturally predicted/confirmed by our model, and hence, fully consistent with it. For systems listed in Broadhurst et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib7\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib7\" data-open=\"bib7\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005b</a>), we maintain the original system identification. Alternative identifications of the central counterimages of some systems have been used in Limousin et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib31\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib31\" data-open=\"bib31\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2007</a>) and Coe et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib11\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib11\" data-open=\"bib11\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2010</a>). Some of these alternative identifications are also reflected in Table\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-tbl2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"tbl2\" data-open=\"tbl2\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">A1</a>. Although not explicitly mentioned in the Table\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-tbl2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"tbl2\" data-open=\"tbl2\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">A1</a>, the last system in Halkola et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib20\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib20\" data-open=\"bib20\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2006</a>) corresponds (at least partially) to our system 58 in Table\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-tbl2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"tbl2\" data-open=\"tbl2\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">A1</a>. The last 11 systems of Table\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-tbl2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"tbl2\" data-open=\"tbl2\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">A1</a> (denoted with D14 in the REF column) should be treated just as mere candidates since they are obtained after identifying new system candidates using our solution discussed below and without a proper photometric redshift estimation. The new candidate systems are shown in Figs\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig24\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig24\" data-open=\"fig24\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">A1</a> and\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig25\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig25\" data-open=\"fig25\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">A2</a> in the appendix. The stamps are extracted from a red giant branch composite image of three <em>Hubble</em> filters (<em>F</em>475<em>W</em>, <em>F</em>814<em>W</em> and the NIR <em>F</em>125<em>W</em>). Some of the positions listed in Coe et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib11\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib11\" data-open=\"bib11\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2010</a>) were incorrectly reported in the tex file of the original paper. These positions have been corrected in Table\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-tbl2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"tbl2\" data-open=\"tbl2\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">A1</a>. Table\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-tbl2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"tbl2\" data-open=\"tbl2\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">A1</a> contains a total of 50 systems.<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fn4\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fn4\" data-open=\"fn4\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-fn js-xref-fn\"><sup>4</sup></a> Systems 25 and 32 contain multiple candidates for some of the secondary images and will not be used in our analysis. Out of the 50 systems listed in Table\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-tbl2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"tbl2\" data-open=\"tbl2\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">A1</a>, we use only a reliable subset of 26 systems corresponding to systems 1 through 30 in Broadhurst et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib7\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib7\" data-open=\"bib7\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005b</a>) but excluding suspicious systems 20, 26, 27 (in addition to system 25 mentioned above) which show different colours between the different counterimages once the new IR data is included in the colour images. Stamps of these systems that we exclude from our analysis are shown online in the same web page.<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fn5\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fn5\" data-open=\"fn5\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-fn js-xref-fn\"><sup>5</sup></a></p><p class=\"chapter-para\">System 10 and 12 have been re-matched after examination of new IR data. The rematching is based on (1) the very distinctive colour of the nucleus (once the IR band is added) of the original 12.2, 12.3 images which is similar to the colour of the nucleus of the original system 10; (2) the need for the original system 12.2, 12.3 to have other counterimages in the field of view (according to the different models we have checked); (3) the predicted counterimages for the original system 12.2, 12.3 fall near the positions of system 10 and (4) the fact that both systems have the same spectroscopic redshift. All these facts make us believe the original system 10 and the images 12.2,12.3 are in fact the same system.</p><p class=\"chapter-para\">Our WL data are derived from Umetsu &amp; Broadhurst (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib48\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib48\" data-open=\"bib48\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2008</a>) based on Subaru <em>Vi</em><sup>\u2032</sup> imaging observations. The background galaxies are selected requiring they are redder than the cluster sequence by (<em>V</em> \u2212 <em>i</em><sup>\u2032</sup>)\u00a0&gt;\u00a01 and 20\u00a0&lt;\u00a0<em>i</em><sup>\u2032</sup>\u00a0&lt;\u00a025.5 resulting in a mean density of background galaxies of 12\u00a0arcmin<sup>\u22122</sup> and a mean effective redshift of 0.68. We assume this mean redshift for all the background galaxies. We refer the reader to that paper for a detailed description of their observations and analysis. In this work, we use two-dimensional reduced-shear data on a regular grid of 10\u00a0\u00d7\u00a010 independent grid points with 1<sup>\u2032</sup> spacing, covering the central 10\u00a0\u00d7\u00a010\u00a0arcmin<sup>2</sup> region out from the original 30\u00a0\u00d7\u00a025\u00a0arcmin<sup>2</sup> region. We are mainly interested in the central region but extending the lensing constraints a bit further beyond the regime of the SL data can help to stabilize the solution. Extending our analysis to distances much farther would have no effect on the constraints derived in the central region. We exclude from our analysis the innermost four pixels overlapping with the SL regime, so that our WL data set consists of 100 \u2212 4\u00a0=\u00a096 reduced-shear data points. Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig1\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig1\" data-open=\"fig1\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">1</a> (left) shows the two data sets used in this paper as well as the distribution (and morphology) of member galaxies that will be used to build the fiducial deflection field (see the next section). The right-hand panel shows the central 3.3\u00a0\u00d7\u00a03.3\u00a0arcmin<sup>2</sup> region (WL data not shown).</p>                        <a id=\"21026314\" scrollto-destination=\"21026314\"></a>\r\n<div data-id=\"fig1\" class=\"fig fig-section js-fig-section\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 1.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig1.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&amp;Signature=lneTrpUGPw1PDKepz0bzmwIQlrsFcZ5h25uYSO7VGcMH7c9spAX-KezicbanHuaf2p8pQNs0IA8ICRWVJ~9Y1Sb033n~PHv~FTBlatgbdFLKtlk5qO8~gWfoJQ7bSYTu7VCLlLkF97mXmqbjXli7a~mKnnskyiM8mNMp4WMp094rK0hWwmVhe~PJBR~g4rVg077fm1dDZLDzBvNfbg2Q6ttxAI503YnF40bmR8xC-5B9PiRt3HBZPFTRjxuUwvZAh0GTdYYgxQQHDXQ2vVGJJAgmvVW3sHP~I8H1rbovlgM2ycRJmUv6L01utiPFnYtTMPWlzeuF1gOb84kxVipAaQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Data set used for the reconstruction. The left-hand panel shows the entire field of view of 10\u2009arcmin with the SL, reduced shear measurements, the position of the fiducial galaxies and their assumed shapes. The right-hand panel shows a zoom into the central 3.33\u2009arcmin region with the arcs and galaxies that shows better extent of the haloes in our model.</p></div></div><div content-id=\"fig1\" class=\"fig fig-modal reveal-modal\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 1.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig1.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&amp;Signature=lneTrpUGPw1PDKepz0bzmwIQlrsFcZ5h25uYSO7VGcMH7c9spAX-KezicbanHuaf2p8pQNs0IA8ICRWVJ~9Y1Sb033n~PHv~FTBlatgbdFLKtlk5qO8~gWfoJQ7bSYTu7VCLlLkF97mXmqbjXli7a~mKnnskyiM8mNMp4WMp094rK0hWwmVhe~PJBR~g4rVg077fm1dDZLDzBvNfbg2Q6ttxAI503YnF40bmR8xC-5B9PiRt3HBZPFTRjxuUwvZAh0GTdYYgxQQHDXQ2vVGJJAgmvVW3sHP~I8H1rbovlgM2ycRJmUv6L01utiPFnYtTMPWlzeuF1gOb84kxVipAaQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Data set used for the reconstruction. The left-hand panel shows the entire field of view of 10\u2009arcmin with the SL, reduced shear measurements, the position of the fiducial galaxies and their assumed shapes. The right-hand panel shows a zoom into the central 3.33\u2009arcmin region with the arcs and galaxies that shows better extent of the haloes in our model.\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig1.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026314/stu2064fig1.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig1.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026314\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig1.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&Signature=yEwXCuLPH4KERtt7-Au~3kILAUUQPsA6zGRgEO~lrMO3gI0EBNT7F9S6e3phMbZ3QJaOHmloo2hWOSQR-zJ2n1wsjM6xGvskCoEWTfNrER-x4a81R-Qax7B3RDKuc6GP-QfNdYrXIYH6Ch07BbLcHAnoZP8vNFZIPK7wf6zw7bI7PNYCGlC1aNx3DLjYsoYOO9sEGGwZBp0neuULxPXFK1xgufOsu9tzaRom4gM2Mr82IFbesm~61om-c5ydVcZVlN3YYgmhm6QIqgwhlIsAwhKFZc-TNic~jos5C5GZPwJxgSUpONHfgHl~oEPtxy-IWsmD3Pok6aE70RwalvT5-w__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026314&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig1.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">Data set used for the reconstruction. The left-hand panel shows the entire field of view of 10\u2009arcmin with the SL, reduced shear measurements, the position of the fiducial galaxies and their assumed shapes. The right-hand panel shows a zoom into the central 3.33\u2009arcmin region with the arcs and galaxies that shows better extent of the haloes in our model.</p></div></div>                    <h2 scrollto-destination=21026315 id=\"21026315\" class=\"section-title js-splitscreen-section-title\" data-legacy-id=sec4>4 RECONSTRUCTION METHOD</h2>\r\n<p class=\"chapter-para\">We use the improved method, <span class=\"small-caps\">wslap+</span>, to combine the weak and SL data and perform the mass reconstruction. The reader can find the details of the method in our previous papers (Diego et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib14\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib14\" data-open=\"bib14\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005a</a>,<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib15\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib15\" data-open=\"bib15\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">b</a>, <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib16\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib16\" data-open=\"bib16\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2007</a>; Ponente &amp; Diego <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib41\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib41\" data-open=\"bib41\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2011</a>; Sendra et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib44\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib44\" data-open=\"bib44\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2014</a>). Here, we give a brief summary of the most essential elements.</p><div class=\"&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            \">Given the standard lens equation <div class=\"formula-wrap\"><div class=\"disp-formula\" id=\"equ1\" content-id=\"equ1\"><div class=\"tex-math display-math\"> \\begin{equation}\r\n\\beta = \\theta - \\alpha (\\theta ,\\Sigma (\\theta )),\r\n\\end{equation} </div></div><span class=\"label\">(1)</span></div>where \u03b8 is the observed position of the source, \u03b1 is the deflection angle, \u03a3(\u03b8) is the surface mass density of the cluster at the position \u03b8 and \u03b2 is the position of the background source. Both the SL and WL observables can be expressed in terms of derivatives of the lensing potential, <div class=\"formula-wrap\"><div class=\"disp-formula\" id=\"equ2\" content-id=\"equ2\"><div class=\"tex-math display-math\"> \\begin{equation}\r\n\\psi (\\theta ) = \\frac{4\\,G D_{{\\rm l}}D_{{\\rm ls}}}{c^2 D_{{\\rm s}}} \\int \\mathrm{d}^2\\theta ^{\\prime } \\Sigma (\\theta ^{\\prime })ln(|\\theta - \\theta ^{\\prime }|),\r\n\\end{equation} </div></div><span class=\"label\">(2)</span></div>where <em>D</em><sub>l</sub>, <em>D</em><sub>ls</sub> and <em>D</em><sub>s</sub> are the angular diameter distances to the lens, from the lens to the source and from the observer to the source, respectively. The unknowns of the lensing problem are in general the surface mass density and the positions of the background sources. As shown in Diego et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib16\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib16\" data-open=\"bib16\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2007</a>), the WL and SL problem can be expressed as a system of linear equations that can be represented in a compact form <div class=\"formula-wrap\"><div class=\"disp-formula\" id=\"equ3\" content-id=\"equ3\"><div class=\"tex-math display-math\"> \\begin{equation}\r\n\\Theta = \\Gamma X,\r\n\\end{equation} </div></div><span class=\"label\">(3)</span></div>where the measured SL and WL observables are contained in the array \u0398 of dimension <em>N</em><sub>\u0398</sub>\u00a0=\u00a02<em>N</em><sub>SL</sub>\u00a0+\u00a02<em>N</em><sub>WL</sub>, the unknown surface mass density and source positions are in the array <em>X</em> of dimension <em>N</em><sub><em>X</em></sub>\u00a0=\u00a0<em>N</em><sub><em>c</em></sub>\u00a0+\u00a0<em>N</em><sub><em>g</em></sub>\u00a0+\u00a02<em>N</em><sub><em>s</em></sub> and the matrix \u0393 is known (for a given grid configuration and fiducial galaxy deflection field, see below) and has dimension <em>N</em><sub>\u0398</sub>\u00a0\u00d7\u00a0<em>N</em><sub><em>X</em></sub>. <em>N</em><sub>SL</sub> is the number of SL observables (each one contributing with two constraints, <em>x</em>, and <em>y</em>). <em>N</em><sub>WL</sub> is the number of WL observables (each one contributing with two constraints, \u03b3<sub>1</sub>, and \u03b3<sub>2</sub>), <em>N</em><sub><em>c</em></sub> is the number of grid points (or cells) that we use to divide the field of view. <em>N</em><sub><em>g</em></sub> is the number of deflection fields (from cluster members) that we consider. <em>N</em><sub><em>s</em></sub> is the number of background sources (each contributes with two unknowns, \u03b2<sub><em>x</em></sub>, and \u03b2<sub><em>y</em></sub>, see Sendra et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib44\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib44\" data-open=\"bib44\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2014</a> for details). The solution is found after minimizing a quadratic function that estimates the solution of the system of equations (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-equ3\"></span><a href=\"#equ3\" class=\"sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec\">3</a>). For this minimization, we use a quadratic algorithm which is optimized for solutions with the constraint that the solution, <em>X</em>, must be positive. This is particularly important since by imposing this constraint we avoid the unphysical situation where the masses associated with the galaxies are negative (that could otherwise provide a reasonable solution, from the formal mathematical point of view, to the system of linear equations\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-equ3\"></span><a href=\"#equ3\" class=\"sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec\">3</a>). Imposing the constrain <em>X</em>\u00a0&gt;\u00a00 also helps in regularizing the solution as it avoids large negative and positive contiguous fluctuations.</div><p class=\"chapter-para\">Earlier work has shown how the addition of the small deflection fields from member galaxies can help improve the mass determination when enough constraints are available (see for instance Kassiola, Kovner &amp; Fort <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib24\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib24\" data-open=\"bib24\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">1992</a>; Kneib et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib25\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib25\" data-open=\"bib25\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">1996</a>). In our previous paper (Sendra et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib44\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib44\" data-open=\"bib44\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2014</a>), we quantified via simulations how the addition of deflections from all the main member galaxies helps improve the mass reconstruction with respect to our previous standard non-parametric method. Strongly lensed galaxies are often locally affected by member galaxies. However, these perturbations cannot be recovered in grid-based reconstructions because the lensing information is too sparse to resolve member galaxies. For our study, we select the 73 brightest elliptical galaxies in the cluster central region and associate with them a mass according to their luminosity. The member galaxies are selected from the red sequence. We assume the fiducial deflection field comprising these member galaxies just scales by a fixed luminosity\u2013mass ratio. Later, the fitting procedure determines this proportionality constant that allows for the best reproduction of the data. For the mass profiles, we assume a NFW profile (Navarro, Frenk &amp; White <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib37\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib37\" data-open=\"bib37\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">1997</a>), and adopt a self-similarity approach where the scale radius scales with the mass. As discussed later, the choice of the particular profile is not very relevant for our results. In Sendra et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib44\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib44\" data-open=\"bib44\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2014</a>), we used one deflection field to model all the galaxies in the cluster. In the case of A1689, we go a step further and we use two deflection fields (i.e <em>N</em><sub><em>g</em></sub>\u00a0=\u00a02, see definition of <em>N</em><sub><em>g</em></sub> above). The first one is associated with the central type-cD galaxy and the second one contains the deflection field from the remaining dominant galaxies in the cluster. Each deflection field contributes in our model as one free parameter (its amplitude with respect to the fiducial amplitude). In principle, one could incorporate an independent deflection field for each one of the member galaxies but caution has to be taken to maintain as much as possible the orthogonality between the grid cells and the individual deflection fields. This will be studied in Section\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-sec7\"></span><a href=\"#sec7\" class=\"sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec\">7</a>. Settling for two deflection fields may be regarded as a fair compromise between the overly simple assumption that all galaxies in the cluster have individual haloes with masses that trace light following the same luminosity\u2013mass relation and a potentially more realistic but also unnecessarily complex assumption that each galaxy has a different luminosity\u2013mass ratio. We make an exception for the central cD galaxy because of its distinctive shallow luminosity profile and the separate origin that may be implied by the anomalously large numbers of globular clusters for this object and cD galaxies in general (see Alamo-Mart\u00ednez et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib1\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib1\" data-open=\"bib1\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2013</a>). All the galaxies used in our fiducial model are shown in Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig1\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig1\" data-open=\"fig1\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">1</a> where we use a non-linear colour scale to better show the extent and shapes of the individual haloes in our fiducial model. As in our previous paper (Sendra et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib44\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib44\" data-open=\"bib44\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2014</a>), we consider truncated NFW profiles to construct our fiducial model.</p>                    <h2 scrollto-destination=21026320 id=\"21026320\" class=\"section-title js-splitscreen-section-title\" data-legacy-id=sec5>5 RESULTS</h2>\r\n<p class=\"chapter-para\">When combining the WL and SL data sets, due to the large field of view (10\u00a0\u00d7\u00a010 arcmin<sup>2</sup>), and in order to maximize the resolution of the grid in the region covering the SL part of the data, we use a two resolution grid where the central 6.66\u00a0\u00d7\u00a06.66\u00a0arcmin<sup>2</sup> is sampled with smaller grid cells (of 9.37 arcsec in size) and the remaining area is sampled with 25 arcsec grid cells. Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig2\" data-open=\"fig2\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">2</a> shows the grid configuration. The small gap that can be appreciated between the two regions has a negligible effect since this region gets filled by the overlapping Gaussians on top of each grid cell. The use of a multiresolution grid introduces a bias in the reconstruction (see discussion below) in the transition region between the two resolutions mostly due to the overlap of Gaussians with different widths. The outer region is used as a buffer zone that, however, still contributes to the WL constraints in the transition phase between the two regions. Hence, we do not make full use of the results from the outer region in our conclusions but instead we will restrict ourselves to the central 6.66\u00a0\u00d7\u00a06.66\u00a0arcmin<sup>2</sup> region for most of our results. However, we should note that even within the central region caution has to be taken when interpreting the results close to the transition phase as some biases are still present near the border.</p>                        <a id=\"21026322\" scrollto-destination=\"21026322\"></a>\r\n<div data-id=\"fig2\" class=\"fig fig-section js-fig-section\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 2.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig2.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&amp;Signature=GZVCPhNSVJjoedfVRNTZg7f8H6l6GBkqdBtyoDzRZfqeEDf2xHlcpBqyLBONiHSAKLJ~VsDO0Yznth0cOuQcteCMjQy2AkJLAjEoDCYf5fOfkrB7U3w~8LyfQxj5Qf4u437F0njUZxFjjf0fPG1LB4c5AZH6xaXgU7Of6b6vl4gC~n3xDodyfXI9ZmA34S2fbmramLK3KQOKH9QgV4-s2J5AELIhBiZJ4hLkHDJDbq3EEt4Y0NvDH3a7xvB6-obSOHiyd34XyVnHNVqJthbBkQ1QfIyCYV3j~nIP-eT~J0Pox~dcCgwA43WNOYKZauGAHxlnWnbDXB-yLW9E~bbacQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Grid used in the reconstruction. The grid cell sizes are 25 and 9.37\u00a0arcsec. The high-resolution grid covers an area of 6.66\u00a0\u00d7\u00a06.66\u00a0arcmin2.\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig2.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026322/stu2064fig2.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig2.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026322\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig2.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&Signature=LXVNIIO4jCLOQYHfAfCRxCD3tIUNybs~D8-WOn0ozeInzLj-JVXbYxSScb-WEinbGyDUmUacQjh4qHxyEi6zgrWamaxNo~TxHkGLms0pn1UDe~rwco1fBZnbamdG8~aoafOxNiipit8p3uAmVW0UUdxLl5TY~ETgQk-Q3tvznsTAYGgiWgXrZyeWVd7KWupjWD4LbgIuEdbuRqUxeb9SEYJhdDT5zNRGu3q7~43lk~MuqoEBs3ncDH7Ke8MbJC~c5TMgW7nzFn~jC6pD96ozDIJgu6Y-Ihz3KT9GQuMnWBSvAYXaMZ~Rul3x8zUOypB2NI2plSf9oL2PGjYIRUMRyA__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026322&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig2.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">Grid used in the reconstruction. The grid cell sizes are 25 and 9.37\u00a0arcsec. The high-resolution grid covers an area of 6.66\u00a0\u00d7\u00a06.66\u00a0arcmin<sup>2</sup>.</p></div></div><div content-id=\"fig2\" class=\"fig fig-modal reveal-modal\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 2.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig2.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&amp;Signature=GZVCPhNSVJjoedfVRNTZg7f8H6l6GBkqdBtyoDzRZfqeEDf2xHlcpBqyLBONiHSAKLJ~VsDO0Yznth0cOuQcteCMjQy2AkJLAjEoDCYf5fOfkrB7U3w~8LyfQxj5Qf4u437F0njUZxFjjf0fPG1LB4c5AZH6xaXgU7Of6b6vl4gC~n3xDodyfXI9ZmA34S2fbmramLK3KQOKH9QgV4-s2J5AELIhBiZJ4hLkHDJDbq3EEt4Y0NvDH3a7xvB6-obSOHiyd34XyVnHNVqJthbBkQ1QfIyCYV3j~nIP-eT~J0Pox~dcCgwA43WNOYKZauGAHxlnWnbDXB-yLW9E~bbacQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Grid used in the reconstruction. The grid cell sizes are 25 and 9.37\u00a0arcsec. The high-resolution grid covers an area of 6.66\u00a0\u00d7\u00a06.66\u00a0arcmin2.\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig2.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026322/stu2064fig2.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig2.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026322\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig2.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&Signature=LXVNIIO4jCLOQYHfAfCRxCD3tIUNybs~D8-WOn0ozeInzLj-JVXbYxSScb-WEinbGyDUmUacQjh4qHxyEi6zgrWamaxNo~TxHkGLms0pn1UDe~rwco1fBZnbamdG8~aoafOxNiipit8p3uAmVW0UUdxLl5TY~ETgQk-Q3tvznsTAYGgiWgXrZyeWVd7KWupjWD4LbgIuEdbuRqUxeb9SEYJhdDT5zNRGu3q7~43lk~MuqoEBs3ncDH7Ke8MbJC~c5TMgW7nzFn~jC6pD96ozDIJgu6Y-Ihz3KT9GQuMnWBSvAYXaMZ~Rul3x8zUOypB2NI2plSf9oL2PGjYIRUMRyA__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026322&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig2.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">Grid used in the reconstruction. The grid cell sizes are 25 and 9.37\u00a0arcsec. The high-resolution grid covers an area of 6.66\u00a0\u00d7\u00a06.66\u00a0arcmin<sup>2</sup>.</p></div></div><p class=\"chapter-para\">For comparison purposes, we have performed the reconstruction in three different cases depending on the data set used. In case (i) we use only the SL data set, in case (ii) we use only the WL data set and in case (iii) we combine the SL and WL data set into the same data vector. In order to make a direct comparison, we use the same grid for all three cases although this is not optimal for the SL or WL case. In the SL-only case, we would use only a regular grid covering a smaller field of view (of 3\u00a0\u00d7\u00a03 arcmin<sup>2</sup>) while in the case of the WL-only case, we would also use a regular grid (with poorer resolution) but over the entire 10\u00a0\u00d7\u00a010\u00a0arcmin<sup>2</sup> field of view. Since our main interest is on the solution obtained when the SL and WL data sets are combined, we maintain the same grid configuration in all three cases. Also, we start the minimization in the same initial condition to eliminate this degree of freedom from the solution (different initial conditions are explored later in the paper). Finally, we use the same number of iterations (8000 iterations, this number will be discussed later) in the SL-only and SL+WL cases. For the WL-only case, we stop the minimization before to avoid overfitting (a large number of iterations in the WL-only case would produce a solution that is capable of reproducing the noisy WL estimates so the minimization must be stopped before this regime is reached). In Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig3\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig3\" data-open=\"fig3\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">3</a>, we present the 2D-reconstructed mass in the central region and the associated critical curves for a source at redshift 2 for the three cases. From left to right, we show the cases of the SL-only, WL-only and SL+WL. Note how the critical curve does not change much in the case SL+WL when compared with the SL-only case. This is a consequence of the critical curve being much more sensitive to the very central region (and the SL data). However, when the WL data is used in combination with the SL data, new interesting features in the mass distribution emerge even beyond the Einstein radius. Some of these features appear even more intriguing when looking at the magnification map (see Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig4\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig4\" data-open=\"fig4\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">4</a>) where some filamentary structures and clumps are made more evident. Both the projected mass and magnification maps are closely connected and the magnification map in this weaker lensing regime can be used as an alternative tracer of the mass especially in the range of interest shown in Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig4\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig4\" data-open=\"fig4\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">4</a> where the convergence, \u03ba\u00a0&lt;\u00a00.5, and \u03ba\u00a0\u223c\u00a0\u03b3. In this regime, and to first order, the magnification, \u03bc, can be approximated (by Taylor expansion) as \u03bc\u00a0\u2248\u00a01\u00a0+\u00a02\u03ba that shows the clear connection between magnification and projected mass. Further investigation of these features demands better-quality WL data and will be the subject of future studies. The small critical curve around the clump at the edge of the bottom-right quadrant is close to a feature seen also in Umetsu &amp; Broadhurst (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib48\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib48\" data-open=\"bib48\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2008</a>). This fact suggests that the feature in our reconstruction, although it could be affected by its proximity to the buffer zone, may also be produced by a real structure in that area.</p>                        <a id=\"21026324\" scrollto-destination=\"21026324\"></a>\r\n<div data-id=\"fig3\" class=\"fig fig-section js-fig-section\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 3.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig3.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&amp;Signature=Em3mShnHbOPbx5ZGqqFEs8Z4GbiPBROFaujr8bBVKFEdLEAJO2J7VD5VA2H7GZAemIaTAeaNNHPMFuQGCk5rnf6VADhS6Q04NzCFwtCXkypR7ran92rdBB8AR9Guqh2UB7PekeYkWSi8UqksyNvdIMAnzSsWULjNHPebxUMGz0V~y4w3NRQEg0USMrwrhUP0P2TCCm9tU6ZP~n0-g-OhqMOlGrasD8nr2YsDlBkRHiaRbexbkhLYneRdE27o9o7MsyxCs~MsFKhEJaUvW9LLAQzytAAqsm1OPNSmMyQbTLVwieA1zqfhZdTUbt3U~~Ks9xIBkFUJyTLt1D9ssrzqoQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Solutions (and associated critical curves for a source at redshift z\u00a0=\u00a02) for the cases where only the SL data is used in the reconstruction (left), only the WL data is used in the reconstruction (centre) and both, the SL and WL data are used in the reconstruction (right). The colours are in log-scale to increase contrast. The two small black regions in the centre correspond to magnifications less than 1 (that have been set to 0 in the log-scale for contrast purposes). The drop in the outer region (buffer zone) is a systematic effect due to the larger cell size in the grid. The features close to the transition region between the two grid resolutions are not always to be trusted.\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig4.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026325/stu2064fig4.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig4.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026325\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig4.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&Signature=t8glQXd9PZu1akSW5ylFGUl7d2sb2ipYZuii~a5WW4I5PqGJ~3wvuV8nTJ0uPJMF4-TKIhRQFFmR4vG7Ov-R~w6PvJjcqWanJXaywQUU-RaIgWlcuvBGcvss~vFt4YYItrvFWwCjFb4azjdoIJzKyHWfFcNfY2XvMuxNXyhy1n2lENc5s-7pZoqLGYbQHgCl-XjX-UtLFThQfZ73b8383niSM0tJw7ZpHxn23AN4X9r5yeOjx~sbXnYgW3L4-g7fICytCOpH2XcZkjKTdvpvKy6VM4CBV1~MmtMON-qGEQRdT5RjLK9ofMnGGP73CmnGYCXIpoTn1sFC5BFlf7lODw__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026325&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig4.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">Magnification map in the entire field of view of 10\u00a0\u00d7\u00a010\u00a0arcmin<sup>2</sup> for the SL+WL case. The colours are in log-scale to increase contrast. The two small black regions in the centre correspond to magnifications less than 1 (that have been set to 0 in the log-scale for contrast purposes). The drop in the outer region (buffer zone) is a systematic effect due to the larger cell size in the grid. The features close to the transition region between the two grid resolutions are not always to be trusted.</p></div></div><p class=\"chapter-para\">A more quantitative comparison of the different solutions is shown in Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig5\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig5\" data-open=\"fig5\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">5</a> where we show the density profiles of the surface mass density in terms of critical density. Unless otherwise noted, the critical density, \u03a3<sub>crit</sub>\u00a0=\u00a04.746\u00a0\u00d7\u00a010<sup>15</sup>\u2009M<sub>\u2299</sub>\u2009<em>h</em>\u2009Mpc<sup>\u22122</sup>, is computed for <em>z</em><sub>mean</sub>\u00a0=\u00a01.07. The WL-only case shows the typical mass-sheet degeneracy which has not been corrected in our solution. Also, in the WL-only solution, the mass at the centre is mostly associated with the individual galaxies accounting for the reduced shear in the vicinity of the Einstein radius, while the grid complements the central galaxy mass. This is better seen when comparing the values of <em>C</em><sub>1</sub> (coefficient for the galaxies in the cluster except the type-cD) and <em>C</em><sub>2</sub> (coefficient for the type-cD galaxy) for each case: for the SL-only case, we get <em>C</em><sub>1</sub>\u00a0=\u00a00.30, <em>C</em><sub>2</sub>\u00a0=\u00a00.25; for the WL-only case, we get <em>C</em><sub>1</sub>\u00a0=\u00a00.55, <em>C</em><sub>2</sub>\u00a0=\u00a00.28 and for the SL+WL case, we get <em>C</em><sub>1</sub>\u00a0=\u00a00.33, <em>C</em><sub>2</sub>\u00a0=\u00a00.26. The WL-only case has more freedom to increase the mass in the galaxies since this does not affect the SL constraints.</p>                        <a id=\"21026327\" scrollto-destination=\"21026327\"></a>\r\n<div data-id=\"fig5\" class=\"fig fig-section js-fig-section\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 5.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig5.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&amp;Signature=ioZgnHq3GNap9NQvkzaBajV0NNvZkNp1xKTS8Ix1JvCLebWGgPZWv~AzcPKgUfRaB0gNFdRZMh8RivROwoP0S7s9aWHZ0KdFCINo7PfG2NaJTyvEEDg-zsxvur5oUFrgJNOLL629uMOaFvhApXQvv9a-H~IfvlmMfNVnJ3~7b8JQkf6uHcGP7uGU53p1oNDttmjRYPZAn6SZxoEL1EQlN9IFFymR5SQl8D94DXZ5xA8G~RN9aHrCrPDtAMtUk7ydJuSTZKj~kJKSeE85RwKsa9k3zRvrkN~JLf0fI45w6av0rbiIDognIlIlRuZhAu4Z4HM6hlfmkL5SUgZVSHDwkg__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Profiles of the solutions obtained with SL data only (dotted), WL data only (dashed) and the combination SL+WL (solid). The systematic bump at 200\u2009arcsec (or 3.33\u2009arcmin) coincides with the position of the transition phase (for the grid) between the 6.66\u2009arcmin region and the outer buffer zone</p></div></div><div content-id=\"fig5\" class=\"fig fig-modal reveal-modal\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 5.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig5.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&amp;Signature=ioZgnHq3GNap9NQvkzaBajV0NNvZkNp1xKTS8Ix1JvCLebWGgPZWv~AzcPKgUfRaB0gNFdRZMh8RivROwoP0S7s9aWHZ0KdFCINo7PfG2NaJTyvEEDg-zsxvur5oUFrgJNOLL629uMOaFvhApXQvv9a-H~IfvlmMfNVnJ3~7b8JQkf6uHcGP7uGU53p1oNDttmjRYPZAn6SZxoEL1EQlN9IFFymR5SQl8D94DXZ5xA8G~RN9aHrCrPDtAMtUk7ydJuSTZKj~kJKSeE85RwKsa9k3zRvrkN~JLf0fI45w6av0rbiIDognIlIlRuZhAu4Z4HM6hlfmkL5SUgZVSHDwkg__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Profiles of the solutions obtained with SL data only (dotted), WL data only (dashed) and the combination SL+WL (solid). The smaller plot shows the same profiles but in linear scale and beyond 100\u2009arcsec. The units in the axis are the same as the larger plot. The systematic bump at 200\u2009arcsec (or 3.33\u2009arcmin) coincides with the position of the transition phase (for the grid) between the 6.66\u2009arcmin region and the outer buffer zone</p></div></div><p class=\"chapter-para\">On the other hand, in the SL-only case, the grid plays a more central role and accounts for most of the mass. Also, the SL-only case shows a sharp drop in mass beyond the Einstein radius, which is expected for this grid-based model, due to the lack of sensitivity of the SL data to the outer regions. When the SL and WL data sets are combined in the joint reconstruction, the new joint profile shows a smoother behaviour to larger radius and the solution compares well with previous estimates of the profile derived from SL-only and WL-only. Both grid and galaxies play important roles in fitting the SL+WL data set.</p><p class=\"chapter-para\">In terms of source reconstruction, Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig6\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig6\" data-open=\"fig6\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">6</a> shows the reconstructed sources for the two cases, SL-only (left) and SL+WL (right). In the two panels, the centre and the scale are the same. In both cases, the solutions obtained with SL-only and SL+WL data seem to be able to form 1\u20133\u2009arcsec sources that fall near well-defined caustics.</p>                        <a id=\"21026332\" scrollto-destination=\"21026332\"></a>\r\n<div data-id=\"fig6\" class=\"fig fig-section js-fig-section\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 6.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig6.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&amp;Signature=jsnftxRfth4eeZOA-merFSnTwFReYG5uqieriX~yKHunEdQ0Y2F-bZQTmIrVutsXx1I~A~a37074h01mUtaYtcbm6XUbh8-ujCEkbLDAul6U~9NXmDodwcdoq3FP-5I7LpfXwJNxH3rGeESzdRXhRTb9rbOC7NzDs8LokQseLiN03tARnwgIIVgBJ4Zga1MG~mHwzbejMryiReRjAgvWQ8YId03LYiMkmnIDW41dDjyh7WfIMlE49Yd91gCBYaXv-GDRcNDtwVmC2C0igSK2vNny2ZD8tIlFAIhzBOvv6TH12X8hOQw03nc7IDMUlXAimeVPtaj-PLwcl6OEjdsfnw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Caustics (at z\u00a0=\u00a02) for the SL only (left) and SL+WL case (right) compared with the reconstructed sources. Each source is represented with a different colour index from 1 (darkest grey) to 26 (lightest grey). The field of view is small and corresponds to 1.3<sup>\u2032</sup> across to maximize the <em>focal plane</em>. The centre is the same in both cases and corresponds to the centre of the original 10<sup>\u2032</sup> field of view.</p></div></div><p class=\"chapter-para\">In Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig7\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig7\" data-open=\"fig7\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">7</a>, we show the ratio between the 2D-reconstructed mass map and the corresponding profile. A circularly symmetric mass distribution should behave as a constant sheet of value <em>Ratio</em>\u00a0=\u00a01. Deviations from this value highlight the asymmetries in different regions of the cluster. Note how the central region exhibits a more symmetric structure but around the Einstein radius there are important deviations from the mean profile by a factor \u22484 above and below the mean density. The largest deviations occur near the buffer zone, and may be affected by the proximity to this transition phase. Overall, a left\u2013right global asymmetry (or gradient) is appreciated across the field of view. A similar asymmetry can also be found in Umetsu &amp; Broadhurst (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib48\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib48\" data-open=\"bib48\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2008</a>). The rings around the centre are due to the individual galaxies which produce spikes in the profile.</p>                        <a id=\"21026334\" scrollto-destination=\"21026334\"></a>\r\n<div data-id=\"fig7\" class=\"fig fig-section js-fig-section\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 7.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig7.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&amp;Signature=fe~YmG6i-h2xbJ8Ypr7jrcI-PFDpto5YzlVkIwwVPTPT1UK9pozVD1wFtQNJg-rI3cFahUdsUAYuyAyKONg9b6VzllTJVeXnzJ7FCyDrDUQ~ooCf2JCeCmiX8frXqWhUoACazYNLXRCagYMsVea2oaYlkIAR8ZYLcCGw8fyKNrqUPX~YbiFH~Ir5eHuUqYOYvPLM1Y~f3QYReavuobvNZ-KXqhH0YmAPbx0np8EwiAboipiu8zop6LgUs~RYSv15QhR4aZyR1bUt5~cjUVhqvWHBVChm9dwY4pFmNHiLgmXLn5oM3FAWUXvaySA0X9HTAatlfsRLQ7YYZEgne6DzGw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Asymmetric behaviour of the mass density in the central region of 6.66\u00a0\u00d7\u00a06.66\u00a0arcmin2. The plot shows the ratio between the solution 2D map (SL+WL case) and the corresponding circularly symmetric profile, that is, each pixel at a distance r from the centre is divided by the profile at the same r. In order to increase contrast, the ratio is saturated beyond the value 7.5 and we show the square root of this ratio.\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig7.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026334/stu2064fig7.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig7.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026334\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig7.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&Signature=p30mS~KESGIYCEIB4eDhMaa5XU5220hk9w6WYqeENf4~eLo6X1mBkGGZuQ2EQ-6RBD6IimAqD7WScl65NwF5mTHb2~9KO84qGw3mAWhiYMQ9cfj950QB3JfYMQ2iJNAyVAsmEXMfcooyA2kqz2ZvQlj7RDZfSPJDG09LelWjX99ZIzyBDqX2BHNL3MkB12sOFtgGF~6PgxeFKtkGn9ID~-DIs-z1c5BD~DkMR3Yl~3-SD2eQg1D9VnMfsfAau6zoL891AOKy7r3lj~9XLk9mwRdSwTesdb9l5hcbyVAn33lY4Xympi0Zm7V0RBWJPzNfG6mEnL~UpxJz0Pg5RCP4qw__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026334&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig7.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">Asymmetric behaviour of the mass density in the central region of 6.66\u00a0\u00d7\u00a06.66\u00a0arcmin<sup>2</sup>. The plot shows the ratio between the solution 2D map (SL+WL case) and the corresponding circularly symmetric profile, that is, each pixel at a distance <em>r</em> from the centre is divided by the profile at the same <em>r</em>. In order to increase contrast, the ratio is saturated beyond the value 7.5 and we show the square root of this ratio.</p></div></div>                    <h3 scrollto-destination=21026335 id=\"21026335\" class=\"section-title js-splitscreen-section-title\" data-legacy-id=sec5-1>5.1 Comparison with previous results and analytical models</h3>\r\n<p class=\"chapter-para\">It is important to compare the results obtained with our non-parametric algorithm with those obtained using fully parametric methods but a similar data set. Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig8\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig8\" data-open=\"fig8\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">8</a> shows our solution compared with two analytical models that fit solutions obtained by parametric methods. Broadhurst et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib6\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib6\" data-open=\"bib6\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005a</a>) found that the NFW profile did not fit well the SL+WL data in a similar way similar to our results, with a tendency to be too steep in the centre (<em>r</em>\u00a0&lt;\u00a050\u00a0kpc).</p>                        <a id=\"21026337\" scrollto-destination=\"21026337\"></a>\r\n<div data-id=\"fig8\" class=\"fig fig-section js-fig-section\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 8.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig8.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&amp;Signature=lXnyeTwn0BJRobkA1GvGX2Nn~Jil6RneA1~l98IrZ9~eAVFzacPayDg0WoF-g3r1Z0qPKRhzx1ubfHJSiDScbqYeRQw7bGUyj77~00dKIDoqpjSYZDRM0zwj-vAB6mG8xRCOsGR5y00-C6jQRy6gIbdGbqA-xmIfhXHNeP6aLwqFLIofJfVOYe-cFbSDn8X~b9Ez8txPEbmxvR07qJH7xvL-1-wpsSxvhdIpVfFU83qGFAgA7GH4zVYY~Th6sMB~NYDfn0VtJNzRFeRhXMx8aGJVTqfMIHRZCHf1uUlRBNxsSOp7UnNWUw6u1u3lsamm1H~pn27fW1VV0kAlYwnB0w__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Comparison of the profile corresponding to the SL+WL solution (after 8000 Iterations) with two NFW models found in the literature, and that fit their corresponding solutions (Broadhurst et\u00a0al. 2005a; Limousin et\u00a0al. 2007). The profiles are centred in the type-cD galaxy.\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig8.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026337/stu2064fig8.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig8.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026337\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig8.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&Signature=WvTshkqKKri57YyYS5aNs0jX0FU~-ya2sSE4KE3qm8BzwH32y3Mf1NnNbK9UO-Yesvr6NnSG7Qz0dWCxy4qCg7qrs6YSrQBwrBoj4kIVqtAnkGI5bgOeufgeAd9rI9t~zSshhqKMej7rwQKRjNQh~otrWB0k3iX9wStkjVoxtZaI3m43ab2InwB65KddBP77CT8qU80jbxOs~WLhNun-g5yHNKUpJsvhKpBY~6WMPpWSsXp-y8Iw~og47FdfshTmVa6~kBJCWJPFMii7cWAcGfwMHna1TmJWesCNpOgYc3f4ZTVFfBfqU71IiOD6Evved6BKe96RTZndR-zrNCKlYg__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026337&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig8.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">Comparison of the profile corresponding to the SL+WL solution (after 8000 Iterations) with two NFW models found in the literature, and that fit their corresponding solutions (Broadhurst et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib6\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib6\" data-open=\"bib6\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005a</a>; Limousin et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib31\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib31\" data-open=\"bib31\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2007</a>).
