The profiles are centred in the type-cD galaxy.</p></div></div><p class=\"chapter-para\">In Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig9\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig9\" data-open=\"fig9\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">9</a>, we compare the radial mass profile derived from our solution with previously published results of A1689 based on different lensing techniques. In the SL regime, our solution overlaps well with the SL modelling results of Broadhurst et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib7\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib7\" data-open=\"bib7\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005b</a>). Our results are also in good agreement with the model-independent mass profile of Umetsu et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib49\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib49\" data-open=\"bib49\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2011</a>) derived from combined WL shear-and-magnification measurements based on the Subaru data. When compared with previous work, we find a good agreement between our solution and other solutions, in terms of the profile and the location and shape of the radial critical curve, although the tangential critical curve we obtain extends further to the south than previous SL solutions.</p>                        <a id=\"21026339\" scrollto-destination=\"21026339\"></a>\r\n<div data-id=\"fig9\" class=\"fig fig-section js-fig-section\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 9.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig9.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&amp;Signature=jz6azIrHneics30B~ruNYJjo7zOoSXj-nPjqa1zedj4Qw~QPIKlVflzZbL3gl8e3obTVT9WSXZAVuQbgqPr8J0mTY8xmKvEd78loLmJJGD8CjhiSfjyDtOqymILL4bfQvegG6yVV5RqjoY0BjldtzhbSZqiiFUIkM3vaIYhxI6YaFUNDBOwVJ44BuCx2agxV~eX9uVd2~nJ26YjS2A1W6k8Am12GjO5Tje67JXUuAGwJQpQqGd4eCtO4wri1XaUWWtHPnXNoelG02haD~W-h94P5SXOWPQZyIwKQGeqlmaYzSxUd8X7-PpYRc6LWfksbT2bkVsbE7IvuT5Kh-8zORg__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Comparison of the profiles from our solution (grey region from Table\u00a01) with previous results from the literature. The profiles are centred in the type-cD galaxy.</p></div></div>                    <h3 scrollto-destination=21026340 id=\"21026340\" class=\"section-title js-splitscreen-section-title\" data-legacy-id=sec5-2>5.2 Mass-to-light ratios</h3>\r\n<p class=\"chapter-para\">To compute the stellar masses and luminosities, rather than relying on magnitudes for a given aperture, we compute the stellar mass and luminosity associated with each pixel in our field of view. Obviously, the pixels containing galaxies not in the cluster have their stellar masses wrongly estimated but we can mask these regions out later on in our analysis. We compute the \u2018<em>B</em>-Johnson\u2019 luminosity of the cluster galaxies on a pixel-by-pixel basis using the new version of the Bayesian Photometric Redshifts (<span class=\"small-caps\">bpz</span>; Ben\u00edtez <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib3\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib3\" data-open=\"bib3\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2000</a>) software. We assume that all galaxies (pixels) have the same redshift and assign to each pixel of the image one of the <span class=\"small-caps\">bpz</span> templates based on their ACS colours. We then calculate the absolute magnitude in the Vega-calibrated Johnson \u2018<em>B</em> band\u2019, using the <em>F</em>814<em>W</em> magnitude and the inferred spectra type. The stellar masses for each pixel are also calculated from the <span class=\"small-caps\">bpz</span> fits to each pixel, using the relationship between rest frame (<em>g</em>\u2212<em>i</em>) colour and stellar mass of Taylor et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib47\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib47\" data-open=\"bib47\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2011</a>).</p><p class=\"chapter-para\">Since our mass model has the galaxy member component differentiated from the diffuse dark matter halo component, we can compute light-to-mass ratios at the position of the member galaxies. The total mass in the galaxies is computed from our reconstructed solution by multiplying the fiducial mass map by the corresponding <em>C</em><sub>1</sub> and <em>C</em><sub>2</sub> factors of the derived solution. The stellar mass can be computed in the same regions after applying a mask that is equal to the footprint of our assumed mass map for the fiducial galaxies. At the same time, we can compute ratios between the total mass derived from our lensing analysis and the stellar mass in the same field of view (without applying any mask or restricting ourselves to particular galaxies).</p><p class=\"chapter-para\">The mass-to-light ratio oscillates around a typical value of \u223c20 for most of the galaxies, with a small decrease towards the central galaxy. In particular, we find a mass-to-light ratio of <em>M</em>/<em>L</em><sub><em>B</em></sub>\u00a0=\u00a021\u00a0\u00b1\u00a014 inside the <em>r</em>\u00a0&lt;\u00a01 arcmin region that drops to <em>M</em>/<em>L</em><sub><em>B</em></sub>\u00a0=\u00a017\u00a0\u00b1\u00a08 inside the <em>r</em>\u00a0&lt;\u00a040 arcsec region. Recently, Okabe et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib39\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib39\" data-open=\"bib39\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2014</a>) found that at large cluster radii, the mass-to-light ratio of subhaloes in the Coma cluster tend to the typical values for clusters (around 200), whereas this ratio decreases towards the centre of the cluster to values around <em>M</em>/<em>L</em><sub><em>B</em></sub>\u00a0\u2248\u00a035 (for <em>h</em>\u00a0=\u00a00.7) (see also, Natarajan et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib36\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib36\" data-open=\"bib36\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2009</a>). When comparing with previous results, our mass-to-light ratios are typically smaller than the ones found in the literature (see for instance Bardeau et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib2\" data-open=\"bib2\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2007</a>; Medezinski et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib33\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib33\" data-open=\"bib33\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2007</a> where they find typical values of about an order of magnitude larger). This is mostly due to the fact that our mass-to-light ratios are computed after averaging the masses and luminosities in the footprint defined by the member galaxies while other authors consider the entire cluster where a significant fraction of the area is not occupied by member galaxies. This is highlighted in Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig10\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig10\" data-open=\"fig10\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">10</a> where the ratio is higher in the region between the member galaxies. Our results are more in line with those derived from isolated systems, (see for instance Jim\u00e9nez-Vicente et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib21\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib21\" data-open=\"bib21\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2014</a> for a recent result where they find significantly smaller stellar to DM mass ratios).</p>                        <a id=\"21026345\" scrollto-destination=\"21026345\"></a>\r\n<div data-id=\"fig10\" class=\"fig fig-section js-fig-section\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 10.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig10.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&amp;Signature=yaDVnEHoHbaXRWP~i3msNiwybOpGkTNvn5v6zannCOvPEfNQ0P7aNruUCJYqAMMFM4oBcZtdERBLLvCLAjG24NvZlNOsrjbm9TW5tD~eY4AzXikVARJozB-3~eguc8OURcbCJWRAAxwKNdCABjwztfKKiRPMbslfCkGGe~4wjptme~9nq74f9DjPeo1a3s-8ssIDlnD0Xo-jqm0ftr1m1ydp89lDLp2RjFVZSSHqu7U8Q2YOHbr71N5-Msc5JeFyDtjOnYmu0nyct~7GFzbTAIoXTQZePqIGWYp92XLkrMdbZPlaEWytA25I7wf1~7FNK6gCFQwX19jvkJYEunUIiw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Ratio of total mass to stellar mass. The field of view is 3.35 arcmin and is centred in the main cD galaxy. The orientation (and scale) is similar to Fig.\u00a01 (right-hand panel).\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig10.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026345/stu2064fig10.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig10.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026345\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig10.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&Signature=V8P1YhGn~cJVy6zv0TCY9mkLW~y4exIcNR7IcrUk5o7bzyrcy2~XGrKp2dRAN702CgsaM-kPSA1IXHMh0FU-Tcfni9SBAFznZqwfheoymcqn-uI9v6tfeCKVJqv9uI~w1rUErWK74ZZ0QQR6jKSr3nIAvMBLunNcf2H05Rk8PN0Se1XoGZtw6nVnYZBPVI8K3XADyOKOl2I8tMjs48TGn1oPJx3a2CLKg8gaKym4tTRU~-6ANNpDlHd3T01nexboChtiikI9kqcZTbNpO6Ve1RBPFqusf5QXD5uvJ~IyPHRnorr-kj82Udn~SspFZ3fGRsrlHHcNRIvlQosMAMw18g__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026345&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig10.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">Ratio of total mass to stellar mass. The field of view is 3.35 arcmin and is centred in the main cD galaxy. The orientation (and scale) is similar to Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig1\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig1\" data-open=\"fig1\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">1</a> (right-hand panel).</p></div></div><div content-id=\"fig10\" class=\"fig fig-modal reveal-modal\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 10.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig10.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&amp;Signature=yaDVnEHoHbaXRWP~i3msNiwybOpGkTNvn5v6zannCOvPEfNQ0P7aNruUCJYqAMMFM4oBcZtdERBLLvCLAjG24NvZlNOsrjbm9TW5tD~eY4AzXikVARJozB-3~eguc8OURcbCJWRAAxwKNdCABjwztfKKiRPMbslfCkGGe~4wjptme~9nq74f9DjPeo1a3s-8ssIDlnD0Xo-jqm0ftr1m1ydp89lDLp2RjFVZSSHqu7U8Q2YOHbr71N5-Msc5JeFyDtjOnYmu0nyct~7GFzbTAIoXTQZePqIGWYp92XLkrMdbZPlaEWytA25I7wf1~7FNK6gCFQwX19jvkJYEunUIiw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Ratio of total mass to stellar mass. The field of view is 3.35 arcmin and is centred in the main cD galaxy. The orientation (and scale) is similar to Fig.\u00a01 (right-hand panel).\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig10.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026345/stu2064fig10.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig10.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026345\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig10.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&Signature=V8P1YhGn~cJVy6zv0TCY9mkLW~y4exIcNR7IcrUk5o7bzyrcy2~XGrKp2dRAN702CgsaM-kPSA1IXHMh0FU-Tcfni9SBAFznZqwfheoymcqn-uI9v6tfeCKVJqv9uI~w1rUErWK74ZZ0QQR6jKSr3nIAvMBLunNcf2H05Rk8PN0Se1XoGZtw6nVnYZBPVI8K3XADyOKOl2I8tMjs48TGn1oPJx3a2CLKg8gaKym4tTRU~-6ANNpDlHd3T01nexboChtiikI9kqcZTbNpO6Ve1RBPFqusf5QXD5uvJ~IyPHRnorr-kj82Udn~SspFZ3fGRsrlHHcNRIvlQosMAMw18g__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026345&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig10.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">Ratio of total mass to stellar mass. The field of view is 3.35 arcmin and is centred in the main cD galaxy. The orientation (and scale) is similar to Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig1\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig1\" data-open=\"fig1\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">1</a> (right-hand panel).</p></div></div><p class=\"chapter-para\">The fact that our critical curves present a smoother form when compared to previous estimations (see for instance Broadhurst et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib7\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib7\" data-open=\"bib7\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005b</a>; Halkola et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib20\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib20\" data-open=\"bib20\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2006</a>; Limousin et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib31\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib31\" data-open=\"bib31\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2007</a>; Coe et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib11\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib11\" data-open=\"bib11\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2010</a>) while the total mass inside the Einstein radius is consistent with previous work, is suggesting that the masses associated with the individual galaxies in our solution are smaller than the corresponding masses derived from alternative methods. The mass-to-light ratio inferred from our solution is therefore probably smaller than the one that could be derived from those alternative methods.</p><p class=\"chapter-para\">Regarding the DM to stellar mass ratios, Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig10\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig10\" data-open=\"fig10\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">10</a> shows the ratio (in log-scale) between the derived total mass from lensing and the inferred stellar mass from the <em>F</em>814<em>W</em> band. The map of the ratio has been smoothed with a Gaussian of FWHM = 6.3\u2009arcsec to reduce the noise fluctuations but also to reduce the impact of background sources and other galaxies not included in our fiducial mass model. The smallest ratios (dark regions) correspond to bright galaxies in the outer regions of the cluster and that were not included in our fiducial model. The highest ratios correspond to regions in the cluster with no significant emission in the <em>F</em>814<em>W</em> band but that have DM in our lens model. Note the gradient at the centre of the main cluster and subcluster in the north-east towards lower ratio values indicating that, as expected, the fraction of baryons with respect to the DM is higher in these regions.</p>                    <h2 scrollto-destination=21026348 id=\"21026348\" class=\"section-title js-splitscreen-section-title\" data-legacy-id=sec6>6 COSMOLOGICAL IMPLICATIONS</h2>\r\n<div class=\"&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            \">Gravitational lensing in well-studied clusters like A1689 can be used to impose constraints in the cosmological model (see for instance Jullo et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib23\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib23\" data-open=\"bib23\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2010</a>). A test based on the relative differences of the deflection angle between pairs of images was applied to A1689 in Broadhurst et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib7\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib7\" data-open=\"bib7\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005b</a>) based on the solution obtained with a parametric model. Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig11\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig11\" data-open=\"fig11\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">11</a> shows the function <em>f</em><sub><em>k</em></sub> as described in Broadhurst et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib7\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib7\" data-open=\"bib7\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005b</a>, see equations 7 and 14 in that paper). <div class=\"formula-wrap\"><div class=\"disp-formula\" id=\"equ4\" content-id=\"equ4\"><div class=\"tex-math display-math\"> \\begin{equation}\r\nf_k = \\frac{D_{{\\rm ls}}(z)D_{\\rm s}(z_{\\rm s}=2)}{D_{\\rm s}(z)D_{{\\rm ls}}(z_{\\rm s}=2)},\r\n\\end{equation} </div></div><span class=\"label\">(4)</span></div>where <em>D</em><sub>ls</sub>(<em>z</em>) is the angular diameter distance from the lens to the source and <em>D</em><sub>s</sub> is the angular diameter distance to the source.</div>                        <a id=\"21026350\" scrollto-destination=\"21026350\"></a>\r\n<div data-id=\"fig11\" class=\"fig fig-section js-fig-section\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 11.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig11.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&amp;Signature=ntTKCM0ta2kGvU-utH1tF5XDoeF93oSUCqk3F77m1ukT3hC2KXGe2R9DC6qPtkQPt9Fcq62uoh8dVFJS5UGZMWC3oq18io0RyOtjHCtw6LDGTmUFRo3rheJtXJKfz8rHpx77vPP9xFrOV-~PG2moXecRdV-hmWp7rRKM5eR4cdYGBpZVc4Px4XbG4o1umQQTyXAeFWZpTa9y3nd19Mg~2kfuq8V8HHeqWw-6L-Ets65VOoj45Blj0pS~78AiBhPafxzf-V8z80PNYqhKrFV25oyclbWm6C-NOI3byTmaZInJgWHRDMf-SdsBG-3r0TY9Gi9mxrmYiW9KkpGt~elPOg__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"The dashed line corresponds to the function fk for a flat model (\u03a9m\u00a0=\u00a00.3, \u039b\u00a0=\u00a00.7) compared with the data (diamonds correspond to systems with spectroscopic redshifts and crosses to systems with photometric redshifts). The main outliers are marked with their corresponding ID.\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig11.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026350/stu2064fig11.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig11.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026350\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig11.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&Signature=L5Q8P9SkhIk11goiItQ43kq4kiPbF7XOV~LdPBrKxTrQLJEVIi5qFrRsgQK53LQT-uXnHql8B6XybmtJ48LbnNepGw91ZfqztM1wCH3UOxeuPUbyVcIfaPG7jJiNaTpTgeLrUJyi5r9EMLePnmcYFjIkG3XPwyE0IFi9Zd7GdiqDLl1msDeY1lAm~yw7cIk9oqTec-TveJk0DqIpHjbsOT7mgjZhe2FPCKHP-5gi9gRJds03m2voqlxlmaCacRnY9RMcPHueDgMPL2GdqIQjo1ARzr20fR-ljH5N-w2laJcIuSaDq2jegO0AUb97LSWgBnXogETa9-8W7Zv~MGBeQg__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026350&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig11.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">The dashed line corresponds to the function <em>f</em><sub><em>k</em></sub> for a flat model (\u03a9<sub>m</sub>\u00a0=\u00a00.3, \u039b\u00a0=\u00a00.7) compared with the data (diamonds correspond to systems with spectroscopic redshifts and crosses to systems with photometric redshifts). The main outliers are marked with their corresponding ID.</p></div></div><div content-id=\"fig11\" class=\"fig fig-modal reveal-modal\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 11.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig11.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&amp;Signature=ntTKCM0ta2kGvU-utH1tF5XDoeF93oSUCqk3F77m1ukT3hC2KXGe2R9DC6qPtkQPt9Fcq62uoh8dVFJS5UGZMWC3oq18io0RyOtjHCtw6LDGTmUFRo3rheJtXJKfz8rHpx77vPP9xFrOV-~PG2moXecRdV-hmWp7rRKM5eR4cdYGBpZVc4Px4XbG4o1umQQTyXAeFWZpTa9y3nd19Mg~2kfuq8V8HHeqWw-6L-Ets65VOoj45Blj0pS~78AiBhPafxzf-V8z80PNYqhKrFV25oyclbWm6C-NOI3byTmaZInJgWHRDMf-SdsBG-3r0TY9Gi9mxrmYiW9KkpGt~elPOg__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"The dashed line corresponds to the function fk for a flat model (\u03a9m\u00a0=\u00a00.3, \u039b\u00a0=\u00a00.7) compared with the data (diamonds correspond to systems with spectroscopic redshifts and crosses to systems with photometric redshifts). The main outliers are marked with their corresponding ID.\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig11.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026350/stu2064fig11.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig11.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026350\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig11.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&Signature=L5Q8P9SkhIk11goiItQ43kq4kiPbF7XOV~LdPBrKxTrQLJEVIi5qFrRsgQK53LQT-uXnHql8B6XybmtJ48LbnNepGw91ZfqztM1wCH3UOxeuPUbyVcIfaPG7jJiNaTpTgeLrUJyi5r9EMLePnmcYFjIkG3XPwyE0IFi9Zd7GdiqDLl1msDeY1lAm~yw7cIk9oqTec-TveJk0DqIpHjbsOT7mgjZhe2FPCKHP-5gi9gRJds03m2voqlxlmaCacRnY9RMcPHueDgMPL2GdqIQjo1ARzr20fR-ljH5N-w2laJcIuSaDq2jegO0AUb97LSWgBnXogETa9-8W7Zv~MGBeQg__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026350&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig11.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">The dashed line corresponds to the function <em>f</em><sub><em>k</em></sub> for a flat model (\u03a9<sub>m</sub>\u00a0=\u00a00.3, \u039b\u00a0=\u00a00.7) compared with the data (diamonds correspond to systems with spectroscopic redshifts and crosses to systems with photometric redshifts). The main outliers are marked with their corresponding ID.</p></div></div><p class=\"chapter-para\">This function is normalized for convenience to <em>z</em>\u00a0=\u00a02 and the shape is determined by the cosmological model. Each data point correspond to a multiply lensed system (out of our set of 26). Due to the more unprecise reconstruction in the very centre of the cluster, we exclude images that are at a distance of 5 arcsec or less from the centre. Diamonds correspond to the spectroscopic redshift systems and cross symbols to those with only photometric redshifts. The dashed line indicates the expected behaviour of our data points for a standard cosmological model (flat \u039bCDM model with \u03a9<sub>m</sub>\u00a0=\u00a00.3). In the ideal scenario where there is no projection effects and we are able to reconstruct the deflection field perfectly, the data points would lie perfectly along the curve for the correct choice of cosmological model. Some scatter is seen here about this expected relation. The symmetry of the scatter indicates that the deflection field we recover is not noise free and imperfections and projection effects along the line of sight unrelated to the cluster must at some level limit the accuracy of this comparison. However, it is important to notice that our result is obtained with just one cluster and is not optimized for in terms of the \u2018best\u2019 multiply lensed systems. For instance, three systems are marked in the above plot that depart more significantly from the expected theoretical behaviour. System number 3 corresponds to a system with only a photometric redshift (and this redshift might be wrong) and besides, two of the images of this system are relatively close to each other (this close proximity of course enhances the uncertainty in estimating <em>f</em><sub><em>k</em></sub> for such systems) and the third image is basically buried behind one of the large elliptical galaxies (and hence very sensitive to the exact mass distribution of this member galaxy at a level not incorporated in our member galaxy model. A similar situation is found in system 21, where two radial images are close to the centre (although farther than the 5 arcsec exclusion radius mentioned above) and one of them is very close to one of the member elliptical galaxies. System 14 corresponds to a system that lies well beyond the Einstein radius, where our reconstruction is less well constrained. It is obvious from the above plot that a more accurate description of the lens (for instance through the addition of new spectroscopic systems, especially at high redshift) would permit a tighter constraint on the cosmological model. A study based on stacking <em>f</em><sub><em>k</em></sub> for many lensing clusters should be able to provide competitive constraints on the cosmological model based on this potentially important independent test, for which some simulations have been explored (Lubini et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib32\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib32\" data-open=\"bib32\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2014</a>).</p>                    <h2 scrollto-destination=21026352 id=\"21026352\" class=\"section-title js-splitscreen-section-title\" data-legacy-id=sec7>7 VARIABILITY OF THE POSSIBLE SOLUTIONS</h2>\r\n<p class=\"chapter-para\">We refer to the best-fitting model presented above as our <em>reference solution</em> since in the context of this form of modelling there is no single unique solution, given that the number of lensed images and the grid resolution are finite. So more important than finding a statistically <em>best</em> solution is to understand the range of possible solutions that are consistent with the data. Hence, as discussed in previous papers (Diego et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib14\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib14\" data-open=\"bib14\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005a</a>, <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib15\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib15\" data-open=\"bib15\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005b</a>, <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib16\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib16\" data-open=\"bib16\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2007</a>; Ponente &amp; Diego <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib41\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib41\" data-open=\"bib41\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2011</a>; Sendra et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib44\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib44\" data-open=\"bib44\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2014</a>), we intentionally seek an approximate solution to the system of equations. A major mistake in this form of modelling is to adopt a grid of higher resolution than justified by the number of lensed images. In this limit, we may obtain what appear to be a near-perfect solution that matches identically the locations of all lensed images but at the expense of a mass distribution that is much more highly structured on small scales that is physically reasonable, including negative surface densities. Such forced solutions tend to predict sources (in the source plane) that are unreasonably small and concentrated together in the centre of the field of view corresponding to huge lens magnifications. This overfitting regime can be avoided by appreciating that uncertainties in the data and the approximations made by our non-parametric reconstruction means that a minimal, inevitable level of error must be allowed in the reconstruction. This includes our assumptions and approximations introduced from our hypothesis that the member galaxy deflections are strictly proportional to the light, and that the soft component can be exactly modelled by a superposition of Gaussians of a given pixel scale, or that the sources in the source plane are delta functions, or that there are no significant projection effects of matter along the line of sight etc.</p><p class=\"chapter-para\">As our input catalogue, we consider first a reliable set of 26 robust strongly lensed systems in which we have great faith. Some of these systems have only photometric redshifts which can be imprecise. Changing the SL (or WL) data set has an impact on the reconstructed solution as the constraints in the system change accordingly. Additional sources of uncertainty in the final solution are related to the particular choice of the initial guess in the minimization process or the number of iterations of the algorithm. In this section, we explore these sources of variability.</p>                    <h3 scrollto-destination=21026355 id=\"21026355\" class=\"section-title js-splitscreen-section-title\" data-legacy-id=sec7-1>7.1 Dependence with iteration number</h3>\r\n<p class=\"chapter-para\">The number of iterations determine some of the properties of the solution (see Sendra et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib44\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib44\" data-open=\"bib44\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2014</a> for details). Adding the fiducial deflection field helps in solving some known issues with non-parametric methods like regularization and the overfitting problem. Nevertheless, overfitting can still occur if the number of iterations is too large so the algorithm always needs to be stopped after a given number of iterations. Using the location of the radial critical curves is a sensitive choice for identifying an optimal range for the number of iterations, as the radius of this critical curve is well defined in the data as it can be seen to be fairly circular in shape from the distribution of very radially extended images. This is not the case for the tangential critical curve.</p><p class=\"chapter-para\">In this paper, this part of the analysis is done a posteriori. However, it could be in principle incorporated into the system of linear equations, however, this is beyond the scope of this work and will be studied in more detail in a future paper, see however Cacciato et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib8\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib8\" data-open=\"bib8\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2006</a>) and Merten et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib34\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib34\" data-open=\"bib34\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2009</a>) where the critical curves are directly used as constraints. In Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig12\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig12\" data-open=\"fig12\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">12</a>, we show three solutions corresponding to three different numbers of iterations (where the number of parameters fitted and the initial condition in the minimization are identical between these three solutions). From left to right, we show the solutions obtained after 5000, 8000 and 15\u00a0000 iterations. By looking at the tangential curves, the three cases look different but they still accommodate well the large tangential arcs in between the tangential critical curve. The radial curve, on the other hand, when compared with the position of key well-identified radial arcs, is clearly too large in the case of 5000 iterations and too small in the case of 15\u00a0000 iterations. In contrast, in the case of 8000 iterations, the radial critical curve (computed for <em>z</em>\u00a0=\u00a02) overlaps almost perfectly with the mean position of different radial arcs present in the cluster at redshifts <em>z</em>\u00a0\u2248\u00a02. This simple comparison seems to indicate that the best solutions are obtained with our code after \u223c8000 iterations. Using the radial critical curve as a way of determining the optimal range of iterations can be also seen as a regularization of our problem. This is an interesting alternative since it is solely based on actual data.</p>                        <a id=\"21026358\" scrollto-destination=\"21026358\"></a>\r\n<div data-id=\"fig12\" class=\"fig fig-section js-fig-section\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 12.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig12.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&amp;Signature=AmtGC96h9p8GXF8zXGBTepjfGyOF3mPv2hzcCZvl6zy5zeWaUL1-p9yPZX~FJEoPUfog3WKX-WXwYYJkXyrUs4a9N1qDr7mLWRiHSofe6s0IgvTTnFR-fDtykSy07h1D3ZICPxTy7LCSX3K1bcJ7NzJaiJ17EEadzVsK8LZjnW3MtE1OLd3RaL-DOTgZRY7a9SeDFnT~O84FhlLl-1Kl8i0OQDPF8OF0Afh3Kw016nOJPYVCPsZWI9YkNNoqFVF34EGFyu98ZTYCku5tMqBemwDZi4pqg16KpSKIetks4HPflT9l-u1UkvtEhUl~DhGnoUWX-VwE81IaS-tN4eSCNQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Solutions (and associated critical curves for a source at redshift z\u00a0=\u00a02) for three different iteration numbers. Left corresponds to 5000 iterations, middle to 8000 iterations and right to 15\u00a0000 iterations. Note how for 8000 iterations both radial and tangential critical curves fall very close to radial and tangential arcs.\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig12.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026358/stu2064fig12.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig12.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026358\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig12.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&Signature=UyxYfYzzPciWm-NeDfa1AmhuBDQryRko38XlAAmZbV0Ek~bOY0lIvaMo64jZqD55P8fmN2Btne5iYSxTKdmdTSIGL3mRzM1T-pFdzIER712ZDfcTU7MJNCQT1Ym3CxcalAoTIpeu2cD0BaBp3FrjMKt1N1dxMrQz4HCRL261ARoBD8EL9ljoroCn0y2tDvVs8n7NomcdUryxrYQZwix1ZP6XYhGrzH6HZDqQWeVv~yizboBShoi5OCGN~f~X~hzFan9f5PqetvfQ2hVat4tjeIrm1IeN3XB2CysLpQZxK63zLVWlTurDG7zSaECVLq6aCdDYWa3jwELN6J3~ozlngA__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026358&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig12.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">Solutions (and associated critical curves for a source at redshift <em>z</em>\u00a0=\u00a02) for three different iteration numbers. Left corresponds to 5000 iterations, middle to 8000 iterations and right to 15\u00a0000 iterations. Note how for 8000 iterations both radial and tangential critical curves fall very close to radial and tangential arcs.</p></div></div><p class=\"chapter-para\">An idea of the dependence of the solution with the number of iterations can be obtained also from Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig13\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig13\" data-open=\"fig13\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">13</a>. In the top part of this plot, we represent the total mass contained in the grid (solid line) versus the iteration number. The solid and dashed lines represent the correction factors C<sub>1</sub> and C<sub>2</sub>, that are applied to the fiducial deflection fields from the galaxies. As the iteration number grows, there is a trade between the mass contained in the grid, and the mass in the galaxies but the total mass (especially in the central region) stays more or less constant beyond a few thousand iterations as can be seen better from the profiles (Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig14\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig14\" data-open=\"fig14\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">14</a>). A similar trend was observed when applying the method to simulated data (Sendra et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib44\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib44\" data-open=\"bib44\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2014</a>). As the iteration number grows, the solution increases its complexity in order to concentrate the arcs into smaller sources. As the fiducial field has only two degrees of freedom (<em>C</em><sub>1</sub> and <em>C</em><sub>2</sub>), new features appear only in the grid part of the solution at the expense of reducing the mass in the member galaxies to keep the total mass more or less constant (within the Einstein radius). Of course, and as mentioned earlier, to avoid overfitting, the minimization process has to be stopped at some point (stopping the minimization after a number of iterations could be seen also as a regularization process). In the range of iterations (6000\u201310\u00a0000) where reliable solutions exist, the changes in the model are small in the central 4 arcmin region. It is also important to note that the increased rise in mass in the grid part of the solution after 2000 iterations (see Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig13\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig13\" data-open=\"fig13\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">13</a>) is driven mostly by the cells in the outermost region (beyond the Einstein radius).</p>                        <a id=\"21026360\" scrollto-destination=\"21026360\"></a>\r\n<div data-id=\"fig13\" class=\"fig fig-section js-fig-section\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 13.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig13.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&amp;Signature=y-PB-kWCoTvQ1OnF0zMg6zoQ7ClY7SvDv~kaa31Px4K-V8Jbt3qlt7qoIzr7Ani32wnjYwOQXWVR4Frnnj9oYmi3Yh3IhG2fE8~fdYGurE5LZOFAcXXDkVdfqwxXTqz1tk-2hnfAtUzVtvfIlWkR7k-z~Wo-peTHacxU-xENQ-wDbF8EJZzGTmL-vrvN73yIH0G-iE0xQRWCM5hIjOLAebDsZc7GlyvIyKZq4CrJkCpwD1sF5aOP2kWeJ4ta-pYzhx-78bMvFFaAuYnlCRcUV-vD7fSXqx5iuZ59QX0yqrAb-WCFGjVr7UAbkj2yD27WIFoOUGssbN0OuKqHHue9zw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Top panel: total mass in the grid (solid line) versus iteration number (from 1 to 15\u00a0000). Again, the smaller subplot shows the tails of these distributions across the transition phase and up the 5\u2009arcmin maximum radius.\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig14.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026361/stu2064fig14.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig14.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026361\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig14.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&Signature=NfgI3yS4iMbwVDuiljEWAPSyNdzH~mgpK3DM~gJxaJSivoiEnr3OOs5LTRziiWVOwXH6PhjYr1u4XrzAtnhQV06qLyrfk~kofJn3PcgiqKZdcLLzeTWFPhEF4XkXLpyUoXr7ZLFSycISrMBvLmtl5NxKqwErOLFShifTOw~EAkHNltlpxg0aUgvMcEshQTcmM-6sPZFCC6Vn~flymVqV4NDBP6e3gJGZTNZGyfPoaVOCr7rDSOCxiKeRvWq~YKPa7Od~kBguhIoxEaW45thqLlREBmqA22v8-28Wk2X3SiDdvZlDZ5bYTeRSxhPcV79RvGooF-kLMcrAVbv8qeEgGg__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026361&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig14.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">Convergence profiles for the three cases shown in Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig12\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig12\" data-open=\"fig12\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">12</a>. The solid line corresponds to the 5000 iteration case, the dotted line to the 8000 iteration case and dashed line to the 15000 iteration case. Again, the smaller subplot shows the tails of these distributions across the transition phase and up the 5\u2009arcmin maximum radius.</p></div></div><div content-id=\"fig14\" class=\"fig fig-modal reveal-modal\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 14.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig14.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&amp;Signature=Tzg4XZ6n2nEj1s2hB3OLhIld4t24d3yZr287hv3mxZr2xlYJOiOvdc4TCoRnXX1F~ZF0wfsnDAW2C81ZAsh6YH2Wi3GgDMAm8mTl4Az6riVSMyBl6R3QljrhLAhnpNonaCCpo9XslmmUcr3BdtySjFviCUNAsprMAVc9GGZ2ZWRwI0xajIukoaSdnrosJtyqFKkmBfzABluKa2Opr53WhQGo9Qt89~tf4dapTLmCyGk5CqqI0b34JQX5iAGYG450EM89UgpR5Ha5mlLtElvoH2DL0p0QwBDLqCqZFSv5Uk1vzixkN6eUlutN2FTCdk6pQ6gfa7W9pU94K-isAI9lVQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Convergence profiles for the three cases shown in Fig.\u00a012. The solid line corresponds to the 5000 iteration case, the dotted line to the 8000 iteration case and dashed line to the 15000 iteration case. Again, the smaller subplot shows the tails of these distributions across the transition phase and up the 5\u2009arcmin maximum radius.\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig14.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026361/stu2064fig14.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig14.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026361\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig14.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&Signature=NfgI3yS4iMbwVDuiljEWAPSyNdzH~mgpK3DM~gJxaJSivoiEnr3OOs5LTRziiWVOwXH6PhjYr1u4XrzAtnhQV06qLyrfk~kofJn3PcgiqKZdcLLzeTWFPhEF4XkXLpyUoXr7ZLFSycISrMBvLmtl5NxKqwErOLFShifTOw~EAkHNltlpxg0aUgvMcEshQTcmM-6sPZFCC6Vn~flymVqV4NDBP6e3gJGZTNZGyfPoaVOCr7rDSOCxiKeRvWq~YKPa7Od~kBguhIoxEaW45thqLlREBmqA22v8-28Wk2X3SiDdvZlDZ5bYTeRSxhPcV79RvGooF-kLMcrAVbv8qeEgGg__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026361&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig14.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">Convergence profiles for the three cases shown in Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig12\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig12\" data-open=\"fig12\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">12</a>. The solid line corresponds to the 5000 iteration case, the dotted line to the 8000 iteration case and dashed line to the 15000 iteration case. Again, the smaller subplot shows the tails of these distributions across the transition phase and up the 5\u2009arcmin maximum radius.</p></div></div><p class=\"chapter-para\">It can also be seen (see the inset in the upper-right corner of Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig14\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig14\" data-open=\"fig14\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">14</a>) that as the iteration number grows, the grid starts to accumulate mass in the transition phase between the 6.66\u2009arcmin region and the buffer zone. The bottom panel of Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig13\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig13\" data-open=\"fig13\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">13</a> shows the quantity that is being minimized (properly re-scaled by some constant for clarity) as a function of the iteration number.</p><p class=\"chapter-para\">When looking at how the mass evolves in the different cells as a function of the iteration number, we observe that the central regions converge first and the outer regions converge last. The region around the buffer zone starts to monotonically grow in mass after a few thousand iterations. For a very large iteration number, the inner region stays stable and most of the changes in mass occur beyond the Einstein radius.</p>                    <h3 scrollto-destination=21026364 id=\"21026364\" class=\"section-title js-splitscreen-section-title\" data-legacy-id=sec7-2>7.2 Dependence with the initial guess</h3>\r\n<p class=\"chapter-para\">When minimizing a multidimensional quadratic function, one can find infinite solutions (for a given error) by varying the starting point of the minimization, all of them equally good in the sense of fitting the data set. The regions in the lens plane that are more sensitive to the data will converge quickly towards stationary points while regions with weaker sensitivity to the data might vary more from minimization to minimization or even not vary significantly and retain values close to their initial values (memory effect).</p><p class=\"chapter-para\">In Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig15\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig15\" data-open=\"fig15\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">15</a>, we show the average (solid) and 1\u03c3 region (dotted) of 40 reconstructions where in each one we change the initial condition by setting it to a vector of random numbers obtained from a Gaussian distribution. The dispersion of this Gaussian distribution is a random variable itself and is such that the total mass in the initial condition takes values in the range [\u223c0.2, \u223c2]\u00a0\u00d7\u00a010<sup>15</sup>\u2009M<sub>\u2299</sub>\u2009<em>h</em><sup>\u22121</sup>. Table\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-tbl1\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"tbl1\" data-open=\"tbl1\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">1</a> includes the values of the mean and errors as a function of distance. The solution retains some memory of the initial condition specially in the outer region where the constraints in the solution are the weakest. The most remarkable aspect of this plot is that all solutions seem to converge to the same profile in the range 20\u201330\u2009arcsec defining a <em>stability</em> region for the solution.</p>                        <a id=\"21026367\" scrollto-destination=\"21026367\"></a>\r\n<div content-id=\"tbl1\" class=\"table-modal table-full-width-wrap\"><div class=\"table-wrap table-wide\"><div class=\"table-wrap-title\" id=\"tbl1\" data-id=\"tbl1\"><span class=\"label\">Table 1.</span><div class=\"caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">Mean profile and dispersion of the 40 solutions shown in Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig15\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig15\" data-open=\"fig15\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">15</a>. Both the mean profile and dispersion are given in units of \u03a3/\u03a3<sub>crit</sub> with \u03a3<sub>crit</sub> computed at <em>z</em>\u00a0=\u00a01.07. The last column shows the integrated (cylindrical) mass in units of 10<sup>14</sup>\u2009M<sub>\u2299</sub>\u2009<em>h</em><sup>\u22121</sup>.</p></div> </div><div ble></div><div class=\"&#xA;          graphic-wrap&#xA;          \"><a class=\"fig-view-orig openInAnotherWindow btn js-view-large\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"/view-large/21026367\">\r\n          Open in new tab\r\n        </a></div></div></div><p class=\"chapter-para\">This convergence is made more evident when looking at the 2D version of the above result. In Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig16\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig16\" data-open=\"fig16\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">16</a> , we show the average of the mass solutions (left-hand panel) from which the above profile is derived. The middle panel shows the dispersion of the mass map and the right-hand panel shows the signal-to-noise ratio (or SNR) defined as the ratio of the left-hand and middle panels. There is a remarkably well-defined circular region of high SNR around 20\u201330\u2009arcsec from the centre. In this region, the solutions seem to be insensitive to the initial condition and they all render almost identical results. This region corresponds to a stability region of the solution where the profile is constrained very well. A second interesting aspect can be seen also in the SNR map. The high SNR of the DM blob (SNR\u00a0\u2248\u00a016), just south of the stability region (i.e the bright blob approximately 2.5 arcmin from the centre of the image on the right-hand panel of Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig16\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig16\" data-open=\"fig16\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">16</a>), indicates that this might be a real substructure. This feature has not been previously claimed and indeed parametric methods would not incorporate such dark substructure in principle. Other interesting features emerge from the SNR map as potential real substructures of the cluster although with a lower SNR. The dispersion map shows how there is a region (upper-right quadrant) where the solutions fluctuate the most indicating that the mass map is less reliable in this region.</p>                        <a id=\"21026369\" scrollto-destination=\"21026369\"></a>\r\n<div data-id=\"fig15\" class=\"fig fig-section js-fig-section\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 15.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig15.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&amp;Signature=JuM9LUxISM-GdNpDfcOD93~sdusO~hoPrHzBc07RqLqzoisDlocLyIT56CTgHj78tcUj9ks3FTjKPHuRFrzeql3Knptu14l1i2NxIoNTAO1H80OeDSuwLOoj~dZAmecjx0yTlWIDWURPvra-BxXV-ricM2u5lIpHoDYplO2Ylu-70iPzgbNhlxhRCEmZ9PnLBGm3Y22xfHR1CtaXgZbWCIrlhmkh~WnCR4GVR5cqWD5vPWRmwdrWR4PHV6csiM03I2v6ZjeMfMtE8R5XLsnqlkXJfnMvivE~iLatzlHESLdTrlOF-sZYlZSpUChHJ5sq1jjJrH-WRshFmwb5R3LqHQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Average profile of the convergence from 40 independent solutions (solid line). The middle panel shows the dispersion of these solutions. The right-hand panel shows the SNR map defined as the average map (left-hand panel) divided by the dispersion map (middle panel). The SNR vary between SNR = 0.7 at its minimum and SNR = 290 at its maximum (but saturated in this plot above SNR = 100). All maps are shown as the square root (in order to increase contrast) and the colour scale (shown in the right-hand panel) is the same in all panels.</p></div></div><p class=\"chapter-para\">Finally, as expected (and already shown in the profile plot), the dispersion of the solutions in the central region (that is, around the cD galaxy) is larger, indicating therefore that our solution is not very sensitive to the very central region. This is due mostly to the fact that the larger arcs have a bigger weight in our solution. In a future paper, we aim to study in more detail the most central region taking advantage of the stability region identified in this paper, and the possible implications for the mass profile of the cD galaxy.</p>                    <h3 scrollto-destination=21026372 id=\"21026372\" class=\"section-title js-splitscreen-section-title\" data-legacy-id=sec7-3>7.3 Dependence with the number of systems and redshift</h3>\r\n<p class=\"chapter-para\">Identifying pairs of images in the SL regime is not always free of subjectivity, resting on experience. A1689 is probably the most scrutinized lens, with hundreds of arclets seen in the image, each with its own distortion that makes it difficult to find morphologically similar galaxies. The colours may also vary across the object due to differential magnification, and also because of overlap with other unrelated images or due to diffuse light in the cluster affecting the colours of relatively faint background galaxies. Spectroscopic redshifts of the arclets are often the best way to discriminate among different possibilities but even this does not always settle the differences and furthermore neighbouring galaxies may become confused in the process if they have the same redshift to within the resolution limits. A good example of this is the difficulty to distinguish between systems 10 and 12 (both having basically the same spectroscopic redshift). Different authors have assigned the arclets to different systems (see Table\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-tbl2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"tbl2\" data-open=\"tbl2\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">A1</a>). In this section, we explore the impact on the solution when we consider different subsets of arclets in our SL part of the data set.</p><p class=\"chapter-para\">In Table\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-tbl2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"tbl2\" data-open=\"tbl2\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">A1</a>, we compile all the systems that were found in the literature and we add several new systems (candidates) which are identified with our model. For the new systems, we simply assume that they are at redshift <em>z</em>\u00a0=\u00a02 when assessing their deflection angles. This is a useful approximation given the weak dependence of the deflection angles over the range <em>z</em>\u00a0=\u00a0[1, 3] (as shown by Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig11\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig11\" data-open=\"fig11\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">11</a>) and should be sufficient for our purposes. For our test, we compare our reference solution described in Section\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-sec5\"></span><a href=\"#sec5\" class=\"sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec\">5</a>, which depended on only the 26 established systems, with new model solutions obtained for sets of images composed in the following three ways. </p><ul class=\"roman-lower\"><li><p class=\"chapter-para\">We consider the extended sample of systems listed in Table\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-tbl2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"tbl2\" data-open=\"tbl2\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">A1</a> but exclude sources 25 and 32 for which multiple options exist for the same system. That is, we consider 48 sources out of the total 50 systems listed in Table\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-tbl2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"tbl2\" data-open=\"tbl2\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">A1</a>.</p></li><li><p class=\"chapter-para\">As a second subsample, we consider the subset of 18 sources from the original 26 sources of our reference solution for which spectroscopic redshifts are available, in Table\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-tbl2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"tbl2\" data-open=\"tbl2\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">A1</a>.</p></li><li><p class=\"chapter-para\">The third subsample is the same as the original sample of 26 but for the sources with photometric redshifts, we allow the redshifts to vary (uniformly) by a generous 2\u03c3 error, adopting the \u03c3 values in Coe et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib11\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib11\" data-open=\"bib11\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2010</a>).</p></li></ul><p class=\"chapter-para\">The extended data set of 48 systems is displayed in Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig17\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig17\" data-open=\"fig17\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">17</a> where the original 26 systems are shown in black and the additional 22 systems in white. For each case, we reproduce the minimization process of Section\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-sec5\"></span><a href=\"#sec5\" class=\"sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec\">5</a> that is, we adopt the same initial condition, number of iterations and make use of both SL and WL data, in order to better examine model differences resulting from changes of the data set. Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig18\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig18\" data-open=\"fig18\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">18</a> shows this comparison in terms of the resulting mass profiles for the above cases.</p>                        <a id=\"21026377\" scrollto-destination=\"21026377\"></a>\r\n<div data-id=\"fig17\" class=\"fig fig-section js-fig-section\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 17.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig17.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&amp;Signature=23b54Co0trHEn669LnqTS5ZKUi2IdrdTwy2oXIBB7RxUDNRUH9~02PiOlykRyAwqRGUAIKD~9LLXZh2tvRLELIeer7QcBnjfb6CtHA2C92X6ou46DjqTYIn0W6op0Zsd3YVmxmcnM-V8Y03M4JfmjP-y88SMnvraiALdOawpjN4rIjWw3Zye-FaAugvom~JILAFvQVeBcTZVALYYPbvMQ~P0pY-bBpNVLyOtR8RQ3~m5uDHxyVBo6YPcRxuCNfzE93bY2Fd1oiQkqFvbpWEBFG~VgdGFGOhwReuyEY3FoWM~SzqozJvn0b2L-M3uteuDjVV2QyUQFb1vPjLDvZQ--g__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"In black, the original robust data set of 26 sources. The solid, dotted, dashed and dot\u2013dashed line have the same meaning as in the top panel.\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig18.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026380/stu2064fig18.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig18.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026380\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig18.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&Signature=cNYeDa~SBXc8o2Bx3l0RaJWX-jAuZG-PhUG4Xscq0wmY2ZExhVlVfzp0tUogUWaeZtRnt3yfw3xkbTsugcMAabJNbavG9lXZ2TfvlYe439tIts1yxxlcq7L7RJle9k3NXujMadV3ecpW5UqlPAZTHqliMslbr5ekTjlCXdeAVh5jIi1te9BYmDumMa7ltxQZRXymxj9ovzeCsTwAhl3y-7D1zhwehVtRyFqDMIegDvwmE798TVXgnHBcPeSIOKrhjVOPYPF8l1yAG0JGsLWBt~6qOyrN4Y0w3bLVW1IYCaQfecJL2JkgJRznWf2D8ZhnAQgyrO02l-QZpN~IyXniQA__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026380&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig18.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">Comparison of the profiles obtained with different subsets of sources. The thick solid line corresponds to our reference solution (26 sources). The dotted line corresponds to the solution obtained with the full sample of in Table\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-tbl2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"tbl2\" data-open=\"tbl2\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">A1</a> (we exclude sources 25 and 32), or case (i) (see text). The dashed line corresponds to the subset with spectroscopic redshifts (18 sources) or case (ii) (see text) and the dot\u2013dashed line corresponds to the same initial set of 26 sources but the sources with photo-<em>z</em> taking different redshifts, or case (iii) (see text). The bottom panel shows the relative difference between the different curves (B) and the reference model (A). The solid, dotted, dashed and dot\u2013dashed line have the same meaning as in the top panel.</p></div></div><div class=\"&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            \">Although there are some differences between the different solutions, the agreement is still remarkably good indicating that all data sets have enough common systems to produce similar results and/or that the solution is not very sensitive to modest changes in the redshift of some systems. This agreement indicates most simply that the systems in the extended sample naturally give good fits when the reference solution is used. The last point is highlighted better in the second last column of Table\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-tbl2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"tbl2\" data-open=\"tbl2\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">A1</a> where we show the \u0394\u03b2 for each arclet (and based on the reference solution). The \u0394\u03b2 for a specific arclet <em>i</em> is defined as <div class=\"formula-wrap\"><div class=\"disp-formula\" id=\"equ5\" content-id=\"equ5\"><div class=\"tex-math display-math\"> \\begin{equation}\r\n\\Delta \\beta _i(\\mathrm{arcsec}) = |\\beta _i - \\langle \\beta \\rangle |,\r\n\\end{equation} </div></div><span class=\"label\">(5)</span></div>where \u03b2<sub><em>i</em></sub> is the predicted position of the arclet in the source plane when the reference solution is used and \u3008\u03b2\u3009 is the average of all the \u03b2<sub><em>i</em></sub> for that system. As shown by the values of \u0394\u03b2 (expressed in arcseconds), most arclets lie at reasonable distances (few arcseconds) from their common centre in the source plane. Also, some systems appear to be problematic since they have large \u0394\u03b2 values (10\u2009arcsec or more, like in systems 25, 41, 44). These systems are either incorrect or our reference solution has substantial errors around the position of these systems. In other cases, like system 7, the arclet 7.3 (\u0394\u03b2\u00a0=\u00a09.3\u2009arcsec) is very close to the central cD galaxy and surrounded by multiple small sources (7.3, together with 8.5, and 19.5 were also rejected by Coe et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib11\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib11\" data-open=\"bib11\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2010</a>). It is possible that either the reference solution is not accurate at the centre (see discussion in Section\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-sec7-2\"></span><a href=\"#sec7-2\" class=\"sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec\">7.2</a>) or that 7.3 does not correspond with the source listed in Table\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-tbl2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"tbl2\" data-open=\"tbl2\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">A1</a> but another one in the vicinity. If that is the case, this explains why 7.1 and 7.2 (which are clearly the same source), have also relatively high values of \u0394\u03b2 since a bad association for 7.3 would bias \u3008\u03b2\u3009 and enhance the \u0394\u03b2 for all the system.</div><p class=\"chapter-para\">Another interesting point from Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig18\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig18\" data-open=\"fig18\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">18</a>, is that the same stability region discussed in Section\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-sec7-2\"></span><a href=\"#sec7-2\" class=\"sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec\">7.2</a> seems to be present when we change the SL data set, in the range 20\u201330\u2009arcsec, where the solutions seem to be insensitive to the particular choice of data sets (among the four used in this comparison). This reinforces the idea that the solution is very well constrained in this regime (20\u201330\u2009arcsec) and nearly insensitive to the intrinsic variation of the solutions.</p><p class=\"chapter-para\">Going beyond the differences in profile, we look at the mass maps for the above cases, comparing the reference solution and the three solutions described above. The result is shown in Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig19\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig19\" data-open=\"fig19\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">19</a>. In this case, the mass difference has been divided by the profile of the reference solution to increase contrast. Also, the middle panel has been saturated below values of \u22121.7 (the most negative value was \u22125) also for contrast purposes. The difference maps show where the surface mass density modifies itself in order to accommodate the possible changes in the data set and by extension, it marks the regions where extra caution needs to be taken into account when interpreting our main results, should the assumed original data set of 26 sources be compromised by systematics.</p>                        <a id=\"21026384\" scrollto-destination=\"21026384\"></a>\r\n<div data-id=\"fig19\" class=\"fig fig-section js-fig-section\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 19.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig19.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&amp;Signature=eIns0XR2R01fq0cOYyeAJXcNWqKeNnGZL11wYgJdz~3rkULMjpm43ulkiHozqZOIxViHF5Ls27g6XIYVpv4HKMjnXdVjV8qfhWH0Skl6v9vwHXZ6NWx3Qk48hQ82o2FlDp600LAqLFFIwE~rNeOLDOL~RXrT1~QcsaQbfUU8LZUiYmjDuUSkoQ-amH3CxLeP6JqmOWw9zzx4rErrviHHUS1KWiSqF6B~qrxoZZHYnk7w76Ir9qB2llYfTO2aeQbhAK6tqGiVM-6a7lmuD7YtiSEdw7da8Kl9MlfW2kIIfrteNHRwlLgUc5~fweuHvIRYxr6GS773UYGdDOm-NUDRow__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"The figures show the difference between our reference solution and solutions obtained with three alternative subsets of sources. Ideally, we would set a large number of cells that allows for a more detailed reconstruction. In practice however, a very large number of cells results only in a more noisy reconstruction that needs to be smoothed (regularized). The smoothed image captures the main eigenmodes of the solution that would be reconstructed also with a smaller number of cells. Also, a large number of cells implies a larger system of equations to resolve and a slower convergence. This limits the ability to explore the space of possible solutions, which is important. On the other hand, a very small number of cells results in a more compact system of linear equations that can be resolved fast but at the expense of not capturing some of the potentially smaller scale details of the mass distribution and consequently forcing the entire mass distribution to adopt, often erroneous, distributions in order to fit the observations. As shown by Ponente &amp; Diego (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib41\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib41\" data-open=\"bib41\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2011</a>) and Sendra et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib44\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib44\" data-open=\"bib44\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2014</a>), a low-resolution grid can still produce reliable solutions but only after allowing for a larger error in the reconstruction. Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig20\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig20\" data-open=\"fig20\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">20</a> shows the reconstructed solution when a lower resolution grid is used. In this case, all the cell sizes are the same and equal to 25\u00a0\u00d7\u00a025 arcsec<sup>2</sup>. The solution obtained with this regular grid resembles a smoothed version of the reference solution except in the radial critical curve where the lack of resolution does not allow for a detailed reconstruction. In this case, the values of <em>C</em><sub>1</sub> and <em>C</em><sub>2</sub> are 0.26 and 0.23, respectively.</p>                        <a id=\"21026388\" scrollto-destination=\"21026388\"></a>\r\n<div data-id=\"fig20\" class=\"fig fig-section js-fig-section\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 20.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig20.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&amp;Signature=LHs3xp5Edy-CCONoyjqYej2SUEblslzzK-hd6AyCP4HVVICzSod1ApzSdJQgV1RRzhZFMNPtfZTT6ICcOI5VFjw2RxytsmlEtzkN9LuDHg~idm8bG~e3zXwXLv3CG~~JPhL1yJf0q8C46D3hc4NasX~NQVWbqomcerJN75cibperQRy~GW9GOv9UKxV0HwESdaUSYmHZHGjbR7k6z~~BPGDVVvlvn3MQmzXoSNlGWx~waX9lzeSKjCwng253iNsnxossIcvZ6xKBsh12mKHeHl7qJuDUkQ6jHgycmRWdFbuEukkiSaV9Evcvd34cYY8VwPRnqFu8bamdY-Mqaz08~Q__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Mass and critical curve for a low-resolution grid reconstruction (SL+WL). The cell sizes are 2.7\u00a0times larger in this case than in the reference solution.\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig20.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026388/stu2064fig20.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig20.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026388\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig20.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&Signature=xQ6issEApKzX4quZmOobLFVSL8Uct0KvE9lEwmaEuJbW7cywf3frpOGM7Fwmc~4KthR9KbrdPr5vYWpNTENVZIw6nBBRP-NVvS2jTH4drJWoI~TAIXGy6xYW-mXjOT1azhoI~ulaD~~mhURIR7h0Zl6W52sYGjsX1XIsKnjhQCTjXJUZnQh5q0gSGCay~TU4ykx1jXn29B5oTPDPooJanAfCoUxJnsova4EiRDKVxSw6WD4RstPPj4Rwp~Aa5uAzPmS3xksI50Zhyo7VKFfPMsLzt9XEqCtyeX~AK~~NKl6mOOljCE0NQn3SKn4Z4p49To7LnEQgW2VWKzZh4K7lGQ__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026388&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig20.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">Mass and critical curve for a low-resolution grid reconstruction (SL+WL). The cell sizes are 2.7\u00a0times larger in this case than in the reference solution.</p></div></div><div content-id=\"fig20\" class=\"fig fig-modal reveal-modal\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 20.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig20.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&amp;Signature=LHs3xp5Edy-CCONoyjqYej2SUEblslzzK-hd6AyCP4HVVICzSod1ApzSdJQgV1RRzhZFMNPtfZTT6ICcOI5VFjw2RxytsmlEtzkN9LuDHg~idm8bG~e3zXwXLv3CG~~JPhL1yJf0q8C46D3hc4NasX~NQVWbqomcerJN75cibperQRy~GW9GOv9UKxV0HwESdaUSYmHZHGjbR7k6z~~BPGDVVvlvn3MQmzXoSNlGWx~waX9lzeSKjCwng253iNsnxossIcvZ6xKBsh12mKHeHl7qJuDUkQ6jHgycmRWdFbuEukkiSaV9Evcvd34cYY8VwPRnqFu8bamdY-Mqaz08~Q__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Mass and critical curve for a low-resolution grid reconstruction (SL+WL). The cell sizes are 2.7\u00a0times larger in this case than in the reference solution.\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig20.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026388/stu2064fig20.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig20.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026388\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig20.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&Signature=xQ6issEApKzX4quZmOobLFVSL8Uct0KvE9lEwmaEuJbW7cywf3frpOGM7Fwmc~4KthR9KbrdPr5vYWpNTENVZIw6nBBRP-NVvS2jTH4drJWoI~TAIXGy6xYW-mXjOT1azhoI~ulaD~~mhURIR7h0Zl6W52sYGjsX1XIsKnjhQCTjXJUZnQh5q0gSGCay~TU4ykx1jXn29B5oTPDPooJanAfCoUxJnsova4EiRDKVxSw6WD4RstPPj4Rwp~Aa5uAzPmS3xksI50Zhyo7VKFfPMsLzt9XEqCtyeX~AK~~NKl6mOOljCE0NQn3SKn4Z4p49To7LnEQgW2VWKzZh4K7lGQ__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026388&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig20.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">Mass and critical curve for a low-resolution grid reconstruction (SL+WL). The cell sizes are 2.7\u00a0times larger in this case than in the reference solution.</p></div></div><p class=\"chapter-para\">A compromise alternative would be to use a multiresolution grid where regions with a complex mass distribution are sampled with smaller cells and regions with a more smooth mass distribution (or less sensitive to the data) are sampled with larger cells. This possibility was explored in previous papers and produces satisfactory results although it is not entirely free of problems. In particular, the boundary region between regions of differing resolution tends to produce biased results (when tested with simulated data). The size of the cell normally introduces a prior in the solution. The reconstruction tends to put more mass in the smallest cells. This problem can be mitigated by solving in an iterative way where the first iteration assumes a regular grid (no prior) and the consecutive iterations increase the resolution in regions where the previous iteration found more mass. We have tried a battery of configurations and found that some of them (in particular those with multiresolution) produce significant artefacts in the solution that need to be avoided. Regular grids are always more stable and reliable so in our particular case and due to the large field of view involved (10\u00a0\u00d7\u00a010 arcmin<sup>2</sup>) we choose a grid with good resolution in the central field of view (6\u00a0\u00d7\u00a06 arcmin<sup>2</sup>) and a lower resolution grid in the outer region (buffer zone). As expected, the solution near the boundary between the two regions produce artefacts as discussed above. We have checked that variations in the grid sizes of \u223c30\u2009per\u2009cent with respect to our configuration, finding the results are nearly identical to the those presented in this paper. The cell sizes in the central part of the field of view are larger than the halo sizes of the galaxies (except the central galaxy) facilitating the orthogonality of the grid+galaxy base.</p>                    <h3 scrollto-destination=21026390 id=\"21026390\" class=\"section-title js-splitscreen-section-title\" data-legacy-id=sec7-5>7.5 Dependence with the parameters in the fiducial model</h3>\r\n<p class=\"chapter-para\">In order to test the sensitivity of the solution to the assumptions made for the adopted profile for the member galaxy component, we compare the reference solution (solid line in Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig21\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig21\" data-open=\"fig21\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">21</a>) with two different assumptions regarding galaxy profiles. In the first case (dotted line in Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig21\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig21\" data-open=\"fig21\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">21</a>), we vary both the total mass of each galaxy and the scale radius by a factor \u223c2 (above and below the values in the reference solution) so the ratio between the new masses or scale radii with respect to the ones in the reference model is around 2. In the second case (dotted line in Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig21\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig21\" data-open=\"fig21\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">21</a>), we take the extreme (and unrealistic) case where all the masses in the galaxies are considered to be in just the centre of each galaxy (that is, galaxies are considered delta functions) and we also change their masses by a factor \u223c2 with respect to the reference solution case. Remarkably, there is a region of stability (around 20\u201340\u2009arcsec) where the profile seems to be unaffected by the particular choice of the fiducial deflection field, even in the case where we consider unphysical assumptions for the fiducial field (delta function case for the galaxy masses). The dotted line (different NFW profiles for each galaxy) is almost indistinguishable from the reference solution. The dashed line case (delta functions) shows a relative deficit in mass at very short radii, since all the mass of the central galaxy is concentrated at (<em>r</em>\u00a0=\u00a00) which is not shown in the plot. At larger radii (<em>r</em>\u00a0=\u00a050\u2013100\u2009arcsec), the grid part of the solution shows an excess of mass (with respect to the reference solution). This might be due to a compensation effect of the unphysical nature of the delta function assumption although this is not observed at <em>r</em>\u00a0=\u00a020\u201330\u2009arcsec. When finding solutions, we are of course dealing with the deflection field and since this relates to the gradient of the potential we may not be so surprised about the independence of the resulting model mass distribution with the choice of galaxy profile, since the galaxy potential is always extended even in the case of point masses.</p>                        <a id=\"21026392\" scrollto-destination=\"21026392\"></a>\r\n<div data-id=\"fig21\" class=\"fig fig-section js-fig-section\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 21.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig21.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&amp;Signature=u04x59CUkbOuqtMqC8gHJ3uPjCDbo2SveiJ8eoh3opVyVP2V95t4Xgn0rJjX2vUrQO3H5~V0B2QlFZ~bKN6r4yJdZ3TcwFmjGX~fSb8iGIF1DFnoswpog6fCgosbiGMFucc6mBl8fiGcEvKWFQxRtSlaaUUTi58gDZJQv0s7UGj3wEW9mJZRpg54zQ~5CCXNLLEPM9sedKDrUcJ6fqYzAj-XtbJh8GBajIaXmQ6qjAnBV8IHa~JyAWkPOES76ipRnZ8TkkFbZmC9mqq7zjhramUYfxgRNcB3TGL9rQsrQAborkjNSVf-5fLqqZ5VzV4ESCUO98uERgCyRyr0zPRa6g__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Changes in the reconstructed profile under three assumptions for the member galaxies in the cluster. The solid line corresponds to the reference solution discussed above, the dotted line is for a different model where both the scale radius and total mass of the assumed NFW profile for the individual galaxies is changed by a factor \u223c2. The dashed line corresponds to another different realization of the masses in the galaxies (different also by a factor \u223c2 with respect to the reference model) but their profiles are taken to the extreme case of delta functions. For the dashed line, there is a peak at the centre not shown in this plot that corresponds to the central galaxy.\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig21.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026392/stu2064fig21.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig21.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026392\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig21.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&Signature=dqVYK2PyONp5lAcgBRBN25ztT~s6SJLGkmQRZF3zxC10TwhYz7nfmLMY4kFoeGnWe6XFu0kn5rNrqakIOZ5OseNLahQkqnN2kzSig1yG98Y~vOskBp9rkEsD7a~Yw4J1Z9FZxMjx5MD8u79~y-85hAk61OUl7GFY4o9eRgjMQDui-CtfdlH4Q3AZxTrw-L7UWEXwvK04Bqr0BBhW1u1KUQ7I94C~NI81pSOpBJZ37FWAwL6irOS0-RgCraDC6qtvzwNy4C~BV2DDCQYJ8b208U8Q9WcXdYl4DrV62y3ZtjARM1RVY3K9n5XvNtEVRn0zEb4EXuYxTpCTh61GWGC1bg__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026392&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig21.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">Changes in the reconstructed profile under three assumptions for the member galaxies in the cluster. The solid line corresponds to the reference solution discussed above, the dotted line is for a different model where both the scale radius and total mass of the assumed NFW profile for the individual galaxies is changed by a factor \u223c2. The dashed line corresponds to another different realization of the masses in the galaxies (different also by a factor \u223c2 with respect to the reference model) but their profiles are taken to the extreme case of delta functions.
