The left-hand panel shows the entire field of view of 10\u2009arcmin with the SL, reduced shear measurements, the position of the fiducial galaxies and their assumed shapes. The right-hand panel shows a zoom into the central 3.33\u2009arcmin region with the arcs and galaxies that shows better extent of the haloes in our model.</p></div></div><div content-id=\"fig1\" class=\"fig fig-modal reveal-modal\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 1.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig1.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&amp;Signature=lneTrpUGPw1PDKepz0bzmwIQlrsFcZ5h25uYSO7VGcMH7c9spAX-KezicbanHuaf2p8pQNs0IA8ICRWVJ~9Y1Sb033n~PHv~FTBlatgbdFLKtlk5qO8~gWfoJQ7bSYTu7VCLlLkF97mXmqbjXli7a~mKnnskyiM8mNMp4WMp094rK0hWwmVhe~PJBR~g4rVg077fm1dDZLDzBvNfbg2Q6ttxAI503YnF40bmR8xC-5B9PiRt3HBZPFTRjxuUwvZAh0GTdYYgxQQHDXQ2vVGJJAgmvVW3sHP~I8H1rbovlgM2ycRJmUv6L01utiPFnYtTMPWlzeuF1gOb84kxVipAaQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Data set used for the reconstruction. The left-hand panel shows the entire field of view of 10\u2009arcmin with the SL, reduced shear measurements, the position of the fiducial galaxies and their assumed shapes. The right-hand panel shows a zoom into the central 3.33\u2009arcmin region with the arcs and galaxies that shows better extent of the haloes in our model.\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig1.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026314/stu2064fig1.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig1.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026314\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig1.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&Signature=yEwXCuLPH4KERtt7-Au~3kILAUUQPsA6zGRgEO~lrMO3gI0EBNT7F9S6e3phMbZ3QJaOHmloo2hWOSQR-zJ2n1wsjM6xGvskCoEWTfNrER-x4a81R-Qax7B3RDKuc6GP-QfNdYrXIYH6Ch07BbLcHAnoZP8vNFZIPK7wf6zw7bI7PNYCGlC1aNx3DLjYsoYOO9sEGGwZBp0neuULxPXFK1xgufOsu9tzaRom4gM2Mr82IFbesm~61om-c5ydVcZVlN3YYgmhm6QIqgwhlIsAwhKFZc-TNic~jos5C5GZPwJxgSUpONHfgHl~oEPtxy-IWsmD3Pok6aE70RwalvT5-w__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026314&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig1.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">Data set used for the reconstruction. The left-hand panel shows the entire field of view of 10\u2009arcmin with the SL, reduced shear measurements, the position of the fiducial galaxies and their assumed shapes. The right-hand panel shows a zoom into the central 3.33\u2009arcmin region with the arcs and galaxies that shows better extent of the haloes in our model.</p></div></div>                    <h2 scrollto-destination=21026315 id=\"21026315\" class=\"section-title js-splitscreen-section-title\" data-legacy-id=sec4>4 RECONSTRUCTION METHOD</h2>\r\n<p class=\"chapter-para\">We use the improved method, <span class=\"small-caps\">wslap+</span>, to combine the weak and SL data and perform the mass reconstruction. The reader can find the details of the method in our previous papers (Diego et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib14\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib14\" data-open=\"bib14\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005a</a>,<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib15\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib15\" data-open=\"bib15\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">b</a>, <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib16\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib16\" data-open=\"bib16\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2007</a>; Ponente &amp; Diego <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib41\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib41\" data-open=\"bib41\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2011</a>; Sendra et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib44\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib44\" data-open=\"bib44\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2014</a>). Here, we give a brief summary of the most essential elements.</p><div class=\"&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            \">Given the standard lens equation <div class=\"formula-wrap\"><div class=\"disp-formula\" id=\"equ1\" content-id=\"equ1\"><div class=\"tex-math display-math\"> \\begin{equation}\r\n\\beta = \\theta - \\alpha (\\theta ,\\Sigma (\\theta )),\r\n\\end{equation} </div></div><span class=\"label\">(1)</span></div>where \u03b8 is the observed position of the source, \u03b1 is the deflection angle, \u03a3(\u03b8) is the surface mass density of the cluster at the position \u03b8 and \u03b2 is the position of the background source. Both the SL and WL observables can be expressed in terms of derivatives of the lensing potential, <div class=\"formula-wrap\"><div class=\"disp-formula\" id=\"equ2\" content-id=\"equ2\"><div class=\"tex-math display-math\"> \\begin{equation}\r\n\\psi (\\theta ) = \\frac{4\\,G D_{{\\rm l}}D_{{\\rm ls}}}{c^2 D_{{\\rm s}}} \\int \\mathrm{d}^2\\theta ^{\\prime } \\Sigma (\\theta ^{\\prime })ln(|\\theta - \\theta ^{\\prime }|),\r\n\\end{equation} </div></div><span class=\"label\">(2)</span></div>where <em>D</em><sub>l</sub>, <em>D</em><sub>ls</sub> and <em>D</em><sub>s</sub> are the angular diameter distances to the lens, from the lens to the source and from the observer to the source, respectively. The unknowns of the lensing problem are in general the surface mass density and the positions of the background sources. As shown in Diego et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib16\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib16\" data-open=\"bib16\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2007</a>), the WL and SL problem can be expressed as a system of linear equations that can be represented in a compact form <div class=\"formula-wrap\"><div class=\"disp-formula\" id=\"equ3\" content-id=\"equ3\"><div class=\"tex-math display-math\"> \\begin{equation}\r\n\\Theta = \\Gamma X,\r\n\\end{equation} </div></div><span class=\"label\">(3)</span></div>where the measured SL and WL observables are contained in the array \u0398 of dimension <em>N</em><sub>\u0398</sub>\u00a0=\u00a02<em>N</em><sub>SL</sub>\u00a0+\u00a02<em>N</em><sub>WL</sub>, the unknown surface mass density and source positions are in the array <em>X</em> of dimension <em>N</em><sub><em>X</em></sub>\u00a0=\u00a0<em>N</em><sub><em>c</em></sub>\u00a0+\u00a0<em>N</em><sub><em>g</em></sub>\u00a0+\u00a02<em>N</em><sub><em>s</em></sub> and the matrix \u0393 is known (for a given grid configuration and fiducial galaxy deflection field, see below) and has dimension <em>N</em><sub>\u0398</sub>\u00a0\u00d7\u00a0<em>N</em><sub><em>X</em></sub>. <em>N</em><sub>SL</sub> is the number of SL observables (each one contributing with two constraints, <em>x</em>, and <em>y</em>). <em>N</em><sub>WL</sub> is the number of WL observables (each one contributing with two constraints, \u03b3<sub>1</sub>, and \u03b3<sub>2</sub>), <em>N</em><sub><em>c</em></sub> is the number of grid points (or cells) that we use to divide the field of view. <em>N</em><sub><em>g</em></sub> is the number of deflection fields (from cluster members) that we consider. <em>N</em><sub><em>s</em></sub> is the number of background sources (each contributes with two unknowns, \u03b2<sub><em>x</em></sub>, and \u03b2<sub><em>y</em></sub>, see Sendra et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib44\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib44\" data-open=\"bib44\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2014</a> for details). The solution is found after minimizing a quadratic function that estimates the solution of the system of equations (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-equ3\"></span><a href=\"#equ3\" class=\"sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec\">3</a>). For this minimization, we use a quadratic algorithm which is optimized for solutions with the constraint that the solution, <em>X</em>, must be positive. This is particularly important since by imposing this constraint we avoid the unphysical situation where the masses associated with the galaxies are negative (that could otherwise provide a reasonable solution, from the formal mathematical point of view, to the system of linear equations\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-equ3\"></span><a href=\"#equ3\" class=\"sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec\">3</a>). Imposing the constrain <em>X</em>\u00a0&gt;\u00a00 also helps in regularizing the solution as it avoids large negative and positive contiguous fluctuations.</div><p class=\"chapter-para\">Earlier work has shown how the addition of the small deflection fields from member galaxies can help improve the mass determination when enough constraints are available (see for instance Kassiola, Kovner &amp; Fort <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib24\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib24\" data-open=\"bib24\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">1992</a>; Kneib et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib25\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib25\" data-open=\"bib25\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">1996</a>). In our previous paper (Sendra et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib44\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib44\" data-open=\"bib44\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2014</a>), we quantified via simulations how the addition of deflections from all the main member galaxies helps improve the mass reconstruction with respect to our previous standard non-parametric method. Strongly lensed galaxies are often locally affected by member galaxies. However, these perturbations cannot be recovered in grid-based reconstructions because the lensing information is too sparse to resolve member galaxies. For our study, we select the 73 brightest elliptical galaxies in the cluster central region and associate with them a mass according to their luminosity. The member galaxies are selected from the red sequence. We assume the fiducial deflection field comprising these member galaxies just scales by a fixed luminosity\u2013mass ratio. Later, the fitting procedure determines this proportionality constant that allows for the best reproduction of the data. For the mass profiles, we assume a NFW profile (Navarro, Frenk &amp; White <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib37\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib37\" data-open=\"bib37\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">1997</a>), and adopt a self-similarity approach where the scale radius scales with the mass. As discussed later, the choice of the particular profile is not very relevant for our results. In Sendra et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib44\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib44\" data-open=\"bib44\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2014</a>), we used one deflection field to model all the galaxies in the cluster. In the case of A1689, we go a step further and we use two deflection fields (i.e <em>N</em><sub><em>g</em></sub>\u00a0=\u00a02, see definition of <em>N</em><sub><em>g</em></sub> above). The first one is associated with the central type-cD galaxy and the second one contains the deflection field from the remaining dominant galaxies in the cluster. Each deflection field contributes in our model as one free parameter (its amplitude with respect to the fiducial amplitude). In principle, one could incorporate an independent deflection field for each one of the member galaxies but caution has to be taken to maintain as much as possible the orthogonality between the grid cells and the individual deflection fields. This will be studied in Section\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-sec7\"></span><a href=\"#sec7\" class=\"sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec\">7</a>. Settling for two deflection fields may be regarded as a fair compromise between the overly simple assumption that all galaxies in the cluster have individual haloes with masses that trace light following the same luminosity\u2013mass relation and a potentially more realistic but also unnecessarily complex assumption that each galaxy has a different luminosity\u2013mass ratio. We make an exception for the central cD galaxy because of its distinctive shallow luminosity profile and the separate origin that may be implied by the anomalously large numbers of globular clusters for this object and cD galaxies in general (see Alamo-Mart\u00ednez et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib1\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib1\" data-open=\"bib1\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2013</a>). All the galaxies used in our fiducial model are shown in Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig1\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig1\" data-open=\"fig1\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">1</a> where we use a non-linear colour scale to better show the extent and shapes of the individual haloes in our fiducial model. As in our previous paper (Sendra et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib44\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib44\" data-open=\"bib44\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2014</a>), we consider truncated NFW profiles to construct our fiducial model.</p>                    <h2 scrollto-destination=21026320 id=\"21026320\" class=\"section-title js-splitscreen-section-title\" data-legacy-id=sec5>5 RESULTS</h2>\r\n<p class=\"chapter-para\">When combining the WL and SL data sets, due to the large field of view (10\u00a0\u00d7\u00a010 arcmin<sup>2</sup>), and in order to maximize the resolution of the grid in the region covering the SL part of the data, we use a two resolution grid where the central 6.66\u00a0\u00d7\u00a06.66\u00a0arcmin<sup>2</sup> is sampled with smaller grid cells (of 9.37 arcsec in size) and the remaining area is sampled with 25 arcsec grid cells. Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig2\" data-open=\"fig2\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">2</a> shows the grid configuration. The small gap that can be appreciated between the two regions has a negligible effect since this region gets filled by the overlapping Gaussians on top of each grid cell. The use of a multiresolution grid introduces a bias in the reconstruction (see discussion below) in the transition region between the two resolutions mostly due to the overlap of Gaussians with different widths. The outer region is used as a buffer zone that, however, still contributes to the WL constraints in the transition phase between the two regions. Hence, we do not make full use of the results from the outer region in our conclusions but instead we will restrict ourselves to the central 6.66\u00a0\u00d7\u00a06.66\u00a0arcmin<sup>2</sup> region for most of our results. However, we should note that even within the central region caution has to be taken when interpreting the results close to the transition phase as some biases are still present near the border.</p>                        <a id=\"21026322\" scrollto-destination=\"21026322\"></a>\r\n<div data-id=\"fig2\" class=\"fig fig-section js-fig-section\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 2.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig2.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&amp;Signature=GZVCPhNSVJjoedfVRNTZg7f8H6l6GBkqdBtyoDzRZfqeEDf2xHlcpBqyLBONiHSAKLJ~VsDO0Yznth0cOuQcteCMjQy2AkJLAjEoDCYf5fOfkrB7U3w~8LyfQxj5Qf4u437F0njUZxFjjf0fPG1LB4c5AZH6xaXgU7Of6b6vl4gC~n3xDodyfXI9ZmA34S2fbmramLK3KQOKH9QgV4-s2J5AELIhBiZJ4hLkHDJDbq3EEt4Y0NvDH3a7xvB6-obSOHiyd34XyVnHNVqJthbBkQ1QfIyCYV3j~nIP-eT~J0Pox~dcCgwA43WNOYKZauGAHxlnWnbDXB-yLW9E~bbacQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Grid used in the reconstruction. The grid cell sizes are 25 and 9.37\u00a0arcsec. The high-resolution grid covers an area of 6.66\u00a0\u00d7\u00a06.66\u00a0arcmin2.\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig2.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026322/stu2064fig2.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig2.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026322\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig2.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&Signature=LXVNIIO4jCLOQYHfAfCRxCD3tIUNybs~D8-WOn0ozeInzLj-JVXbYxSScb-WEinbGyDUmUacQjh4qHxyEi6zgrWamaxNo~TxHkGLms0pn1UDe~rwco1fBZnbamdG8~aoafOxNiipit8p3uAmVW0UUdxLl5TY~ETgQk-Q3tvznsTAYGgiWgXrZyeWVd7KWupjWD4LbgIuEdbuRqUxeb9SEYJhdDT5zNRGu3q7~43lk~MuqoEBs3ncDH7Ke8MbJC~c5TMgW7nzFn~jC6pD96ozDIJgu6Y-Ihz3KT9GQuMnWBSvAYXaMZ~Rul3x8zUOypB2NI2plSf9oL2PGjYIRUMRyA__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026322&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig2.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">Grid used in the reconstruction. The grid cell sizes are 25 and 9.37\u00a0arcsec. The high-resolution grid covers an area of 6.66\u00a0\u00d7\u00a06.66\u00a0arcmin<sup>2</sup>.</p></div></div><div content-id=\"fig2\" class=\"fig fig-modal reveal-modal\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 2.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig2.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&amp;Signature=GZVCPhNSVJjoedfVRNTZg7f8H6l6GBkqdBtyoDzRZfqeEDf2xHlcpBqyLBONiHSAKLJ~VsDO0Yznth0cOuQcteCMjQy2AkJLAjEoDCYf5fOfkrB7U3w~8LyfQxj5Qf4u437F0njUZxFjjf0fPG1LB4c5AZH6xaXgU7Of6b6vl4gC~n3xDodyfXI9ZmA34S2fbmramLK3KQOKH9QgV4-s2J5AELIhBiZJ4hLkHDJDbq3EEt4Y0NvDH3a7xvB6-obSOHiyd34XyVnHNVqJthbBkQ1QfIyCYV3j~nIP-eT~J0Pox~dcCgwA43WNOYKZauGAHxlnWnbDXB-yLW9E~bbacQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Grid used in the reconstruction. The grid cell sizes are 25 and 9.37\u00a0arcsec. The high-resolution grid covers an area of 6.66\u00a0\u00d7\u00a06.66\u00a0arcmin2.\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig2.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026322/stu2064fig2.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig2.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026322\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig2.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&Signature=LXVNIIO4jCLOQYHfAfCRxCD3tIUNybs~D8-WOn0ozeInzLj-JVXbYxSScb-WEinbGyDUmUacQjh4qHxyEi6zgrWamaxNo~TxHkGLms0pn1UDe~rwco1fBZnbamdG8~aoafOxNiipit8p3uAmVW0UUdxLl5TY~ETgQk-Q3tvznsTAYGgiWgXrZyeWVd7KWupjWD4LbgIuEdbuRqUxeb9SEYJhdDT5zNRGu3q7~43lk~MuqoEBs3ncDH7Ke8MbJC~c5TMgW7nzFn~jC6pD96ozDIJgu6Y-Ihz3KT9GQuMnWBSvAYXaMZ~Rul3x8zUOypB2NI2plSf9oL2PGjYIRUMRyA__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026322&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig2.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">Grid used in the reconstruction. The grid cell sizes are 25 and 9.37\u00a0arcsec. The high-resolution grid covers an area of 6.66\u00a0\u00d7\u00a06.66\u00a0arcmin<sup>2</sup>.</p></div></div><p class=\"chapter-para\">For comparison purposes, we have performed the reconstruction in three different cases depending on the data set used. In case (i) we use only the SL data set, in case (ii) we use only the WL data set and in case (iii) we combine the SL and WL data set into the same data vector. In order to make a direct comparison, we use the same grid for all three cases although this is not optimal for the SL or WL case. In the SL-only case, we would use only a regular grid covering a smaller field of view (of 3\u00a0\u00d7\u00a03 arcmin<sup>2</sup>) while in the case of the WL-only case, we would also use a regular grid (with poorer resolution) but over the entire 10\u00a0\u00d7\u00a010\u00a0arcmin<sup>2</sup> field of view. Since our main interest is on the solution obtained when the SL and WL data sets are combined, we maintain the same grid configuration in all three cases. Also, we start the minimization in the same initial condition to eliminate this degree of freedom from the solution (different initial conditions are explored later in the paper). Finally, we use the same number of iterations (8000 iterations, this number will be discussed later) in the SL-only and SL+WL cases. For the WL-only case, we stop the minimization before to avoid overfitting (a large number of iterations in the WL-only case would produce a solution that is capable of reproducing the noisy WL estimates so the minimization must be stopped before this regime is reached). In Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig3\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig3\" data-open=\"fig3\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">3</a>, we present the 2D-reconstructed mass in the central region and the associated critical curves for a source at redshift 2 for the three cases. From left to right, we show the cases of the SL-only, WL-only and SL+WL. Note how the critical curve does not change much in the case SL+WL when compared with the SL-only case. This is a consequence of the critical curve being much more sensitive to the very central region (and the SL data). However, when the WL data is used in combination with the SL data, new interesting features in the mass distribution emerge even beyond the Einstein radius. Some of these features appear even more intriguing when looking at the magnification map (see Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig4\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig4\" data-open=\"fig4\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">4</a>) where some filamentary structures and clumps are made more evident. Both the projected mass and magnification maps are closely connected and the magnification map in this weaker lensing regime can be used as an alternative tracer of the mass especially in the range of interest shown in Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig4\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig4\" data-open=\"fig4\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">4</a> where the convergence, \u03ba\u00a0&lt;\u00a00.5, and \u03ba\u00a0\u223c\u00a0\u03b3. In this regime, and to first order, the magnification, \u03bc, can be approximated (by Taylor expansion) as \u03bc\u00a0\u2248\u00a01\u00a0+\u00a02\u03ba that shows the clear connection between magnification and projected mass. Further investigation of these features demands better-quality WL data and will be the subject of future studies. The small critical curve around the clump at the edge of the bottom-right quadrant is close to a feature seen also in Umetsu &amp; Broadhurst (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib48\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib48\" data-open=\"bib48\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2008</a>). This fact suggests that the feature in our reconstruction, although it could be affected by its proximity to the buffer zone, may also be produced by a real structure in that area.</p>                        <a id=\"21026324\" scrollto-destination=\"21026324\"></a>\r\n<div data-id=\"fig3\" class=\"fig fig-section js-fig-section\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 3.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig3.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&amp;Signature=Em3mShnHbOPbx5ZGqqFEs8Z4GbiPBROFaujr8bBVKFEdLEAJO2J7VD5VA2H7GZAemIaTAeaNNHPMFuQGCk5rnf6VADhS6Q04NzCFwtCXkypR7ran92rdBB8AR9Guqh2UB7PekeYkWSi8UqksyNvdIMAnzSsWULjNHPebxUMGz0V~y4w3NRQEg0USMrwrhUP0P2TCCm9tU6ZP~n0-g-OhqMOlGrasD8nr2YsDlBkRHiaRbexbkhLYneRdE27o9o7MsyxCs~MsFKhEJaUvW9LLAQzytAAqsm1OPNSmMyQbTLVwieA1zqfhZdTUbt3U~~Ks9xIBkFUJyTLt1D9ssrzqoQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Solutions (and associated critical curves for a source at redshift z\u00a0=\u00a02) for the cases where only the SL data is used in the reconstruction (left), only the WL data is used in the reconstruction (centre) and both, the SL and WL data are used in the reconstruction (right). The colours are in log-scale to increase contrast. The two small black regions in the centre correspond to magnifications less than 1 (that have been set to 0 in the log-scale for contrast purposes). The drop in the outer region (buffer zone) is a systematic effect due to the larger cell size in the grid. The features close to the transition region between the two grid resolutions are not always to be trusted.\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig4.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026325/stu2064fig4.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig4.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026325\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig4.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&Signature=t8glQXd9PZu1akSW5ylFGUl7d2sb2ipYZuii~a5WW4I5PqGJ~3wvuV8nTJ0uPJMF4-TKIhRQFFmR4vG7Ov-R~w6PvJjcqWanJXaywQUU-RaIgWlcuvBGcvss~vFt4YYItrvFWwCjFb4azjdoIJzKyHWfFcNfY2XvMuxNXyhy1n2lENc5s-7pZoqLGYbQHgCl-XjX-UtLFThQfZ73b8383niSM0tJw7ZpHxn23AN4X9r5yeOjx~sbXnYgW3L4-g7fICytCOpH2XcZkjKTdvpvKy6VM4CBV1~MmtMON-qGEQRdT5RjLK9ofMnGGP73CmnGYCXIpoTn1sFC5BFlf7lODw__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026325&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig4.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">Magnification map in the entire field of view of 10\u00a0\u00d7\u00a010\u00a0arcmin<sup>2</sup> for the SL+WL case. The colours are in log-scale to increase contrast. The two small black regions in the centre correspond to magnifications less than 1 (that have been set to 0 in the log-scale for contrast purposes). The drop in the outer region (buffer zone) is a systematic effect due to the larger cell size in the grid. The features close to the transition region between the two grid resolutions are not always to be trusted.</p></div></div><p class=\"chapter-para\">A more quantitative comparison of the different solutions is shown in Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig5\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig5\" data-open=\"fig5\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">5</a> where we show the density profiles of the surface mass density in terms of critical density. Unless otherwise noted, the critical density, \u03a3<sub>crit</sub>\u00a0=\u00a04.746\u00a0\u00d7\u00a010<sup>15</sup>\u2009M<sub>\u2299</sub>\u2009<em>h</em>\u2009Mpc<sup>\u22122</sup>, is computed for <em>z</em><sub>mean</sub>\u00a0=\u00a01.07. The WL-only case shows the typical mass-sheet degeneracy which has not been corrected in our solution. Also, in the WL-only solution, the mass at the centre is mostly associated with the individual galaxies accounting for the reduced shear in the vicinity of the Einstein radius, while the grid complements the central galaxy mass. This is better seen when comparing the values of <em>C</em><sub>1</sub> (coefficient for the galaxies in the cluster except the type-cD) and <em>C</em><sub>2</sub> (coefficient for the type-cD galaxy) for each case: for the SL-only case, we get <em>C</em><sub>1</sub>\u00a0=\u00a00.30, <em>C</em><sub>2</sub>\u00a0=\u00a00.25; for the WL-only case, we get <em>C</em><sub>1</sub>\u00a0=\u00a00.55, <em>C</em><sub>2</sub>\u00a0=\u00a00.28 and for the SL+WL case, we get <em>C</em><sub>1</sub>\u00a0=\u00a00.33, <em>C</em><sub>2</sub>\u00a0=\u00a00.26. The WL-only case has more freedom to increase the mass in the galaxies since this does not affect the SL constraints.</p>                        <a id=\"21026327\" scrollto-destination=\"21026327\"></a>\r\n<div data-id=\"fig5\" class=\"fig fig-section js-fig-section\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 5.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig5.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&amp;Signature=ioZgnHq3GNap9NQvkzaBajV0NNvZkNp1xKTS8Ix1JvCLebWGgPZWv~AzcPKgUfRaB0gNFdRZMh8RivROwoP0S7s9aWHZ0KdFCINo7PfG2NaJTyvEEDg-zsxvur5oUFrgJNOLL629uMOaFvhApXQvv9a-H~IfvlmMfNVnJ3~7b8JQkf6uHcGP7uGU53p1oNDttmjRYPZAn6SZxoEL1EQlN9IFFymR5SQl8D94DXZ5xA8G~RN9aHrCrPDtAMtUk7ydJuSTZKj~kJKSeE85RwKsa9k3zRvrkN~JLf0fI45w6av0rbiIDognIlIlRuZhAu4Z4HM6hlfmkL5SUgZVSHDwkg__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Profiles of the solutions obtained with SL data only (dotted), WL data only (dashed) and the combination SL+WL (solid). The systematic bump at 200\u2009arcsec (or 3.33\u2009arcmin) coincides with the position of the transition phase (for the grid) between the 6.66\u2009arcmin region and the outer buffer zone</p></div></div><div content-id=\"fig5\" class=\"fig fig-modal reveal-modal\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 5.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig5.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&amp;Signature=ioZgnHq3GNap9NQvkzaBajV0NNvZkNp1xKTS8Ix1JvCLebWGgPZWv~AzcPKgUfRaB0gNFdRZMh8RivROwoP0S7s9aWHZ0KdFCINo7PfG2NaJTyvEEDg-zsxvur5oUFrgJNOLL629uMOaFvhApXQvv9a-H~IfvlmMfNVnJ3~7b8JQkf6uHcGP7uGU53p1oNDttmjRYPZAn6SZxoEL1EQlN9IFFymR5SQl8D94DXZ5xA8G~RN9aHrCrPDtAMtUk7ydJuSTZKj~kJKSeE85RwKsa9k3zRvrkN~JLf0fI45w6av0rbiIDognIlIlRuZhAu4Z4HM6hlfmkL5SUgZVSHDwkg__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Profiles of the solutions obtained with SL data only (dotted), WL data only (dashed) and the combination SL+WL (solid). The smaller plot shows the same profiles but in linear scale and beyond 100\u2009arcsec. The units in the axis are the same as the larger plot. The systematic bump at 200\u2009arcsec (or 3.33\u2009arcmin) coincides with the position of the transition phase (for the grid) between the 6.66\u2009arcmin region and the outer buffer zone</p></div></div><p class=\"chapter-para\">On the other hand, in the SL-only case, the grid plays a more central role and accounts for most of the mass. Also, the SL-only case shows a sharp drop in mass beyond the Einstein radius, which is expected for this grid-based model, due to the lack of sensitivity of the SL data to the outer regions. When the SL and WL data sets are combined in the joint reconstruction, the new joint profile shows a smoother behaviour to larger radius and the solution compares well with previous estimates of the profile derived from SL-only and WL-only. Both grid and galaxies play important roles in fitting the SL+WL data set.</p><p class=\"chapter-para\">In terms of source reconstruction, Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig6\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig6\" data-open=\"fig6\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">6</a> shows the reconstructed sources for the two cases, SL-only (left) and SL+WL (right). In the two panels, the centre and the scale are the same. In both cases, the solutions obtained with SL-only and SL+WL data seem to be able to form 1\u20133\u2009arcsec sources that fall near well-defined caustics.</p>                        <a id=\"21026332\" scrollto-destination=\"21026332\"></a>\r\n<div data-id=\"fig6\" class=\"fig fig-section js-fig-section\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 6.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig6.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&amp;Signature=jsnftxRfth4eeZOA-merFSnTwFReYG5uqieriX~yKHunEdQ0Y2F-bZQTmIrVutsXx1I~A~a37074h01mUtaYtcbm6XUbh8-ujCEkbLDAul6U~9NXmDodwcdoq3FP-5I7LpfXwJNxH3rGeESzdRXhRTb9rbOC7NzDs8LokQseLiN03tARnwgIIVgBJ4Zga1MG~mHwzbejMryiReRjAgvWQ8YId03LYiMkmnIDW41dDjyh7WfIMlE49Yd91gCBYaXv-GDRcNDtwVmC2C0igSK2vNny2ZD8tIlFAIhzBOvv6TH12X8hOQw03nc7IDMUlXAimeVPtaj-PLwcl6OEjdsfnw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Caustics (at z\u00a0=\u00a02) for the SL only (left) and SL+WL case (right) compared with the reconstructed sources. Each source is represented with a different colour index from 1 (darkest grey) to 26 (lightest grey). The field of view is small and corresponds to 1.3<sup>\u2032</sup> across to maximize the <em>focal plane</em>. The centre is the same in both cases and corresponds to the centre of the original 10<sup>\u2032</sup> field of view.</p></div></div><p class=\"chapter-para\">In Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig7\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig7\" data-open=\"fig7\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">7</a>, we show the ratio between the 2D-reconstructed mass map and the corresponding profile. A circularly symmetric mass distribution should behave as a constant sheet of value <em>Ratio</em>\u00a0=\u00a01. Deviations from this value highlight the asymmetries in different regions of the cluster. Note how the central region exhibits a more symmetric structure but around the Einstein radius there are important deviations from the mean profile by a factor \u22484 above and below the mean density. The largest deviations occur near the buffer zone, and may be affected by the proximity to this transition phase. Overall, a left\u2013right global asymmetry (or gradient) is appreciated across the field of view. A similar asymmetry can also be found in Umetsu &amp; Broadhurst (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib48\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib48\" data-open=\"bib48\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2008</a>). The rings around the centre are due to the individual galaxies which produce spikes in the profile.</p>                        <a id=\"21026334\" scrollto-destination=\"21026334\"></a>\r\n<div data-id=\"fig7\" class=\"fig fig-section js-fig-section\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 7.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig7.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&amp;Signature=fe~YmG6i-h2xbJ8Ypr7jrcI-PFDpto5YzlVkIwwVPTPT1UK9pozVD1wFtQNJg-rI3cFahUdsUAYuyAyKONg9b6VzllTJVeXnzJ7FCyDrDUQ~ooCf2JCeCmiX8frXqWhUoACazYNLXRCagYMsVea2oaYlkIAR8ZYLcCGw8fyKNrqUPX~YbiFH~Ir5eHuUqYOYvPLM1Y~f3QYReavuobvNZ-KXqhH0YmAPbx0np8EwiAboipiu8zop6LgUs~RYSv15QhR4aZyR1bUt5~cjUVhqvWHBVChm9dwY4pFmNHiLgmXLn5oM3FAWUXvaySA0X9HTAatlfsRLQ7YYZEgne6DzGw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Asymmetric behaviour of the mass density in the central region of 6.66\u00a0\u00d7\u00a06.66\u00a0arcmin2. The plot shows the ratio between the solution 2D map (SL+WL case) and the corresponding circularly symmetric profile, that is, each pixel at a distance r from the centre is divided by the profile at the same r. In order to increase contrast, the ratio is saturated beyond the value 7.5 and we show the square root of this ratio.\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig7.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026334/stu2064fig7.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig7.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026334\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig7.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&Signature=p30mS~KESGIYCEIB4eDhMaa5XU5220hk9w6WYqeENf4~eLo6X1mBkGGZuQ2EQ-6RBD6IimAqD7WScl65NwF5mTHb2~9KO84qGw3mAWhiYMQ9cfj950QB3JfYMQ2iJNAyVAsmEXMfcooyA2kqz2ZvQlj7RDZfSPJDG09LelWjX99ZIzyBDqX2BHNL3MkB12sOFtgGF~6PgxeFKtkGn9ID~-DIs-z1c5BD~DkMR3Yl~3-SD2eQg1D9VnMfsfAau6zoL891AOKy7r3lj~9XLk9mwRdSwTesdb9l5hcbyVAn33lY4Xympi0Zm7V0RBWJPzNfG6mEnL~UpxJz0Pg5RCP4qw__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026334&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig7.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">Asymmetric behaviour of the mass density in the central region of 6.66\u00a0\u00d7\u00a06.66\u00a0arcmin<sup>2</sup>. The plot shows the ratio between the solution 2D map (SL+WL case) and the corresponding circularly symmetric profile, that is, each pixel at a distance <em>r</em> from the centre is divided by the profile at the same <em>r</em>. In order to increase contrast, the ratio is saturated beyond the value 7.5 and we show the square root of this ratio.</p></div></div>                    <h3 scrollto-destination=21026335 id=\"21026335\" class=\"section-title js-splitscreen-section-title\" data-legacy-id=sec5-1>5.1 Comparison with previous results and analytical models</h3>\r\n<p class=\"chapter-para\">It is important to compare the results obtained with our non-parametric algorithm with those obtained using fully parametric methods but a similar data set. Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig8\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig8\" data-open=\"fig8\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">8</a> shows our solution compared with two analytical models that fit solutions obtained by parametric methods. Broadhurst et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib6\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib6\" data-open=\"bib6\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005a</a>) found that the NFW profile did not fit well the SL+WL data in a similar way similar to our results, with a tendency to be too steep in the centre (<em>r</em>\u00a0&lt;\u00a050\u00a0kpc).</p>                        <a id=\"21026337\" scrollto-destination=\"21026337\"></a>\r\n<div data-id=\"fig8\" class=\"fig fig-section js-fig-section\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 8.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig8.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&amp;Signature=lXnyeTwn0BJRobkA1GvGX2Nn~Jil6RneA1~l98IrZ9~eAVFzacPayDg0WoF-g3r1Z0qPKRhzx1ubfHJSiDScbqYeRQw7bGUyj77~00dKIDoqpjSYZDRM0zwj-vAB6mG8xRCOsGR5y00-C6jQRy6gIbdGbqA-xmIfhXHNeP6aLwqFLIofJfVOYe-cFbSDn8X~b9Ez8txPEbmxvR07qJH7xvL-1-wpsSxvhdIpVfFU83qGFAgA7GH4zVYY~Th6sMB~NYDfn0VtJNzRFeRhXMx8aGJVTqfMIHRZCHf1uUlRBNxsSOp7UnNWUw6u1u3lsamm1H~pn27fW1VV0kAlYwnB0w__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Comparison of the profile corresponding to the SL+WL solution (after 8000 Iterations) with two NFW models found in the literature, and that fit their corresponding solutions (Broadhurst et\u00a0al. 2005a; Limousin et\u00a0al. 2007). The profiles are centred in the type-cD galaxy.\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig8.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026337/stu2064fig8.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig8.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026337\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig8.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&Signature=WvTshkqKKri57YyYS5aNs0jX0FU~-ya2sSE4KE3qm8BzwH32y3Mf1NnNbK9UO-Yesvr6NnSG7Qz0dWCxy4qCg7qrs6YSrQBwrBoj4kIVqtAnkGI5bgOeufgeAd9rI9t~zSshhqKMej7rwQKRjNQh~otrWB0k3iX9wStkjVoxtZaI3m43ab2InwB65KddBP77CT8qU80jbxOs~WLhNun-g5yHNKUpJsvhKpBY~6WMPpWSsXp-y8Iw~og47FdfshTmVa6~kBJCWJPFMii7cWAcGfwMHna1TmJWesCNpOgYc3f4ZTVFfBfqU71IiOD6Evved6BKe96RTZndR-zrNCKlYg__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026337&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig8.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">Comparison of the profile corresponding to the SL+WL solution (after 8000 Iterations) with two NFW models found in the literature, and that fit their corresponding solutions (Broadhurst et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib6\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib6\" data-open=\"bib6\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005a</a>; Limousin et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib31\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib31\" data-open=\"bib31\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2007</a>). The profiles are centred in the type-cD galaxy.</p></div></div><p class=\"chapter-para\">In Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig9\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig9\" data-open=\"fig9\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">9</a>, we compare the radial mass profile derived from our solution with previously published results of A1689 based on different lensing techniques. In the SL regime, our solution overlaps well with the SL modelling results of Broadhurst et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib7\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib7\" data-open=\"bib7\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005b</a>). Our results are also in good agreement with the model-independent mass profile of Umetsu et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib49\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib49\" data-open=\"bib49\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2011</a>) derived from combined WL shear-and-magnification measurements based on the Subaru data. When compared with previous work, we find a good agreement between our solution and other solutions, in terms of the profile and the location and shape of the radial critical curve, although the tangential critical curve we obtain extends further to the south than previous SL solutions.</p>                        <a id=\"21026339\" scrollto-destination=\"21026339\"></a>\r\n<div data-id=\"fig9\" class=\"fig fig-section js-fig-section\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 9.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig9.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&amp;Signature=jz6azIrHneics30B~ruNYJjo7zOoSXj-nPjqa1zedj4Qw~QPIKlVflzZbL3gl8e3obTVT9WSXZAVuQbgqPr8J0mTY8xmKvEd78loLmJJGD8CjhiSfjyDtOqymILL4bfQvegG6yVV5RqjoY0BjldtzhbSZqiiFUIkM3vaIYhxI6YaFUNDBOwVJ44BuCx2agxV~eX9uVd2~nJ26YjS2A1W6k8Am12GjO5Tje67JXUuAGwJQpQqGd4eCtO4wri1XaUWWtHPnXNoelG02haD~W-h94P5SXOWPQZyIwKQGeqlmaYzSxUd8X7-PpYRc6LWfksbT2bkVsbE7IvuT5Kh-8zORg__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Comparison of the profiles from our solution (grey region from Table\u00a01) with previous results from the literature. The profiles are centred in the type-cD galaxy.</p></div></div>                    <h3 scrollto-destination=21026340 id=\"21026340\" class=\"section-title js-splitscreen-section-title\" data-legacy-id=sec5-2>5.2 Mass-to-light ratios</h3>\r\n<p class=\"chapter-para\">To compute the stellar masses and luminosities, rather than relying on magnitudes for a given aperture, we compute the stellar mass and luminosity associated with each pixel in our field of view. Obviously, the pixels containing galaxies not in the cluster have their stellar masses wrongly estimated but we can mask these regions out later on in our analysis. We compute the \u2018<em>B</em>-Johnson\u2019 luminosity of the cluster galaxies on a pixel-by-pixel basis using the new version of the Bayesian Photometric Redshifts (<span class=\"small-caps\">bpz</span>; Ben\u00edtez <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib3\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib3\" data-open=\"bib3\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2000</a>) software. We assume that all galaxies (pixels) have the same redshift and assign to each pixel of the image one of the <span class=\"small-caps\">bpz</span> templates based on their ACS colours. We then calculate the absolute magnitude in the Vega-calibrated Johnson \u2018<em>B</em> band\u2019, using the <em>F</em>814<em>W</em> magnitude and the inferred spectra type. The stellar masses for each pixel are also calculated from the <span class=\"small-caps\">bpz</span> fits to each pixel, using the relationship between rest frame (<em>g</em>\u2212<em>i</em>) colour and stellar mass of Taylor et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib47\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib47\" data-open=\"bib47\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2011</a>).</p><p class=\"chapter-para\">Since our mass model has the galaxy member component differentiated from the diffuse dark matter halo component, we can compute light-to-mass ratios at the position of the member galaxies. The total mass in the galaxies is computed from our reconstructed solution by multiplying the fiducial mass map by the corresponding <em>C</em><sub>1</sub> and <em>C</em><sub>2</sub> factors of the derived solution. The stellar mass can be computed in the same regions after applying a mask that is equal to the footprint of our assumed mass map for the fiducial galaxies. At the same time, we can compute ratios between the total mass derived from our lensing analysis and the stellar mass in the same field of view (without applying any mask or restricting ourselves to particular galaxies).</p><p class=\"chapter-para\">The mass-to-light ratio oscillates around a typical value of \u223c20 for most of the galaxies, with a small decrease towards the central galaxy. In particular, we find a mass-to-light ratio of <em>M</em>/<em>L</em><sub><em>B</em></sub>\u00a0=\u00a021\u00a0\u00b1\u00a014 inside the <em>r</em>\u00a0&lt;\u00a01 arcmin region that drops to <em>M</em>/<em>L</em><sub><em>B</em></sub>\u00a0=\u00a017\u00a0\u00b1\u00a08 inside the <em>r</em>\u00a0&lt;\u00a040 arcsec region. Recently, Okabe et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib39\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib39\" data-open=\"bib39\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2014</a>) found that at large cluster radii, the mass-to-light ratio of subhaloes in the Coma cluster tend to the typical values for clusters (around 200), whereas this ratio decreases towards the centre of the cluster to values around <em>M</em>/<em>L</em><sub><em>B</em></sub>\u00a0\u2248\u00a035 (for <em>h</em>\u00a0=\u00a00.7) (see also, Natarajan et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib36\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib36\" data-open=\"bib36\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2009</a>). When comparing with previous results, our mass-to-light ratios are typically smaller than the ones found in the literature (see for instance Bardeau et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib2\" data-open=\"bib2\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2007</a>; Medezinski et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib33\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib33\" data-open=\"bib33\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2007</a> where they find typical values of about an order of magnitude larger). This is mostly due to the fact that our mass-to-light ratios are computed after averaging the masses and luminosities in the footprint defined by the member galaxies while other authors consider the entire cluster where a significant fraction of the area is not occupied by member galaxies. This is highlighted in Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig10\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig10\" data-open=\"fig10\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">10</a> where the ratio is higher in the region between the member galaxies. Our results are more in line with those derived from isolated systems, (see for instance Jim\u00e9nez-Vicente et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib21\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib21\" data-open=\"bib21\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2014</a> for a recent result where they find significantly smaller stellar to DM mass ratios).</p>                        <a id=\"21026345\" scrollto-destination=\"21026345\"></a>\r\n<div data-id=\"fig10\" class=\"fig fig-section js-fig-section\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 10.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig10.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&amp;Signature=yaDVnEHoHbaXRWP~i3msNiwybOpGkTNvn5v6zannCOvPEfNQ0P7aNruUCJYqAMMFM4oBcZtdERBLLvCLAjG24NvZlNOsrjbm9TW5tD~eY4AzXikVARJozB-3~eguc8OURcbCJWRAAxwKNdCABjwztfKKiRPMbslfCkGGe~4wjptme~9nq74f9DjPeo1a3s-8ssIDlnD0Xo-jqm0ftr1m1ydp89lDLp2RjFVZSSHqu7U8Q2YOHbr71N5-Msc5JeFyDtjOnYmu0nyct~7GFzbTAIoXTQZePqIGWYp92XLkrMdbZPlaEWytA25I7wf1~7FNK6gCFQwX19jvkJYEunUIiw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Ratio of total mass to stellar mass. The field of view is 3.35 arcmin and is centred in the main cD galaxy. The orientation (and scale) is similar to Fig.\u00a01 (right-hand panel).\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig10.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026345/stu2064fig10.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig10.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026345\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig10.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&Signature=V8P1YhGn~cJVy6zv0TCY9mkLW~y4exIcNR7IcrUk5o7bzyrcy2~XGrKp2dRAN702CgsaM-kPSA1IXHMh0FU-Tcfni9SBAFznZqwfheoymcqn-uI9v6tfeCKVJqv9uI~w1rUErWK74ZZ0QQR6jKSr3nIAvMBLunNcf2H05Rk8PN0Se1XoGZtw6nVnYZBPVI8K3XADyOKOl2I8tMjs48TGn1oPJx3a2CLKg8gaKym4tTRU~-6ANNpDlHd3T01nexboChtiikI9kqcZTbNpO6Ve1RBPFqusf5QXD5uvJ~IyPHRnorr-kj82Udn~SspFZ3fGRsrlHHcNRIvlQosMAMw18g__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026345&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig10.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">Ratio of total mass to stellar mass. The field of view is 3.35 arcmin and is centred in the main cD galaxy. The orientation (and scale) is similar to Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig1\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig1\" data-open=\"fig1\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">1</a> (right-hand panel).</p></div></div><div content-id=\"fig10\" class=\"fig fig-modal reveal-modal\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 10.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig10.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&amp;Signature=yaDVnEHoHbaXRWP~i3msNiwybOpGkTNvn5v6zannCOvPEfNQ0P7aNruUCJYqAMMFM4oBcZtdERBLLvCLAjG24NvZlNOsrjbm9TW5tD~eY4AzXikVARJozB-3~eguc8OURcbCJWRAAxwKNdCABjwztfKKiRPMbslfCkGGe~4wjptme~9nq74f9DjPeo1a3s-8ssIDlnD0Xo-jqm0ftr1m1ydp89lDLp2RjFVZSSHqu7U8Q2YOHbr71N5-Msc5JeFyDtjOnYmu0nyct~7GFzbTAIoXTQZePqIGWYp92XLkrMdbZPlaEWytA25I7wf1~7FNK6gCFQwX19jvkJYEunUIiw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Ratio of total mass to stellar mass. The field of view is 3.35 arcmin and is centred in the main cD galaxy. The orientation (and scale) is similar to Fig.\u00a01 (right-hand panel).\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig10.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026345/stu2064fig10.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig10.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026345\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig10.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&Signature=V8P1YhGn~cJVy6zv0TCY9mkLW~y4exIcNR7IcrUk5o7bzyrcy2~XGrKp2dRAN702CgsaM-kPSA1IXHMh0FU-Tcfni9SBAFznZqwfheoymcqn-uI9v6tfeCKVJqv9uI~w1rUErWK74ZZ0QQR6jKSr3nIAvMBLunNcf2H05Rk8PN0Se1XoGZtw6nVnYZBPVI8K3XADyOKOl2I8tMjs48TGn1oPJx3a2CLKg8gaKym4tTRU~-6ANNpDlHd3T01nexboChtiikI9kqcZTbNpO6Ve1RBPFqusf5QXD5uvJ~IyPHRnorr-kj82Udn~SspFZ3fGRsrlHHcNRIvlQosMAMw18g__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026345&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig10.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">Ratio of total mass to stellar mass. The field of view is 3.35 arcmin and is centred in the main cD galaxy. The orientation (and scale) is similar to Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig1\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig1\" data-open=\"fig1\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">1</a> (right-hand panel).</p></div></div><p class=\"chapter-para\">The fact that our critical curves present a smoother form when compared to previous estimations (see for instance Broadhurst et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib7\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib7\" data-open=\"bib7\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005b</a>; Halkola et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib20\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib20\" data-open=\"bib20\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2006</a>; Limousin et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib31\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib31\" data-open=\"bib31\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2007</a>; Coe et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib11\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib11\" data-open=\"bib11\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2010</a>) while the total mass inside the Einstein radius is consistent with previous work, is suggesting that the masses associated with the individual galaxies in our solution are smaller than the corresponding masses derived from alternative methods. The mass-to-light ratio inferred from our solution is therefore probably smaller than the one that could be derived from those alternative methods.</p><p class=\"chapter-para\">Regarding the DM to stellar mass ratios, Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig10\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig10\" data-open=\"fig10\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">10</a> shows the ratio (in log-scale) between the derived total mass from lensing and the inferred stellar mass from the <em>F</em>814<em>W</em> band. The map of the ratio has been smoothed with a Gaussian of FWHM = 6.3\u2009arcsec to reduce the noise fluctuations but also to reduce the impact of background sources and other galaxies not included in our fiducial mass model. The smallest ratios (dark regions) correspond to bright galaxies in the outer regions of the cluster and that were not included in our fiducial model. The highest ratios correspond to regions in the cluster with no significant emission in the <em>F</em>814<em>W</em> band but that have DM in our lens model. Note the gradient at the centre of the main cluster and subcluster in the north-east towards lower ratio values indicating that, as expected, the fraction of baryons with respect to the DM is higher in these regions.</p>                    <h2 scrollto-destination=21026348 id=\"21026348\" class=\"section-title js-splitscreen-section-title\" data-legacy-id=sec6>6 COSMOLOGICAL IMPLICATIONS</h2>\r\n<div class=\"&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            \">Gravitational lensing in well-studied clusters like A1689 can be used to impose constraints in the cosmological model (see for instance Jullo et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib23\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib23\" data-open=\"bib23\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2010</a>). A test based on the relative differences of the deflection angle between pairs of images was applied to A1689 in Broadhurst et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib7\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib7\" data-open=\"bib7\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005b</a>) based on the solution obtained with a parametric model. Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig11\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig11\" data-open=\"fig11\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">11</a> shows the function <em>f</em><sub><em>k</em></sub> as described in Broadhurst et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib7\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib7\" data-open=\"bib7\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005b</a>, see equations 7 and 14 in that paper). <div class=\"formula-wrap\"><div class=\"disp-formula\" id=\"equ4\" content-id=\"equ4\"><div class=\"tex-math display-math\"> \\begin{equation}\r\nf_k = \\frac{D_{{\\rm ls}}(z)D_{\\rm s}(z_{\\rm s}=2)}{D_{\\rm s}(z)D_{{\\rm ls}}(z_{\\rm s}=2)},\r\n\\end{equation} </div></div><span class=\"label\">(4)</span></div>where <em>D</em><sub>ls</sub>(<em>z</em>) is the angular diameter distance from the lens to the source and <em>D</em><sub>s</sub> is the angular diameter distance to the source.</div>                        <a id=\"21026350\" scrollto-destination=\"21026350\"></a>\r\n<div data-id=\"fig11\" class=\"fig fig-section js-fig-section\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 11.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig11.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&amp;Signature=ntTKCM0ta2kGvU-utH1tF5XDoeF93oSUCqk3F77m1ukT3hC2KXGe2R9DC6qPtkQPt9Fcq62uoh8dVFJS5UGZMWC3oq18io0RyOtjHCtw6LDGTmUFRo3rheJtXJKfz8rHpx77vPP9xFrOV-~PG2moXecRdV-hmWp7rRKM5eR4cdYGBpZVc4Px4XbG4o1umQQTyXAeFWZpTa9y3nd19Mg~2kfuq8V8HHeqWw-6L-Ets65VOoj45Blj0pS~78AiBhPafxzf-V8z80PNYqhKrFV25oyclbWm6C-NOI3byTmaZInJgWHRDMf-SdsBG-3r0TY9Gi9mxrmYiW9KkpGt~elPOg__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"The dashed line corresponds to the function fk for a flat model (\u03a9m\u00a0=\u00a00.3, \u039b\u00a0=\u00a00.7) compared with the data (diamonds correspond to systems with spectroscopic redshifts and crosses to systems with photometric redshifts). The main outliers are marked with their corresponding ID.\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig11.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026350/stu2064fig11.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig11.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026350\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig11.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&Signature=L5Q8P9SkhIk11goiItQ43kq4kiPbF7XOV~LdPBrKxTrQLJEVIi5qFrRsgQK53LQT-uXnHql8B6XybmtJ48LbnNepGw91ZfqztM1wCH3UOxeuPUbyVcIfaPG7jJiNaTpTgeLrUJyi5r9EMLePnmcYFjIkG3XPwyE0IFi9Zd7GdiqDLl1msDeY1lAm~yw7cIk9oqTec-TveJk0DqIpHjbsOT7mgjZhe2FPCKHP-5gi9gRJds03m2voqlxlmaCacRnY9RMcPHueDgMPL2GdqIQjo1ARzr20fR-ljH5N-w2laJcIuSaDq2jegO0AUb97LSWgBnXogETa9-8W7Zv~MGBeQg__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026350&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig11.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">The dashed line corresponds to the function <em>f</em><sub><em>k</em></sub> for a flat model (\u03a9<sub>m</sub>\u00a0=\u00a00.3, \u039b\u00a0=\u00a00.7) compared with the data (diamonds correspond to systems with spectroscopic redshifts and crosses to systems with photometric redshifts). The main outliers are marked with their corresponding ID.</p></div></div><div content-id=\"fig11\" class=\"fig fig-modal reveal-modal\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 11.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig11.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&amp;Signature=ntTKCM0ta2kGvU-utH1tF5XDoeF93oSUCqk3F77m1ukT3hC2KXGe2R9DC6qPtkQPt9Fcq62uoh8dVFJS5UGZMWC3oq18io0RyOtjHCtw6LDGTmUFRo3rheJtXJKfz8rHpx77vPP9xFrOV-~PG2moXecRdV-hmWp7rRKM5eR4cdYGBpZVc4Px4XbG4o1umQQTyXAeFWZpTa9y3nd19Mg~2kfuq8V8HHeqWw-6L-Ets65VOoj45Blj0pS~78AiBhPafxzf-V8z80PNYqhKrFV25oyclbWm6C-NOI3byTmaZInJgWHRDMf-SdsBG-3r0TY9Gi9mxrmYiW9KkpGt~elPOg__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"The dashed line corresponds to the function fk for a flat model (\u03a9m\u00a0=\u00a00.3, \u039b\u00a0=\u00a00.7) compared with the data (diamonds correspond to systems with spectroscopic redshifts and crosses to systems with photometric redshifts). The main outliers are marked with their corresponding ID.\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig11.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026350/stu2064fig11.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig11.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026350\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig11.jpeg?Expires=1639265418&Signature=L5Q8P9SkhIk11goiItQ43kq4kiPbF7XOV~LdPBrKxTrQLJEVIi5qFrRsgQK53LQT-uXnHql8B6XybmtJ48LbnNepGw91ZfqztM1wCH3UOxeuPUbyVcIfaPG7jJiNaTpTgeLrUJyi5r9EMLePnmcYFjIkG3XPwyE0IFi9Zd7GdiqDLl1msDeY1lAm~yw7cIk9oqTec-TveJk0DqIpHjbsOT7mgjZhe2FPCKHP-5gi9gRJds03m2voqlxlmaCacRnY9RMcPHueDgMPL2GdqIQjo1ARzr20fR-ljH5N-w2laJcIuSaDq2jegO0AUb97LSWgBnXogETa9-8W7Zv~MGBeQg__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026350&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig11.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">The dashed line corresponds to the function <em>f</em><sub><em>k</em></sub> for a flat model (\u03a9<sub>m</sub>\u00a0=\u00a00.3, \u039b\u00a0=\u00a00.7) compared with the data (diamonds correspond to systems with spectroscopic redshifts and crosses to systems with photometric redshifts). The main outliers are marked with their corresponding ID.</p></div></div><p class=\"chapter-para\">This function is normalized for convenience to <em>z</em>\u00a0=\u00a02 and the shape is determined by the cosmological model. Each data point correspond to a multiply lensed system (out of our set of 26). Due to the more unprecise reconstruction in the very centre of the cluster, we exclude images that are at a distance of 5 arcsec or less from the centre. Diamonds correspond to the spectroscopic redshift systems and cross symbols to those with only photometric redshifts. The dashed line indicates the expected behaviour of our data points for a standard cosmological model (flat \u039bCDM model with \u03a9<sub>m</sub>\u00a0=\u00a00.3). In the ideal scenario where there is no projection effects and we are able to reconstruct the deflection field perfectly, the data points would lie perfectly along the curve for the correct choice of cosmological model. Some scatter is seen here about this expected relation. The symmetry of the scatter indicates that the deflection field we recover is not noise free and imperfections and projection effects along the line of sight unrelated to the cluster must at some level limit the accuracy of this comparison. However, it is important to notice that our result is obtained with just one cluster and is not optimized for in terms of the \u2018best\u2019 multiply lensed systems. For instance, three systems are marked in the above plot that depart more significantly from the expected theoretical behaviour. System number 3 corresponds to a system with only a photometric redshift (and this redshift might be wrong) and besides, two of the images of this system are relatively close to each other (this close proximity of course enhances the uncertainty in estimating <em>f</em><sub><em>k</em></sub> for such systems) and the third image is basically buried behind one of the large elliptical galaxies (and hence very sensitive to the exact mass distribution of this member galaxy at a level not incorporated in our member galaxy model. A similar situation is found in system 21, where two radial images are close to the centre (although farther than the 5 arcsec exclusion radius mentioned above) and one of them is very close to one of the member elliptical galaxies. System 14 corresponds to a system that lies well beyond the Einstein radius, where our reconstruction is less well constrained. It is obvious from the above plot that a more accurate description of the lens (for instance through the addition of new spectroscopic systems, especially at high redshift) would permit a tighter constraint on the cosmological model. A study based on stacking <em>f</em><sub><em>k</em></sub> for many lensing clusters should be able to provide competitive constraints on the cosmological model based on this potentially important independent test, for which some simulations have been explored (Lubini et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib32\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib32\" data-open=\"bib32\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2014</a>).</p>                    <h2 scrollto-destination=21026352 id=\"21026352\" class=\"section-title js-splitscreen-section-title\" data-legacy-id=sec7>7 VARIABILITY OF THE POSSIBLE SOLUTIONS</h2>\r\n<p class=\"chapter-para\">We refer to the best-fitting model presented above as our <em>reference solution</em> since in the context of this form of modelling there is no single unique solution, given that the number of lensed images and the grid resolution are finite. So more important than finding a statistically <em>best</em> solution is to understand the range of possible solutions that are consistent with the data. Hence, as discussed in previous papers (Diego et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib14\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib14\" data-open=\"bib14\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005a</a>, <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib15\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib15\" data-open=\"bib15\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005b</a>, <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib16\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib16\" data-open=\"bib16\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2007</a>; Ponente &amp; Diego <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib41\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib41\" data-open=\"bib41\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2011</a>; Sendra et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib44\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib44\" data-open=\"bib44\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2014</a>), we intentionally seek an approximate solution to the system of equations. A major mistake in this form of modelling is to adopt a grid of higher resolution than justified by the number of lensed images. In this limit, we may obtain what appear to be a near-perfect solution that matches identically the locations of all lensed images but at the expense of a mass distribution that is much more highly structured on small scales that is physically reasonable, including negative surface densities. Such forced solutions tend to predict sources (in the source plane) that are unreasonably small and concentrated together in the centre of the field of view corresponding to huge lens magnifications. This overfitting regime can be avoided by appreciating that uncertainties in the data and the approximations made by our non-parametric reconstruction means that a minimal, inevitable level of error must be allowed in the reconstruction. This includes our assumptions and approximations introduced from our hypothesis that the member galaxy deflections are strictly proportional to the light, and that the soft component can be exactly modelled by a superposition of Gaussians of a given pixel scale, or that the sources in the source plane are delta functions, or that there are no significant projection effects of matter along the line of sight etc.</p><p class=\"chapter-para\">As our input catalogue, we consider first a reliable set of 26 robust strongly lensed systems in which we have great faith. Some of these systems have only photometric redshifts which can be imprecise. Changing the SL (or WL) data set has an impact on the reconstructed solution as the constraints in the system change accordingly. Additional sources of uncertainty in the final solution are related to the particular choice of the initial guess in the minimization process or the number of iterations of the algorithm. In this section, we explore these sources of variability.</p>                    <h3 scrollto-destination=21026355 id=\"21026355\" class=\"section-title js-splitscreen-section-title\" data-legacy-id=sec7-1>7.1 Dependence with iteration number</h3>\r\n<p class=\"chapter-para\">The number of iterations determine some of the properties of the solution (see Sendra et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib44\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib44\" data-open=\"bib44\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2014</a> for details). Adding the fiducial deflection field helps in solving some known issues with non-parametric methods like regularization and the overfitting problem. Nevertheless, overfitting can still occur if the number of iterations is too large so the algorithm always needs to be stopped after a given number of iterations. Using the location of the radial critical curves is a sensitive choice for identifying an optimal range for the number of iterations, as the radius of this critical curve is well defined in the data as it can be seen to be fairly circular in shape from the distribution of very radially extended images. This is not the case for the tangential critical curve.</p><p class=\"chapter-para\">In this paper, this part of the analysis is done a posteriori. However, it could be in principle incorporated into the system of linear equations, however, this is beyond the scope of this work and will be studied in more detail in a future paper, see however Cacciato et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib8\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib8\" data-open=\"bib8\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2006</a>) and Merten et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib34\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib34\" data-open=\"bib34\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2009</a>) where the critical curves are directly used as constraints. In Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig12\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig12\" data-open=\"fig12\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">12</a>, we show three solutions corresponding to three different numbers of iterations (where the number of parameters fitted and the initial condition in the minimization are identical between these three solutions). From left to right, we show the solutions obtained after 5000, 8000 and 15\u00a0000 iterations. By looking at the tangential curves, the three cases look different but they still accommodate well the large tangential arcs in between the tangential critical curve. The radial curve, on the other hand, when compared with the position of key well-identified radial arcs, is clearly too large in the case of 5000 iterations and too small in the case of 15\u00a0000 iterations. In contrast, in the case of 8000 iterations, the radial critical curve (computed for <em>z</em>\u00a0=\u00a02) overlaps almost perfectly with the mean position of different radial arcs present in the cluster at redshifts <em>z</em>\u00a0\u2248\u00a02. This simple comparison seems to indicate that the best solutions are obtained with our code after \u223c8000 iterations. Using the radial critical curve as a way of determining the optimal range of iterations can be also seen as a regularization of our problem. This is an interesting alternative since it is solely based on actual data.</p>                        <a id=\"21026358\" scrollto-destination=\"21026358\"></a>\r\n<div data-id=\"fig12\" class=\"fig fig-section js-fig-section\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 12.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig12.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&amp;Signature=AmtGC96h9p8GXF8zXGBTepjfGyOF3mPv2hzcCZvl6zy5zeWaUL1-p9yPZX~FJEoPUfog3WKX-WXwYYJkXyrUs4a9N1qDr7mLWRiHSofe6s0IgvTTnFR-fDtykSy07h1D3ZICPxTy7LCSX3K1bcJ7NzJaiJ17EEadzVsK8LZjnW3MtE1OLd3RaL-DOTgZRY7a9SeDFnT~O84FhlLl-1Kl8i0OQDPF8OF0Afh3Kw016nOJPYVCPsZWI9YkNNoqFVF34EGFyu98ZTYCku5tMqBemwDZi4pqg16KpSKIetks4HPflT9l-u1UkvtEhUl~DhGnoUWX-VwE81IaS-tN4eSCNQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Solutions (and associated critical curves for a source at redshift z\u00a0=\u00a02) for three different iteration numbers. Left corresponds to 5000 iterations, middle to 8000 iterations and right to 15\u00a0000 iterations. Note how for 8000 iterations both radial and tangential critical curves fall very close to radial and tangential arcs.\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig12.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026358/stu2064fig12.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig12.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026358\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig12.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&Signature=UyxYfYzzPciWm-NeDfa1AmhuBDQryRko38XlAAmZbV0Ek~bOY0lIvaMo64jZqD55P8fmN2Btne5iYSxTKdmdTSIGL3mRzM1T-pFdzIER712ZDfcTU7MJNCQT1Ym3CxcalAoTIpeu2cD0BaBp3FrjMKt1N1dxMrQz4HCRL261ARoBD8EL9ljoroCn0y2tDvVs8n7NomcdUryxrYQZwix1ZP6XYhGrzH6HZDqQWeVv~yizboBShoi5OCGN~f~X~hzFan9f5PqetvfQ2hVat4tjeIrm1IeN3XB2CysLpQZxK63zLVWlTurDG7zSaECVLq6aCdDYWa3jwELN6J3~ozlngA__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026358&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig12.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">Solutions (and associated critical curves for a source at redshift <em>z</em>\u00a0=\u00a02) for three different iteration numbers. Left corresponds to 5000 iterations, middle to 8000 iterations and right to 15\u00a0000 iterations. Note how for 8000 iterations both radial and tangential critical curves fall very close to radial and tangential arcs.</p></div></div><p class=\"chapter-para\">An idea of the dependence of the solution with the number of iterations can be obtained also from Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig13\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig13\" data-open=\"fig13\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">13</a>. In the top part of this plot, we represent the total mass contained in the grid (solid line) versus the iteration number. The solid and dashed lines represent the correction factors C<sub>1</sub> and C<sub>2</sub>, that are applied to the fiducial deflection fields from the galaxies. As the iteration number grows, there is a trade between the mass contained in the grid, and the mass in the galaxies but the total mass (especially in the central region) stays more or less constant beyond a few thousand iterations as can be seen better from the profiles (Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig14\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig14\" data-open=\"fig14\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">14</a>). A similar trend was observed when applying the method to simulated data (Sendra et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib44\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib44\" data-open=\"bib44\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2014</a>). As the iteration number grows, the solution increases its complexity in order to concentrate the arcs into smaller sources. As the fiducial field has only two degrees of freedom (<em>C</em><sub>1</sub> and <em>C</em><sub>2</sub>), new features appear only in the grid part of the solution at the expense of reducing the mass in the member galaxies to keep the total mass more or less constant (within the Einstein radius). Of course, and as mentioned earlier, to avoid overfitting, the minimization process has to be stopped at some point (stopping the minimization after a number of iterations could be seen also as a regularization process). In the range of iterations (6000\u201310\u00a0000) where reliable solutions exist, the changes in the model are small in the central 4 arcmin region. It is also important to note that the increased rise in mass in the grid part of the solution after 2000 iterations (see Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig13\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig13\" data-open=\"fig13\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">13</a>) is driven mostly by the cells in the outermost region (beyond the Einstein radius).</p>                        <a id=\"21026360\" scrollto-destination=\"21026360\"></a>\r\n<div data-id=\"fig13\" class=\"fig fig-section js-fig-section\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 13.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig13.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&amp;Signature=y-PB-kWCoTvQ1OnF0zMg6zoQ7ClY7SvDv~kaa31Px4K-V8Jbt3qlt7qoIzr7Ani32wnjYwOQXWVR4Frnnj9oYmi3Yh3IhG2fE8~fdYGurE5LZOFAcXXDkVdfqwxXTqz1tk-2hnfAtUzVtvfIlWkR7k-z~Wo-peTHacxU-xENQ-wDbF8EJZzGTmL-vrvN73yIH0G-iE0xQRWCM5hIjOLAebDsZc7GlyvIyKZq4CrJkCpwD1sF5aOP2kWeJ4ta-pYzhx-78bMvFFaAuYnlCRcUV-vD7fSXqx5iuZ59QX0yqrAb-WCFGjVr7UAbkj2yD27WIFoOUGssbN0OuKqHHue9zw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Top panel: total mass in the grid (solid line) versus iteration number (from 1 to 15\u00a0000).
