Again, the smaller subplot shows the tails of these distributions across the transition phase and up the 5\u2009arcmin maximum radius.\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig14.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026361/stu2064fig14.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig14.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026361\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig14.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&Signature=NfgI3yS4iMbwVDuiljEWAPSyNdzH~mgpK3DM~gJxaJSivoiEnr3OOs5LTRziiWVOwXH6PhjYr1u4XrzAtnhQV06qLyrfk~kofJn3PcgiqKZdcLLzeTWFPhEF4XkXLpyUoXr7ZLFSycISrMBvLmtl5NxKqwErOLFShifTOw~EAkHNltlpxg0aUgvMcEshQTcmM-6sPZFCC6Vn~flymVqV4NDBP6e3gJGZTNZGyfPoaVOCr7rDSOCxiKeRvWq~YKPa7Od~kBguhIoxEaW45thqLlREBmqA22v8-28Wk2X3SiDdvZlDZ5bYTeRSxhPcV79RvGooF-kLMcrAVbv8qeEgGg__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026361&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig14.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">Convergence profiles for the three cases shown in Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig12\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig12\" data-open=\"fig12\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">12</a>. The solid line corresponds to the 5000 iteration case, the dotted line to the 8000 iteration case and dashed line to the 15000 iteration case. Again, the smaller subplot shows the tails of these distributions across the transition phase and up the 5\u2009arcmin maximum radius.</p></div></div><div content-id=\"fig14\" class=\"fig fig-modal reveal-modal\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 14.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig14.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&amp;Signature=Tzg4XZ6n2nEj1s2hB3OLhIld4t24d3yZr287hv3mxZr2xlYJOiOvdc4TCoRnXX1F~ZF0wfsnDAW2C81ZAsh6YH2Wi3GgDMAm8mTl4Az6riVSMyBl6R3QljrhLAhnpNonaCCpo9XslmmUcr3BdtySjFviCUNAsprMAVc9GGZ2ZWRwI0xajIukoaSdnrosJtyqFKkmBfzABluKa2Opr53WhQGo9Qt89~tf4dapTLmCyGk5CqqI0b34JQX5iAGYG450EM89UgpR5Ha5mlLtElvoH2DL0p0QwBDLqCqZFSv5Uk1vzixkN6eUlutN2FTCdk6pQ6gfa7W9pU94K-isAI9lVQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Convergence profiles for the three cases shown in Fig.\u00a012. The solid line corresponds to the 5000 iteration case, the dotted line to the 8000 iteration case and dashed line to the 15000 iteration case. Again, the smaller subplot shows the tails of these distributions across the transition phase and up the 5\u2009arcmin maximum radius.\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig14.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026361/stu2064fig14.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig14.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026361\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig14.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&Signature=NfgI3yS4iMbwVDuiljEWAPSyNdzH~mgpK3DM~gJxaJSivoiEnr3OOs5LTRziiWVOwXH6PhjYr1u4XrzAtnhQV06qLyrfk~kofJn3PcgiqKZdcLLzeTWFPhEF4XkXLpyUoXr7ZLFSycISrMBvLmtl5NxKqwErOLFShifTOw~EAkHNltlpxg0aUgvMcEshQTcmM-6sPZFCC6Vn~flymVqV4NDBP6e3gJGZTNZGyfPoaVOCr7rDSOCxiKeRvWq~YKPa7Od~kBguhIoxEaW45thqLlREBmqA22v8-28Wk2X3SiDdvZlDZ5bYTeRSxhPcV79RvGooF-kLMcrAVbv8qeEgGg__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026361&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig14.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">Convergence profiles for the three cases shown in Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig12\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig12\" data-open=\"fig12\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">12</a>. The solid line corresponds to the 5000 iteration case, the dotted line to the 8000 iteration case and dashed line to the 15000 iteration case. Again, the smaller subplot shows the tails of these distributions across the transition phase and up the 5\u2009arcmin maximum radius.</p></div></div><p class=\"chapter-para\">It can also be seen (see the inset in the upper-right corner of Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig14\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig14\" data-open=\"fig14\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">14</a>) that as the iteration number grows, the grid starts to accumulate mass in the transition phase between the 6.66\u2009arcmin region and the buffer zone. The bottom panel of Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig13\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig13\" data-open=\"fig13\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">13</a> shows the quantity that is being minimized (properly re-scaled by some constant for clarity) as a function of the iteration number.</p><p class=\"chapter-para\">When looking at how the mass evolves in the different cells as a function of the iteration number, we observe that the central regions converge first and the outer regions converge last. The region around the buffer zone starts to monotonically grow in mass after a few thousand iterations. For a very large iteration number, the inner region stays stable and most of the changes in mass occur beyond the Einstein radius.</p>                    <h3 scrollto-destination=21026364 id=\"21026364\" class=\"section-title js-splitscreen-section-title\" data-legacy-id=sec7-2>7.2 Dependence with the initial guess</h3>\r\n<p class=\"chapter-para\">When minimizing a multidimensional quadratic function, one can find infinite solutions (for a given error) by varying the starting point of the minimization, all of them equally good in the sense of fitting the data set. The regions in the lens plane that are more sensitive to the data will converge quickly towards stationary points while regions with weaker sensitivity to the data might vary more from minimization to minimization or even not vary significantly and retain values close to their initial values (memory effect).</p><p class=\"chapter-para\">In Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig15\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig15\" data-open=\"fig15\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">15</a>, we show the average (solid) and 1\u03c3 region (dotted) of 40 reconstructions where in each one we change the initial condition by setting it to a vector of random numbers obtained from a Gaussian distribution. The dispersion of this Gaussian distribution is a random variable itself and is such that the total mass in the initial condition takes values in the range [\u223c0.2, \u223c2]\u00a0\u00d7\u00a010<sup>15</sup>\u2009M<sub>\u2299</sub>\u2009<em>h</em><sup>\u22121</sup>. Table\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-tbl1\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"tbl1\" data-open=\"tbl1\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">1</a> includes the values of the mean and errors as a function of distance. The solution retains some memory of the initial condition specially in the outer region where the constraints in the solution are the weakest. The most remarkable aspect of this plot is that all solutions seem to converge to the same profile in the range 20\u201330\u2009arcsec defining a <em>stability</em> region for the solution.</p>                        <a id=\"21026367\" scrollto-destination=\"21026367\"></a>\r\n<div content-id=\"tbl1\" class=\"table-modal table-full-width-wrap\"><div class=\"table-wrap table-wide\"><div class=\"table-wrap-title\" id=\"tbl1\" data-id=\"tbl1\"><span class=\"label\">Table 1.</span><div class=\"caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">Mean profile and dispersion of the 40 solutions shown in Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig15\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig15\" data-open=\"fig15\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">15</a>. Both the mean profile and dispersion are given in units of \u03a3/\u03a3<sub>crit</sub> with \u03a3<sub>crit</sub> computed at <em>z</em>\u00a0=\u00a01.07. The last column shows the integrated (cylindrical) mass in units of 10<sup>14</sup>\u2009M<sub>\u2299</sub>\u2009<em>h</em><sup>\u22121</sup>.</p></div> </div><div ble></div><div class=\"&#xA;          graphic-wrap&#xA;          \"><a class=\"fig-view-orig openInAnotherWindow btn js-view-large\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"/view-large/21026367\">\r\n          Open in new tab\r\n        </a></div></div></div><p class=\"chapter-para\">This convergence is made more evident when looking at the 2D version of the above result. In Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig16\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig16\" data-open=\"fig16\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">16</a> , we show the average of the mass solutions (left-hand panel) from which the above profile is derived. The middle panel shows the dispersion of the mass map and the right-hand panel shows the signal-to-noise ratio (or SNR) defined as the ratio of the left-hand and middle panels. There is a remarkably well-defined circular region of high SNR around 20\u201330\u2009arcsec from the centre. In this region, the solutions seem to be insensitive to the initial condition and they all render almost identical results. This region corresponds to a stability region of the solution where the profile is constrained very well. A second interesting aspect can be seen also in the SNR map. The high SNR of the DM blob (SNR\u00a0\u2248\u00a016), just south of the stability region (i.e the bright blob approximately 2.5 arcmin from the centre of the image on the right-hand panel of Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig16\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig16\" data-open=\"fig16\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">16</a>), indicates that this might be a real substructure. This feature has not been previously claimed and indeed parametric methods would not incorporate such dark substructure in principle. Other interesting features emerge from the SNR map as potential real substructures of the cluster although with a lower SNR. The dispersion map shows how there is a region (upper-right quadrant) where the solutions fluctuate the most indicating that the mass map is less reliable in this region.</p>                        <a id=\"21026369\" scrollto-destination=\"21026369\"></a>\r\n<div data-id=\"fig15\" class=\"fig fig-section js-fig-section\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 15.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig15.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&amp;Signature=JuM9LUxISM-GdNpDfcOD93~sdusO~hoPrHzBc07RqLqzoisDlocLyIT56CTgHj78tcUj9ks3FTjKPHuRFrzeql3Knptu14l1i2NxIoNTAO1H80OeDSuwLOoj~dZAmecjx0yTlWIDWURPvra-BxXV-ricM2u5lIpHoDYplO2Ylu-70iPzgbNhlxhRCEmZ9PnLBGm3Y22xfHR1CtaXgZbWCIrlhmkh~WnCR4GVR5cqWD5vPWRmwdrWR4PHV6csiM03I2v6ZjeMfMtE8R5XLsnqlkXJfnMvivE~iLatzlHESLdTrlOF-sZYlZSpUChHJ5sq1jjJrH-WRshFmwb5R3LqHQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Average profile of the convergence from 40 independent solutions (solid line). The middle panel shows the dispersion of these solutions. The right-hand panel shows the SNR map defined as the average map (left-hand panel) divided by the dispersion map (middle panel). The SNR vary between SNR = 0.7 at its minimum and SNR = 290 at its maximum (but saturated in this plot above SNR = 100). All maps are shown as the square root (in order to increase contrast) and the colour scale (shown in the right-hand panel) is the same in all panels.</p></div></div><p class=\"chapter-para\">Finally, as expected (and already shown in the profile plot), the dispersion of the solutions in the central region (that is, around the cD galaxy) is larger, indicating therefore that our solution is not very sensitive to the very central region. This is due mostly to the fact that the larger arcs have a bigger weight in our solution. In a future paper, we aim to study in more detail the most central region taking advantage of the stability region identified in this paper, and the possible implications for the mass profile of the cD galaxy.</p>                    <h3 scrollto-destination=21026372 id=\"21026372\" class=\"section-title js-splitscreen-section-title\" data-legacy-id=sec7-3>7.3 Dependence with the number of systems and redshift</h3>\r\n<p class=\"chapter-para\">Identifying pairs of images in the SL regime is not always free of subjectivity, resting on experience. A1689 is probably the most scrutinized lens, with hundreds of arclets seen in the image, each with its own distortion that makes it difficult to find morphologically similar galaxies. The colours may also vary across the object due to differential magnification, and also because of overlap with other unrelated images or due to diffuse light in the cluster affecting the colours of relatively faint background galaxies. Spectroscopic redshifts of the arclets are often the best way to discriminate among different possibilities but even this does not always settle the differences and furthermore neighbouring galaxies may become confused in the process if they have the same redshift to within the resolution limits. A good example of this is the difficulty to distinguish between systems 10 and 12 (both having basically the same spectroscopic redshift). Different authors have assigned the arclets to different systems (see Table\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-tbl2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"tbl2\" data-open=\"tbl2\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">A1</a>). In this section, we explore the impact on the solution when we consider different subsets of arclets in our SL part of the data set.</p><p class=\"chapter-para\">In Table\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-tbl2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"tbl2\" data-open=\"tbl2\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">A1</a>, we compile all the systems that were found in the literature and we add several new systems (candidates) which are identified with our model. For the new systems, we simply assume that they are at redshift <em>z</em>\u00a0=\u00a02 when assessing their deflection angles. This is a useful approximation given the weak dependence of the deflection angles over the range <em>z</em>\u00a0=\u00a0[1, 3] (as shown by Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig11\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig11\" data-open=\"fig11\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">11</a>) and should be sufficient for our purposes. For our test, we compare our reference solution described in Section\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-sec5\"></span><a href=\"#sec5\" class=\"sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec\">5</a>, which depended on only the 26 established systems, with new model solutions obtained for sets of images composed in the following three ways. </p><ul class=\"roman-lower\"><li><p class=\"chapter-para\">We consider the extended sample of systems listed in Table\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-tbl2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"tbl2\" data-open=\"tbl2\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">A1</a> but exclude sources 25 and 32 for which multiple options exist for the same system. That is, we consider 48 sources out of the total 50 systems listed in Table\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-tbl2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"tbl2\" data-open=\"tbl2\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">A1</a>.</p></li><li><p class=\"chapter-para\">As a second subsample, we consider the subset of 18 sources from the original 26 sources of our reference solution for which spectroscopic redshifts are available, in Table\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-tbl2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"tbl2\" data-open=\"tbl2\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">A1</a>.</p></li><li><p class=\"chapter-para\">The third subsample is the same as the original sample of 26 but for the sources with photometric redshifts, we allow the redshifts to vary (uniformly) by a generous 2\u03c3 error, adopting the \u03c3 values in Coe et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib11\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib11\" data-open=\"bib11\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2010</a>).</p></li></ul><p class=\"chapter-para\">The extended data set of 48 systems is displayed in Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig17\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig17\" data-open=\"fig17\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">17</a> where the original 26 systems are shown in black and the additional 22 systems in white. For each case, we reproduce the minimization process of Section\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-sec5\"></span><a href=\"#sec5\" class=\"sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec\">5</a> that is, we adopt the same initial condition, number of iterations and make use of both SL and WL data, in order to better examine model differences resulting from changes of the data set. Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig18\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig18\" data-open=\"fig18\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">18</a> shows this comparison in terms of the resulting mass profiles for the above cases.</p>                        <a id=\"21026377\" scrollto-destination=\"21026377\"></a>\r\n<div data-id=\"fig17\" class=\"fig fig-section js-fig-section\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 17.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig17.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&amp;Signature=23b54Co0trHEn669LnqTS5ZKUi2IdrdTwy2oXIBB7RxUDNRUH9~02PiOlykRyAwqRGUAIKD~9LLXZh2tvRLELIeer7QcBnjfb6CtHA2C92X6ou46DjqTYIn0W6op0Zsd3YVmxmcnM-V8Y03M4JfmjP-y88SMnvraiALdOawpjN4rIjWw3Zye-FaAugvom~JILAFvQVeBcTZVALYYPbvMQ~P0pY-bBpNVLyOtR8RQ3~m5uDHxyVBo6YPcRxuCNfzE93bY2Fd1oiQkqFvbpWEBFG~VgdGFGOhwReuyEY3FoWM~SzqozJvn0b2L-M3uteuDjVV2QyUQFb1vPjLDvZQ--g__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"In black, the original robust data set of 26 sources. The solid, dotted, dashed and dot\u2013dashed line have the same meaning as in the top panel.\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig18.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026380/stu2064fig18.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig18.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026380\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig18.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&Signature=cNYeDa~SBXc8o2Bx3l0RaJWX-jAuZG-PhUG4Xscq0wmY2ZExhVlVfzp0tUogUWaeZtRnt3yfw3xkbTsugcMAabJNbavG9lXZ2TfvlYe439tIts1yxxlcq7L7RJle9k3NXujMadV3ecpW5UqlPAZTHqliMslbr5ekTjlCXdeAVh5jIi1te9BYmDumMa7ltxQZRXymxj9ovzeCsTwAhl3y-7D1zhwehVtRyFqDMIegDvwmE798TVXgnHBcPeSIOKrhjVOPYPF8l1yAG0JGsLWBt~6qOyrN4Y0w3bLVW1IYCaQfecJL2JkgJRznWf2D8ZhnAQgyrO02l-QZpN~IyXniQA__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026380&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig18.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">Comparison of the profiles obtained with different subsets of sources. The thick solid line corresponds to our reference solution (26 sources). The dotted line corresponds to the solution obtained with the full sample of in Table\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-tbl2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"tbl2\" data-open=\"tbl2\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">A1</a> (we exclude sources 25 and 32), or case (i) (see text). The dashed line corresponds to the subset with spectroscopic redshifts (18 sources) or case (ii) (see text) and the dot\u2013dashed line corresponds to the same initial set of 26 sources but the sources with photo-<em>z</em> taking different redshifts, or case (iii) (see text). The bottom panel shows the relative difference between the different curves (B) and the reference model (A). The solid, dotted, dashed and dot\u2013dashed line have the same meaning as in the top panel.</p></div></div><div class=\"&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            \">Although there are some differences between the different solutions, the agreement is still remarkably good indicating that all data sets have enough common systems to produce similar results and/or that the solution is not very sensitive to modest changes in the redshift of some systems. This agreement indicates most simply that the systems in the extended sample naturally give good fits when the reference solution is used. The last point is highlighted better in the second last column of Table\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-tbl2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"tbl2\" data-open=\"tbl2\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">A1</a> where we show the \u0394\u03b2 for each arclet (and based on the reference solution). The \u0394\u03b2 for a specific arclet <em>i</em> is defined as <div class=\"formula-wrap\"><div class=\"disp-formula\" id=\"equ5\" content-id=\"equ5\"><div class=\"tex-math display-math\"> \\begin{equation}\r\n\\Delta \\beta _i(\\mathrm{arcsec}) = |\\beta _i - \\langle \\beta \\rangle |,\r\n\\end{equation} </div></div><span class=\"label\">(5)</span></div>where \u03b2<sub><em>i</em></sub> is the predicted position of the arclet in the source plane when the reference solution is used and \u3008\u03b2\u3009 is the average of all the \u03b2<sub><em>i</em></sub> for that system. As shown by the values of \u0394\u03b2 (expressed in arcseconds), most arclets lie at reasonable distances (few arcseconds) from their common centre in the source plane. Also, some systems appear to be problematic since they have large \u0394\u03b2 values (10\u2009arcsec or more, like in systems 25, 41, 44). These systems are either incorrect or our reference solution has substantial errors around the position of these systems. In other cases, like system 7, the arclet 7.3 (\u0394\u03b2\u00a0=\u00a09.3\u2009arcsec) is very close to the central cD galaxy and surrounded by multiple small sources (7.3, together with 8.5, and 19.5 were also rejected by Coe et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib11\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib11\" data-open=\"bib11\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2010</a>). It is possible that either the reference solution is not accurate at the centre (see discussion in Section\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-sec7-2\"></span><a href=\"#sec7-2\" class=\"sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec\">7.2</a>) or that 7.3 does not correspond with the source listed in Table\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-tbl2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"tbl2\" data-open=\"tbl2\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">A1</a> but another one in the vicinity. If that is the case, this explains why 7.1 and 7.2 (which are clearly the same source), have also relatively high values of \u0394\u03b2 since a bad association for 7.3 would bias \u3008\u03b2\u3009 and enhance the \u0394\u03b2 for all the system.</div><p class=\"chapter-para\">Another interesting point from Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig18\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig18\" data-open=\"fig18\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">18</a>, is that the same stability region discussed in Section\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-sec7-2\"></span><a href=\"#sec7-2\" class=\"sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec\">7.2</a> seems to be present when we change the SL data set, in the range 20\u201330\u2009arcsec, where the solutions seem to be insensitive to the particular choice of data sets (among the four used in this comparison). This reinforces the idea that the solution is very well constrained in this regime (20\u201330\u2009arcsec) and nearly insensitive to the intrinsic variation of the solutions.</p><p class=\"chapter-para\">Going beyond the differences in profile, we look at the mass maps for the above cases, comparing the reference solution and the three solutions described above. The result is shown in Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig19\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig19\" data-open=\"fig19\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">19</a>. In this case, the mass difference has been divided by the profile of the reference solution to increase contrast. Also, the middle panel has been saturated below values of \u22121.7 (the most negative value was \u22125) also for contrast purposes. The difference maps show where the surface mass density modifies itself in order to accommodate the possible changes in the data set and by extension, it marks the regions where extra caution needs to be taken into account when interpreting our main results, should the assumed original data set of 26 sources be compromised by systematics.</p>                        <a id=\"21026384\" scrollto-destination=\"21026384\"></a>\r\n<div data-id=\"fig19\" class=\"fig fig-section js-fig-section\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 19.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig19.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&amp;Signature=eIns0XR2R01fq0cOYyeAJXcNWqKeNnGZL11wYgJdz~3rkULMjpm43ulkiHozqZOIxViHF5Ls27g6XIYVpv4HKMjnXdVjV8qfhWH0Skl6v9vwHXZ6NWx3Qk48hQ82o2FlDp600LAqLFFIwE~rNeOLDOL~RXrT1~QcsaQbfUU8LZUiYmjDuUSkoQ-amH3CxLeP6JqmOWw9zzx4rErrviHHUS1KWiSqF6B~qrxoZZHYnk7w76Ir9qB2llYfTO2aeQbhAK6tqGiVM-6a7lmuD7YtiSEdw7da8Kl9MlfW2kIIfrteNHRwlLgUc5~fweuHvIRYxr6GS773UYGdDOm-NUDRow__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"The figures show the difference between our reference solution and solutions obtained with three alternative subsets of sources. Ideally, we would set a large number of cells that allows for a more detailed reconstruction. In practice however, a very large number of cells results only in a more noisy reconstruction that needs to be smoothed (regularized). The smoothed image captures the main eigenmodes of the solution that would be reconstructed also with a smaller number of cells. Also, a large number of cells implies a larger system of equations to resolve and a slower convergence. This limits the ability to explore the space of possible solutions, which is important. On the other hand, a very small number of cells results in a more compact system of linear equations that can be resolved fast but at the expense of not capturing some of the potentially smaller scale details of the mass distribution and consequently forcing the entire mass distribution to adopt, often erroneous, distributions in order to fit the observations. As shown by Ponente &amp; Diego (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib41\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib41\" data-open=\"bib41\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2011</a>) and Sendra et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib44\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib44\" data-open=\"bib44\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2014</a>), a low-resolution grid can still produce reliable solutions but only after allowing for a larger error in the reconstruction. Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig20\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig20\" data-open=\"fig20\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">20</a> shows the reconstructed solution when a lower resolution grid is used. In this case, all the cell sizes are the same and equal to 25\u00a0\u00d7\u00a025 arcsec<sup>2</sup>. The solution obtained with this regular grid resembles a smoothed version of the reference solution except in the radial critical curve where the lack of resolution does not allow for a detailed reconstruction. In this case, the values of <em>C</em><sub>1</sub> and <em>C</em><sub>2</sub> are 0.26 and 0.23, respectively.</p>                        <a id=\"21026388\" scrollto-destination=\"21026388\"></a>\r\n<div data-id=\"fig20\" class=\"fig fig-section js-fig-section\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 20.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig20.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&amp;Signature=LHs3xp5Edy-CCONoyjqYej2SUEblslzzK-hd6AyCP4HVVICzSod1ApzSdJQgV1RRzhZFMNPtfZTT6ICcOI5VFjw2RxytsmlEtzkN9LuDHg~idm8bG~e3zXwXLv3CG~~JPhL1yJf0q8C46D3hc4NasX~NQVWbqomcerJN75cibperQRy~GW9GOv9UKxV0HwESdaUSYmHZHGjbR7k6z~~BPGDVVvlvn3MQmzXoSNlGWx~waX9lzeSKjCwng253iNsnxossIcvZ6xKBsh12mKHeHl7qJuDUkQ6jHgycmRWdFbuEukkiSaV9Evcvd34cYY8VwPRnqFu8bamdY-Mqaz08~Q__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Mass and critical curve for a low-resolution grid reconstruction (SL+WL). The cell sizes are 2.7\u00a0times larger in this case than in the reference solution.\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig20.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026388/stu2064fig20.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig20.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026388\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig20.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&Signature=xQ6issEApKzX4quZmOobLFVSL8Uct0KvE9lEwmaEuJbW7cywf3frpOGM7Fwmc~4KthR9KbrdPr5vYWpNTENVZIw6nBBRP-NVvS2jTH4drJWoI~TAIXGy6xYW-mXjOT1azhoI~ulaD~~mhURIR7h0Zl6W52sYGjsX1XIsKnjhQCTjXJUZnQh5q0gSGCay~TU4ykx1jXn29B5oTPDPooJanAfCoUxJnsova4EiRDKVxSw6WD4RstPPj4Rwp~Aa5uAzPmS3xksI50Zhyo7VKFfPMsLzt9XEqCtyeX~AK~~NKl6mOOljCE0NQn3SKn4Z4p49To7LnEQgW2VWKzZh4K7lGQ__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026388&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig20.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">Mass and critical curve for a low-resolution grid reconstruction (SL+WL). The cell sizes are 2.7\u00a0times larger in this case than in the reference solution.</p></div></div><div content-id=\"fig20\" class=\"fig fig-modal reveal-modal\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 20.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig20.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&amp;Signature=LHs3xp5Edy-CCONoyjqYej2SUEblslzzK-hd6AyCP4HVVICzSod1ApzSdJQgV1RRzhZFMNPtfZTT6ICcOI5VFjw2RxytsmlEtzkN9LuDHg~idm8bG~e3zXwXLv3CG~~JPhL1yJf0q8C46D3hc4NasX~NQVWbqomcerJN75cibperQRy~GW9GOv9UKxV0HwESdaUSYmHZHGjbR7k6z~~BPGDVVvlvn3MQmzXoSNlGWx~waX9lzeSKjCwng253iNsnxossIcvZ6xKBsh12mKHeHl7qJuDUkQ6jHgycmRWdFbuEukkiSaV9Evcvd34cYY8VwPRnqFu8bamdY-Mqaz08~Q__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Mass and critical curve for a low-resolution grid reconstruction (SL+WL). The cell sizes are 2.7\u00a0times larger in this case than in the reference solution.\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig20.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026388/stu2064fig20.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig20.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026388\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig20.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&Signature=xQ6issEApKzX4quZmOobLFVSL8Uct0KvE9lEwmaEuJbW7cywf3frpOGM7Fwmc~4KthR9KbrdPr5vYWpNTENVZIw6nBBRP-NVvS2jTH4drJWoI~TAIXGy6xYW-mXjOT1azhoI~ulaD~~mhURIR7h0Zl6W52sYGjsX1XIsKnjhQCTjXJUZnQh5q0gSGCay~TU4ykx1jXn29B5oTPDPooJanAfCoUxJnsova4EiRDKVxSw6WD4RstPPj4Rwp~Aa5uAzPmS3xksI50Zhyo7VKFfPMsLzt9XEqCtyeX~AK~~NKl6mOOljCE0NQn3SKn4Z4p49To7LnEQgW2VWKzZh4K7lGQ__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026388&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig20.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">Mass and critical curve for a low-resolution grid reconstruction (SL+WL). The cell sizes are 2.7\u00a0times larger in this case than in the reference solution.</p></div></div><p class=\"chapter-para\">A compromise alternative would be to use a multiresolution grid where regions with a complex mass distribution are sampled with smaller cells and regions with a more smooth mass distribution (or less sensitive to the data) are sampled with larger cells. This possibility was explored in previous papers and produces satisfactory results although it is not entirely free of problems. In particular, the boundary region between regions of differing resolution tends to produce biased results (when tested with simulated data). The size of the cell normally introduces a prior in the solution. The reconstruction tends to put more mass in the smallest cells. This problem can be mitigated by solving in an iterative way where the first iteration assumes a regular grid (no prior) and the consecutive iterations increase the resolution in regions where the previous iteration found more mass. We have tried a battery of configurations and found that some of them (in particular those with multiresolution) produce significant artefacts in the solution that need to be avoided. Regular grids are always more stable and reliable so in our particular case and due to the large field of view involved (10\u00a0\u00d7\u00a010 arcmin<sup>2</sup>) we choose a grid with good resolution in the central field of view (6\u00a0\u00d7\u00a06 arcmin<sup>2</sup>) and a lower resolution grid in the outer region (buffer zone). As expected, the solution near the boundary between the two regions produce artefacts as discussed above. We have checked that variations in the grid sizes of \u223c30\u2009per\u2009cent with respect to our configuration, finding the results are nearly identical to the those presented in this paper. The cell sizes in the central part of the field of view are larger than the halo sizes of the galaxies (except the central galaxy) facilitating the orthogonality of the grid+galaxy base.</p>                    <h3 scrollto-destination=21026390 id=\"21026390\" class=\"section-title js-splitscreen-section-title\" data-legacy-id=sec7-5>7.5 Dependence with the parameters in the fiducial model</h3>\r\n<p class=\"chapter-para\">In order to test the sensitivity of the solution to the assumptions made for the adopted profile for the member galaxy component, we compare the reference solution (solid line in Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig21\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig21\" data-open=\"fig21\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">21</a>) with two different assumptions regarding galaxy profiles. In the first case (dotted line in Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig21\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig21\" data-open=\"fig21\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">21</a>), we vary both the total mass of each galaxy and the scale radius by a factor \u223c2 (above and below the values in the reference solution) so the ratio between the new masses or scale radii with respect to the ones in the reference model is around 2. In the second case (dotted line in Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig21\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig21\" data-open=\"fig21\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">21</a>), we take the extreme (and unrealistic) case where all the masses in the galaxies are considered to be in just the centre of each galaxy (that is, galaxies are considered delta functions) and we also change their masses by a factor \u223c2 with respect to the reference solution case. Remarkably, there is a region of stability (around 20\u201340\u2009arcsec) where the profile seems to be unaffected by the particular choice of the fiducial deflection field, even in the case where we consider unphysical assumptions for the fiducial field (delta function case for the galaxy masses). The dotted line (different NFW profiles for each galaxy) is almost indistinguishable from the reference solution. The dashed line case (delta functions) shows a relative deficit in mass at very short radii, since all the mass of the central galaxy is concentrated at (<em>r</em>\u00a0=\u00a00) which is not shown in the plot. At larger radii (<em>r</em>\u00a0=\u00a050\u2013100\u2009arcsec), the grid part of the solution shows an excess of mass (with respect to the reference solution). This might be due to a compensation effect of the unphysical nature of the delta function assumption although this is not observed at <em>r</em>\u00a0=\u00a020\u201330\u2009arcsec. When finding solutions, we are of course dealing with the deflection field and since this relates to the gradient of the potential we may not be so surprised about the independence of the resulting model mass distribution with the choice of galaxy profile, since the galaxy potential is always extended even in the case of point masses.</p>                        <a id=\"21026392\" scrollto-destination=\"21026392\"></a>\r\n<div data-id=\"fig21\" class=\"fig fig-section js-fig-section\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 21.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig21.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&amp;Signature=u04x59CUkbOuqtMqC8gHJ3uPjCDbo2SveiJ8eoh3opVyVP2V95t4Xgn0rJjX2vUrQO3H5~V0B2QlFZ~bKN6r4yJdZ3TcwFmjGX~fSb8iGIF1DFnoswpog6fCgosbiGMFucc6mBl8fiGcEvKWFQxRtSlaaUUTi58gDZJQv0s7UGj3wEW9mJZRpg54zQ~5CCXNLLEPM9sedKDrUcJ6fqYzAj-XtbJh8GBajIaXmQ6qjAnBV8IHa~JyAWkPOES76ipRnZ8TkkFbZmC9mqq7zjhramUYfxgRNcB3TGL9rQsrQAborkjNSVf-5fLqqZ5VzV4ESCUO98uERgCyRyr0zPRa6g__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Changes in the reconstructed profile under three assumptions for the member galaxies in the cluster. The solid line corresponds to the reference solution discussed above, the dotted line is for a different model where both the scale radius and total mass of the assumed NFW profile for the individual galaxies is changed by a factor \u223c2. The dashed line corresponds to another different realization of the masses in the galaxies (different also by a factor \u223c2 with respect to the reference model) but their profiles are taken to the extreme case of delta functions. For the dashed line, there is a peak at the centre not shown in this plot that corresponds to the central galaxy.\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig21.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026392/stu2064fig21.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig21.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026392\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig21.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&Signature=dqVYK2PyONp5lAcgBRBN25ztT~s6SJLGkmQRZF3zxC10TwhYz7nfmLMY4kFoeGnWe6XFu0kn5rNrqakIOZ5OseNLahQkqnN2kzSig1yG98Y~vOskBp9rkEsD7a~Yw4J1Z9FZxMjx5MD8u79~y-85hAk61OUl7GFY4o9eRgjMQDui-CtfdlH4Q3AZxTrw-L7UWEXwvK04Bqr0BBhW1u1KUQ7I94C~NI81pSOpBJZ37FWAwL6irOS0-RgCraDC6qtvzwNy4C~BV2DDCQYJ8b208U8Q9WcXdYl4DrV62y3ZtjARM1RVY3K9n5XvNtEVRn0zEb4EXuYxTpCTh61GWGC1bg__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026392&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig21.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">Changes in the reconstructed profile under three assumptions for the member galaxies in the cluster. The solid line corresponds to the reference solution discussed above, the dotted line is for a different model where both the scale radius and total mass of the assumed NFW profile for the individual galaxies is changed by a factor \u223c2. The dashed line corresponds to another different realization of the masses in the galaxies (different also by a factor \u223c2 with respect to the reference model) but their profiles are taken to the extreme case of delta functions. The solid line corresponds to the reference solution discussed above, the dotted line is for a different model where both the scale radius and total mass of the assumed NFW profile for the individual galaxies is changed by a factor \u223c2. The dashed line corresponds to another different realization of the masses in the galaxies (different also by a factor \u223c2 with respect to the reference model) but their profiles are taken to the extreme case of delta functions. For the dashed line, there is a peak at the centre not shown in this plot that corresponds to the central galaxy.</p></div></div>                    <h2 scrollto-destination=21026394 id=\"21026394\" class=\"section-title js-splitscreen-section-title\" data-legacy-id=sec8>8 PREDICTED NEW SYSTEMS/ARCS</h2>\r\n<p class=\"chapter-para\">Using our solution (masses and source positions) for the case of SL+WL and 8000 iterations in Section\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-sec5\"></span><a href=\"#sec5\" class=\"sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec\">5</a>, we can predict the position of the multiple images for each source. In most cases, the agreement between these positions and the observed arcs is very good with typical errors of less than 5\u2009arcmin in the image plane but there are some deviations between the model and the data set that are interesting to explore in more detail. Disagreements between the predicted arcs and input data might reveal a systematic bias in the solution in that particular region of the image plane or even some tension between the identification of the multiple images in the data set. Also, new images (from a given system) might be identified with the new model. Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig22\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig22\" data-open=\"fig22\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">22</a> shows two interesting cases. In dark grey, we show the distance to the source position when that particular point in the image plane is projected back into the source plane at the redshift of the source (its inverse can be seen as the probability of having a counterimage). White crosses mark the observed position of the arcs in the original data set while black crosses show the predicted position of the delensed observed positions. These systems together with the remaining systems in Table\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-tbl2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"tbl2\" data-open=\"tbl2\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">A1</a> can be found online at this website.<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fn6\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fn6\" data-open=\"fn6\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-fn js-xref-fn\"><sup>6</sup></a> The reader should keep in mind that the predictions are based on the reference model that is obtained only from 26 systems, so systems 32 and beyond in Table\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-tbl2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"tbl2\" data-open=\"tbl2\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">A1</a> are not used to constrain this model. The predictions for these systems are useful to check how consistent the second half of Table\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-tbl2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"tbl2\" data-open=\"tbl2\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">A1</a> (systems 32 and above) is with the first half.</p>                        <a id=\"21026396\" scrollto-destination=\"21026396\"></a>\r\n<div data-id=\"fig22\" class=\"fig fig-section js-fig-section\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 22.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig22.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&amp;Signature=o9-jJl7fwRa75ZFhzb2FdnhrXH97cbs01ts9asGNOP3unxuBLtMUR0rUeejjomxRUOYxFQSAy1G-g0kK~seTTkvxvzQ2xB5imBSgyJeXHzFFJzhjtAonhMK-M6RlZD2e-rPz4AgAitYGRrAkNxWsRerJqFoe6Em~eb31SMjqP~Xeu2Qbf96~XdeSRwCMDgzDVtMITEC60c8~jE7Vev-xtzIb3ZXSulOfgH6~oASFYDPMir9vXBhTcu0DQWfq7ORp4NJJl19quToAYReztu-nADBduiGV-OUYw--cnbr2-CEKyFfkZH~ysL9X7fCTvgQ-J7m7y0r4zqXmRHx~wmSAyw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Predicted positions for systems 12 (left) and 22 (right). The observed positions are shown as white crosses and the prediction positions in dark grey. The smaller black crosses correspond to the deprojected observed positions. For system 12, the solution correctly predicts an arclet (on the right-hand side) identified by Limousin et\u00a0al. (2007). For system 22, no counterimage is found at or near the position predicted by the solution (bottom right).\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig22.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026396/stu2064fig22.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig22.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026396\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig22.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&Signature=Sers5rjimDmONX5HDvLCu2mCsRMHk1-IA3Wdl0PhSBts7FVxoj7of1DRyzZ09UFHtwNLeEdetAo9QP2b4~WuZa-Ktlc~kW3IN5demRVmF-0k8L6rB4Ef4Wdkyld3awYSYk7~YloOQblCGQ9WUX130xPM5sIrAZa2IfgcZ7-EMPdUc68GSZhBLqB6fw8bBVaCX0gHtOhoF-O9kxkKRQxcrUi7Lj1KcROTTXYXSPEH16YqKzpDbk9yCgFss23du~TQicmyKFnSw0bsTmSWXoqr36fX3ccxugDo7UhPGC-3uFGjOlvWtTMIoeuYu2EtWgiyjX6Fcv1EtSzwmyazcEQ5KQ__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026396&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig22.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">Predicted positions for systems 12 (left) and 22 (right). The observed positions are shown as white crosses and the prediction positions in dark grey. The smaller black crosses correspond to the deprojected observed positions. For system 12, the solution correctly predicts an arclet (on the right-hand side) identified by Limousin et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib31\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib31\" data-open=\"bib31\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2007</a>). For system 22, no counterimage is found at or near the position predicted by the solution (bottom right).</p></div></div><div content-id=\"fig22\" class=\"fig fig-modal reveal-modal\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 22.</div><div class=\"graphic-wrap\"><img class=\"content-image\" src=\"https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/m_stu2064fig22.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&amp;Signature=o9-jJl7fwRa75ZFhzb2FdnhrXH97cbs01ts9asGNOP3unxuBLtMUR0rUeejjomxRUOYxFQSAy1G-g0kK~seTTkvxvzQ2xB5imBSgyJeXHzFFJzhjtAonhMK-M6RlZD2e-rPz4AgAitYGRrAkNxWsRerJqFoe6Em~eb31SMjqP~Xeu2Qbf96~XdeSRwCMDgzDVtMITEC60c8~jE7Vev-xtzIb3ZXSulOfgH6~oASFYDPMir9vXBhTcu0DQWfq7ORp4NJJl19quToAYReztu-nADBduiGV-OUYw--cnbr2-CEKyFfkZH~ysL9X7fCTvgQ-J7m7y0r4zqXmRHx~wmSAyw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA\" alt=\"Predicted positions for systems 12 (left) and 22 (right). The observed positions are shown as white crosses and the prediction positions in dark grey. The smaller black crosses correspond to the deprojected observed positions. For system 12, the solution correctly predicts an arclet (on the right-hand side) identified by Limousin et\u00a0al. (2007). For system 22, no counterimage is found at or near the position predicted by the solution (bottom right).\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig22.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026396/stu2064fig22.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig22.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026396\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig22.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&Signature=Sers5rjimDmONX5HDvLCu2mCsRMHk1-IA3Wdl0PhSBts7FVxoj7of1DRyzZ09UFHtwNLeEdetAo9QP2b4~WuZa-Ktlc~kW3IN5demRVmF-0k8L6rB4Ef4Wdkyld3awYSYk7~YloOQblCGQ9WUX130xPM5sIrAZa2IfgcZ7-EMPdUc68GSZhBLqB6fw8bBVaCX0gHtOhoF-O9kxkKRQxcrUi7Lj1KcROTTXYXSPEH16YqKzpDbk9yCgFss23du~TQicmyKFnSw0bsTmSWXoqr36fX3ccxugDo7UhPGC-3uFGjOlvWtTMIoeuYu2EtWgiyjX6Fcv1EtSzwmyazcEQ5KQ__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026396&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig22.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">Predicted positions for systems 12 (left) and 22 (right). The observed positions are shown as white crosses and the prediction positions in dark grey. The smaller black crosses correspond to the deprojected observed positions. For system 12, the solution correctly predicts an arclet (on the right-hand side) identified by Limousin et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib31\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib31\" data-open=\"bib31\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2007</a>). For system 22, no counterimage is found at or near the position predicted by the solution (bottom right).</p></div></div><p class=\"chapter-para\">We show the interesting cases for systems 12 and 22. In system 12, we observe that the model predicts a new image on the right-hand side of the field of view. Exploring this position in the original ACS image, the alleged new image is easily identified about 10\u2009arcsec north of the predicted position. Given the fact that this is near a critical curve, 10\u2009arcsec are actually a relatively short distance along a critical curve. That new image was already correctly identified by Limousin et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib31\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib31\" data-open=\"bib31\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2007</a>). On the other hand, system 22 shows a clear prediction that is missing from our data set (and others in the literature).</p><p class=\"chapter-para\">ACS data shows nothing that resembles this bright and distinctive source indicating that this is either a region that is near the regime where multiple sources merge and disappear (as suggested by the fact that by moving the source position a few arcseconds the predicted image disappears) or, maybe more likely, that the mass model is not very well constrained in this part of the lens plane.</p><p class=\"chapter-para\">From our reference model, we have also identified a set of 11 new system candidates never published before. These new system candidates are listed in Table\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-tbl2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"tbl2\" data-open=\"tbl2\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">A1</a> (in the appendix) with IDs ranging from 51 to 61. For most of these systems, we have assumed a redshift of <em>z</em>\u00a0=\u00a02. The stamps for the arclets in the new system candidates are shown in Figs\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig24\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig24\" data-open=\"fig24\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">A1</a> and\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig25\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig25\" data-open=\"fig25\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">A2</a> (also in the appendix). The full collection of stamps for the arclets in Table\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-tbl2\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"tbl2\" data-open=\"tbl2\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">A1</a> can be found online at this website.<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fn7\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fn7\" data-open=\"fn7\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-fn js-xref-fn\"><sup>7</sup></a></p>                    <h2 scrollto-destination=21026400 id=\"21026400\" class=\"section-title js-splitscreen-section-title\" data-legacy-id=sec9>9 CONCLUSIONS</h2>\r\n<p class=\"chapter-para\">We present a robust estimation of the DM distribution in the cluster A1689. We explore the range of variability of the solutions and identify a region of minimum variance where the solution is stable against changes in the configuration of the data set, the number of iterations, the grid resolution and, assumptions made on the fiducial deflection field. We also identify regions where the results should be taken with more caution. Our solution can be used to identify additional strongly lensed systems. We identify 11 new systems (candidates) and confirm some of the previous identifications like including the contentious system number 12 where our solution correctly predicts the fourth arclet identified in Limousin et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib31\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib31\" data-open=\"bib31\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2007</a>).</p><p class=\"chapter-para\">Even though the WL measurements have a typical sampling scale of 1\u2009arcmin, through the combination of the SL and WL data sets in the same minimization algorithm, we manage to improve upon this resolution beyond the Einstein radius and be sensitive to smaller scales (than the ones available to WL analysis). This allows us to resolve details unseen before in the DM distribution around and beyond the Einstein radius, some of which have no obvious correlation with the luminous matter. At larger radii (<em>r</em>\u00a0&gt;\u00a02\u00a0arcmin), the sensitivity to smaller details weakens as the SL data set loses its capability to constrain the matter distribution at these distances.</p><p class=\"chapter-para\">A consequence of knowing the mass distribution of a lens is that it makes it possible to make predictions that can be used in other observations. For instance, we can derive redshifts for sources with unknown redshift by projecting the system back at different redshifts and finding the redshift at which the system <em>come into focus</em>. Fig.\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-fig23\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"fig23\" data-open=\"fig23\" class=\"link link-reveal link-table xref-fig\">23</a> is an example for two of the photometric redshift systems in our sample. For these sources, the lens predicts lower redshifts than the photo-<em>z</em> although the predicted redshift is still consistent with the photo-<em>z</em>.</p>                        <a id=\"21026404\" scrollto-destination=\"21026404\"></a>\r\n<div data-id=\"fig23\" class=\"fig fig-section js-fig-section\"><div class=\"label fig-label\">Figure 23.</div><div alt=\"Gravitational lensing redshift prediction for systems 8 (dotted) and 9 (dashed) from our reference model.\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig23.tiff\" /><div class=\"fig-orig original-slide\"><a class=\"fig-view-orig js-view-large openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"/view-large/figure/21026404/stu2064fig23.tiff\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig23.tiff\" target=\"_blank\">Open in new tab</a><a data-section=\"21026404\" href=\"/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/446/1/10.1093/mnras/stu2064/2/stu2064fig23.jpeg?Expires=1639265419&Signature=wZn22TjB~Eo~S~wyhu3YqEi29jepyCowwZEDgJP9eDoXLKmwMtsqhUfth2QVt9-Ttudgg05Zp9WVip747guBQn7YSEiWtXvKv5fgQCSigrokTATU83W3Le5O8jEKE3bYSbjM0LctHDk-QLlsGMjswI21sYNBUfwndrvSmu8WobmFa21OS68faJSwTu5nl8xl~NGF9QEG4bhrMzlAnu533unN8TyZtqWVowfzhsms5tdbtTSYaWXULoo0jp4VhR0-YBpWx6JZs01IbFoLbWx1YLPnxjvLJmxCgjicmR0-rgh9g~-GQ-T9E3niNicuqdTgZmWdeby2I3XIA1a-JIhlJA__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=21026404&ar=1317500&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326\" class=\"download-slide\" data-path-from-xml=\"stu2064fig23.tiff\">Download slide</a></div></div><div class=\"caption fig-caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">Gravitational lensing redshift prediction for systems 8 (dotted) and 9 (dashed) from our reference model.</p></div></div><p class=\"chapter-para\">The mass model can be also used to impose constraints on the cosmological model, for instance through the <em>f</em><sub><em>k</em></sub> function as shown in Section\u00a0<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-sec6\"></span><a href=\"#sec6\" class=\"sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec\">6</a> although we also show that in order to get competitive constraints, one should probably rely on stacking results from multiple clusters.</p><p class=\"chapter-para\">Finally, our free-form model allows us to determine the mass-to-light ratio of the main galaxies in the cluster. We find ratios that are generally consistent with earlier results found in the literature. However, with the exception of the central galaxy, the galaxies in our model assume the same <em>M</em>/<em>L</em><sub><em>B</em></sub> ratio limiting somehow the power of our study. A more detailed study where member galaxies are allowed to take on individual <em>M</em>/<em>L</em><sub><em>B</em></sub> ratios will be considered in a future work.</p><p class=\"chapter-para\">The authors would like to thank the referee, Eric Jullo, for very useful comments and suggestions that have helped improved this paper substantially. JMD acknowledges support of the consolider project CAD2010-00064 and AYA2012-39475-C02-01 funded by the Ministerio de Economia y Competitividad. JMD also acknowledges the hospitality of the Department of Physics and Astronomy at UPenn during part of this research. KU acknowledges partial support from the National Science Council of Taiwan (grant NSC100-2112-M-001-008-MY3). MS acknowledges financial support from the agreement ASI/INAF/023/12/0. NB and TB acknowledge support of the grants AYA2010- 22111-C03-01 funded by the Ministerio de Econom\u00eda y Competitividad and PEX/10-CFQM-6444 of the Junta de Andaluc\u00eda.</p><div through a high-pass filter.</p></div></div>                        <a id=\"21026423\" scrollto-destination=\"21026423\"></a>\r\n<div content-id=\"tbl2\" class=\"table-modal table-full-width-wrap\"><div class=\"table-wrap table-wide\"><div class=\"table-wrap-title\" id=\"tbl2\" data-id=\"tbl2\"><span class=\"label\">Table A1.</span><div class=\"caption\"><p class=\"chapter-para\">SL data set. The second column shows the new system ID following the original notation of Broadhurst et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib7\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib7\" data-open=\"bib7\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005b</a>). The third column shows the original notation (Broadhurst et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib7\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib7\" data-open=\"bib7\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005b</a>). Systems not present in the original paper are left blank in this column. The fourth column indicates previous papers in the literature where that system was identified, B05 is for Broadhurst et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib7\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib7\" data-open=\"bib7\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005b</a>), L07 for Limousin et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib31\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib31\" data-open=\"bib31\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2007</a>), C10 for Coe et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib11\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib11\" data-open=\"bib11\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2010</a>) and D14 for this paper. Fifth and sixths columns show the coordinates of each arclet. Discrepancies with some of the positions published in Coe et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib11\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib11\" data-open=\"bib11\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2010</a>) are corrected in the present version of the table. Column 7 includes the redshifts used in our study and are taken from Coe et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib11\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib11\" data-open=\"bib11\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2010</a>). A negative sign in this column indicates that they are photo-<em>z</em>. New systems in this work are all assumed to have <em>z</em>\u00a0=\u00a02. Column number 8 shows the \u0394\u03b2 derived from our reference model (in arcseconds), see equation (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-equ5\"></span><a href=\"#equ5\" class=\"sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec\">5</a>). The last column shows the distance between the observed and predicted positions, \u0394\u03b8, derived from our reference model (in arcseconds). Cut-outs from these images together with additional information like the magnitudes of the new systems can be found on this website <a class=\"link link-uri openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"http://max.ifca.unican.es/diego/FigsA1689/\" target=\"_blank\">http://max.ifca.unican.es/diego/FigsA1689/</a>. Also on the same website, there is a file with useful comments from the referee based on a comparison between our solution and the model of Limousin et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib31\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib31\" data-open=\"bib31\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2007</a>).</p></div> </div><div class=\"table-overflow\"><table><thead><tr><th><em>i</em><span aria-hidden=\"true\" style=\"display: none;\">\r\n            .\u00a0</span></th><th>ID<span aria-hidden=\"true\" style=\"display: none;\">\r\n            .\u00a0</span></th><th>B05<span aria-hidden=\"true\" style=\"display: none;\">\r\n            .\u00a0</span></th><th>REF<span aria-hidden=\"true\" style=\"display: none;\">\r\n            .\u00a0</span></th><th>RAJ2000(h:m:s)<span aria-hidden=\"true\" style=\"display: none;\">\r\n            .\u00a0</span></th><th>DECJ2000(d:m:s)<span aria-hidden=\"true\" style=\"display: The second column shows the new system ID following the original notation of Broadhurst et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib7\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib7\" data-open=\"bib7\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005b</a>). The third column shows the original notation (Broadhurst et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib7\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib7\" data-open=\"bib7\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005b</a>). Systems not present in the original paper are left blank in this column. The fourth column indicates previous papers in the literature where that system was identified, B05 is for Broadhurst et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib7\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib7\" data-open=\"bib7\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2005b</a>), L07 for Limousin et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib31\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib31\" data-open=\"bib31\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2007</a>), C10 for Coe et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib11\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib11\" data-open=\"bib11\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2010</a>) and D14 for this paper. Fifth and sixths columns show the coordinates of each arclet. Discrepancies with some of the positions published in Coe et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib11\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib11\" data-open=\"bib11\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2010</a>) are corrected in the present version of the table. Column 7 includes the redshifts used in our study and are taken from Coe et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib11\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib11\" data-open=\"bib11\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2010</a>). A negative sign in this column indicates that they are photo-<em>z</em>. New systems in this work are all assumed to have <em>z</em>\u00a0=\u00a02. Column number 8 shows the \u0394\u03b2 derived from our reference model (in arcseconds), see equation (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-equ5\"></span><a href=\"#equ5\" class=\"sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec\">5</a>). The last column shows the distance between the observed and predicted positions, \u0394\u03b8, derived from our reference model (in arcseconds). Cut-outs from these images together with additional information like the magnitudes of the new systems can be found on this website <a class=\"link link-uri openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"http://max.ifca.unican.es/diego/FigsA1689/\" target=\"_blank\">http://max.ifca.unican.es/diego/FigsA1689/</a>. Also on the same website, there is a file with useful comments from the referee based on a comparison between our solution and the model of Limousin et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib31\"></span><a href=\"javascript:;\" reveal-id=\"bib31\" data-open=\"bib31\" class=\"link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr\">2007</a>).</p></div> </div><div The second column shows the new system ID following the original notation of Broadhurst et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib7\"></span>2005b). The third column shows the original notation (Broadhurst et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib7\"></span>2005b). Systems not present in the original paper are left blank in this column. The fourth column indicates previous papers in the literature where that system was identified, B05 is for Broadhurst et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib7\"></span>2005b), L07 for Limousin et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib31\"></span>2007), C10 for Coe et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib11\"></span>2010) and D14 for this paper. Fifth and sixths columns show the coordinates of each arclet. Discrepancies with some of the positions published in Coe et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib11\"></span>2010) are corrected in the present version of the table. Column 7 includes the redshifts used in our study and are taken from Coe et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib11\"></span>2010). A negative sign in this column indicates that they are photo-<em>z</em>. New systems in this work are all assumed to have <em>z</em>\u00a0=\u00a02. Column number 8 shows the \u0394\u03b2 derived from our reference model (in arcseconds), see equation (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-equ5\"></span>5). The last column shows the distance between the observed and predicted positions, \u0394\u03b8, derived from our reference model (in arcseconds). Cut-outs from these images together with additional information like the magnitudes of the new systems can be found on this website <a class=\"link link-uri openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"http://max.ifca.unican.es/diego/FigsA1689/\" target=\"_blank\">http://max.ifca.unican.es/diego/FigsA1689/</a>. Also on the same website, there is a file with useful comments from the referee based on a comparison between our solution and the model of Limousin et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib31\"></span>2007).</p></div> </div><div class=\"table-overflow\"><table><thead><tr><th><em>i</em><span aria-hidden=\"true\" style=\"display: none;\">\r\n The second column shows the new system ID following the original notation of Broadhurst et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib7\"></span>2005b). The third column shows the original notation (Broadhurst et\u00a0al. <span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib7\"></span>2005b). Systems not present in the original paper are left blank in this column. The fourth column indicates previous papers in the literature where that system was identified, B05 is for Broadhurst et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib7\"></span>2005b), L07 for Limousin et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib31\"></span>2007), C10 for Coe et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib11\"></span>2010) and D14 for this paper. Fifth and sixths columns show the coordinates of each arclet. Discrepancies with some of the positions published in Coe et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib11\"></span>2010) are corrected in the present version of the table. Column 7 includes the redshifts used in our study and are taken from Coe et\u00a0al. (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-bib11\"></span>2010). A negative sign in this column indicates that they are photo-<em>z</em>. New systems in this work are all assumed to have <em>z</em>\u00a0=\u00a02. Column number 8 shows the \u0394\u03b2 derived from our reference model (in arcseconds), see equation (<span class=\"xrefLink\" id=\"jumplink-equ5\"></span>5). The last column shows the distance between the observed and predicted positions, \u0394\u03b8, derived from our reference model (in arcseconds). Cut-outs from these images together with additional information like the magnitudes of the new systems can be found on this website <a class=\"link link-uri openInAnotherWindow\" href=\"http://max.ifca.unican.es/diego/FigsA1689/\" target=\"_blank\">http://max.ifca.unican.es/diego/FigsA1689/</a>.
